<HEAD>
<title>Chemical weapons in former Yugoslavia</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<FONT SIZE="+1">


<h3>Source: BBC Summary of World Broadcasts</h3>

<h3>Primary Source: Yugoslav Telegraph Service news agency (TANJUG), Belgrade</h3>

<h3>Time:11:13 gmt, 20 Jun 1994</h3><p>

Zvornik-Bratunac, 20th June: All-out Muslim attacks, including the use of poisonous gases, against the Serb side in the Ozren [Bosnian Serb enclave south of Doboj, almost completely encircled by Muslim forces], Vozuca [southern part of the Ozren enclave] and Srbobran [former Donji Vakuf in western Bosnia] areas were continued, Tanjug has learned form sources in the Serb Republic Army...<p>

Muslim forces are using all available weapons in the attacks, including tanks, heavy artillery, multiple rocket launchers and shells charged with poisonous gases.<p>

On Saturday [18th June], the Serb side lodged a protest with Unprofor's command today.  Unprofor has warned again about the most serious Muslim violation of the Geneva agreement on a four-week truce from 10th June and about the use of poisonous gases banned by all valid international legal provisions.<p>

<hr>

<h3>Source: Reuters</h3>

<h3>Primary Source: United Nations</h3>

<h3>Date: 10/21/93</h3>

<h2>HEADLINE: Bosnians Said To Be Using Chemical Grenades In War</h2>

A Bosnian Muslim commander bragged to U.N. personnel in Tuzla his forces were using chemical grenades against the Bosnian Serb army, according to a report to the Security Council disclosed Thursday.<p>

But council sources, who received the report, said UNPROFOR could not confirm independently whether any chemical weapons had been used by Muslim forces or others in the Bosnian conflict.<p>

The report from the U.N. protection Force (UNPROFOR) in the former Yugoslavia said the commander of the 126th Brigade told the U.N. military observers that chemical grenades were used against Bosnian Serb forces to demonstrate "the capability" of the Bosnian government army.<p>

Croatia's U.N. mission, in a press statement, quoted its own chemical warfare experts as saying that Bosnian MUslim forces have used "sensitive narve gases, most likely chlorine," a poison used in World War I.<p>

A second UNPROFOR report to the council complained that the Bosnian army south of Tuzla had been painting military vehicles white, evidently to disguise them as U.N. transport.<p>

Serb commanders have threatned to shoot at all white vehicles and UNPROFOR has protested to the Muslim dominated army, the sources said.<P>

<hr>

<h3>Source:Reuters</h3>

<h3>Primary Source:United Nations</h3>

<h3>Date: 7/28/93</h3>

<h2>Headline: U.N. Says Non-Lethal Gas Shells Fired in Sarajevo</h2>

A U.N. spokesman said on Wednesday that shells apparently containing riot-control gas had been fired in Sarajevo, but there was no evidence any side was using poison gas in the Bosnian conflict.<P>

Barry Frewer, spokesman for the U.N. Protection force (UNPROFOR), siad U.N. military observers had seen some shells which sent up white clouds during fighting on Tuesday on Zuc hill, where the Moslem-led Bosnian army has been pounded for several days by Serb artillery.<P>

"Our UNMOs observed some shells which sent up white clouds which were assessed to be non-poison gas, probably CS (riot control) gas or something like that," Frewer told a news briefing.<P>

"We have no knowledge of the use of poisonous gases," he said.<p>

The Moslem-led Bosnian government has accused Serbs of using chemical shells in the Zuc battle and on other fronts in the republic's civil war.<p>

In Belgrade, deputy UNPROFOR chief Cedric Thornberry told a news conference the U.N. would be investigating "what was different about the shells and their contents and see who fired them."<P>

"We have learned not to jump to conclusions," Thornberry said, adding that UNPROFOR was treating the incident "very guardedly."<P>

Reuters television on Wednesday filmed what the Bosnian army alleged was an unexploded chemical shell which had landed in Kobilja Glava, a Moslem-held suburb in the north of Sarajevo.<p>

The film showed a U.N. military observer approach the 122mm shell wearingsd a gas mask in order to photograph its markings.<p>

UNPROFOR headquorters in Sarajevods said it was not immediately aware of the discovery.<P>

Earlier this month, the British government said it believed all three sides in the Bosnian civil war possessed improvised grenades containing riot-control gas but not confirm reports they had been used by Moslems against Croats.<P>

Thornberry also said Moslem-led government forces fighting to prevent Serbs widening a strategic corridor in northern Bosnia around Brcko had threatened to use chlorine gas if the Serbs did not stop using rockets.<P>

The Moslem side has threatened before to use chlorine, produced in a large industrial chemical plant in the Moslem-held north Bosnian town of Tuzla.<P>

But the U.N. has cast considerable doubts on its effectiveness as a battlefield weapon.<P>

<hr>

<h3>Source:BBC Summary of World Broadcasts</h3>

<h3>Primary Source: Yugoslav Telegraph Service news agency (TANJUG), Belgrade</h3>

<h3>Date: 12:01 gmt 10/22/93</h3>

Zvornik, 22 October: Muslim artillery units resumed their shelling of the territory of the Serbian Republic [in Bosnia-Hercegovina] some 15km northeast of Zvornik [northeastern Bosnia] shortly before 1200 [1100 gmt] today.  Tanjug's correspondent was told by the command of the Zvornik garrison of the army of the Serbian Republic that Muslim forces used shells with toxic charges in today's attacks, as well as in the course of the previous day [21st October].<p>

Serb military sources have said that, owing to yesterday's several-hour-long Muslim attack and the use of prohibited toxic weapons, a UN military observer commission has been assigned to carry out an on-the-spot investigation and collect all the necessary samples.<p>

Several dozen mortar shells of different calibres were fired from Muslim strongholds in [the villages of] Vitnica, Kovacevici, Nezuk and the hamlet of Zaseok from 0900 [0800 gmt] to 1500 [1400 gmt] yesterday [21st October].  today's attack came from the same diractions.<P>

According to the commander of the Zvornik garrison of the army of the Serbian republic, maj Vinko Pandurevic, more than 60 shells were fired in the course of yesterday's attack - at least one third of them charged with toxic substances based on chlorine....<P>

<hr>

<h3>Source:BBC Summary of World Broadcasts</h3>

<h3>Primary Source: Radio Bosnia-Hercegovina, Sarajevo</h3>

<h3>Date: 1300 gmt 29/7/93</h3>

...... Reporting from Tuzla, Salih Brkic said that "the members of the Bosnia-Hercegovina army Second Corps have continued with intense preparations for using chemical agents for defense purposes and the use of chlorine unless the criminal attacks on the free Brcko territory cease.  Since the material has been taken out to the front earlier, now the Second Corps command has sent out detailed instructions and orders.  It has been decided that if the Chetnik attacks on the free Brcko territory do not stop immediately, first only warning amounts of chlorine and other highly dangerous chemical agents will be released and then those from the large containers, each with several tonnes of such agents.  the containers are also ready.  They are positioned close to the places where they should be activated.<p>

The Second Corps command is warning the civilians in the temporarily occupied territories that, if the monstuous Chetnik attacks continue, they will be in the zone of influence of the chlorine and other chemical agents and the aggressor's leaders will be to blame.  that is why the Second Corps command is warning the civilians in the occupied regions of Brcko, Mrkvica, Loncari, Porebrice and Obudovac to evacuate promptly all the children, the old and the ill and to [words indistinct].".................<p>

<hr>

<h3>Source: The Houston Chronicle</h3>

<h3>Byline: New York Times</h3>

<h3>Date:10/31/92</h3>

<h2>HEADLINE: Bosnia Chief Threatens to Use Poison Gas Against Serbs</h2>

Teheran, Iran: The president of Bosnia-Hercegovina said Friday that his Bosnian Muslim forces have poison-gas weapons and may be forced to use them as a defensive measure against Serbian forces.......<p>

"If the current situation continues, the people of Bosnia will be forced to use poison gas to defend themselves and end the crimes committed by the Serbs, even though this may be against their true wishes."<p>

Izetbegovic did not specify how the poison gas had been obtained, but he added that his forces had the chemicals in Bosnia.............<p>

<hr>

<h3>Source:The Atlanta Journal and Constitution</h3>

<h3>Byline: By Andrew Alexander and Bob Deans Washington Bureau</h3>

<h3>Date:11/30/93</h3>

<h2>HEADLINE: Did U.S. head off chemical war in Bosnia? Fears of illegal attacks may have led to warning</h2>

Washington: U.S. officials collected enough evidence that Bosnia was on the verge of chemical warfare this summer to issue secret warnings to two of the three warring parties.<p>

The State Department learned in July that Bosnian army commanders in the field, having lost ground to rebel Serbs in the spring, were threatening to strike back with chemical weapons, according to Marshal Harris, the chief desk officer for Bosnia-Hercegovina at the time.<p>

Meanwhile, he said, U.S. officials in former areas of Yugoslavia received "credible evidence" that traces of chemical weapons had been detected in shell casings left at Serb artillery positions around Bosnia's capital, Sarajevo.<p>

Harris could not recall the types of chemicals detected in the shell casings.<P>

"We were concerned enough to send a warning to the Bosnian government... And the same warning went out to the Serbs," said Harris, who resigned in early August to protest U.S. policy in the Balkans.  He is now an aide to Rep. Frank McCloskey (D-Ind.).<P>

The State Department had no official comment on the matter.<P>

A U.S. diplomat familiar with the situation, however, recalled "escaleting concern" in July that both sides would launch cjemical weapons attacks.  he added that it was unclear what types of chemical weapons either side possessed or whether they had arsenals of sufficient size to cause widespread death and suffering.<P>

The Bosnian government and the Serb rebels waging war against it have accused each other at various times of using chemical weapons in fighting in the past 19 months.<P>

On Monday, representatives of both sides insisted they do not possess, and have never used, chemical weapons.<P>

Harris said the U.S. warning to the Muslim-led Bosnian government was issued by Victor Jackovich, U.S. ambassador to Bosnia, who cautioned that such an attack would violate the 1925 Geneva Protocol, which bans the use of mustard, chlorine and other lethal gases.<P>

Jackovich, now in Vienna, Austria, could not be reached Monday for comment.<P>

A similar diplomatic demarche was delivered to Serbian government officials, said Harris, who added that he read cables relating to the chemical weapons threat.<P>

The Serbian-dominated government of Yugoslavia, which backs Serb rebels fighting the Bosnian government, denies ever having had chemical weapons of supplying them to the Serb rebels.<P>

"It's never been available to the Serbs in Bosnia and they never used it, and there is no single evidence that they did," said Nebojsa Vujovic, press spokesman for the Yugoslav Embassy in Washington.<P>

Even before Yugoslavia split into several independent republics, the country's defense strategy relied upon conventional weapons, not chemical arms, Vujovic said.<P>

In the savage war over disputed territory across former areas of Yugoslavia, U.N. observers have occasionally looked into claims that Bosnian government forces and Serb rebels have used chemical weapons.  There have been no documented instances, however.<P>

Following heavy Serb shelling of Sarajevo in October, for instance, local television footage showed unusually thick smoke rising from a blast site, causing speculation that chemicals may have been used.<P>

U.N. observers visited the site but found no evidence of a chamical attack.<P>

Earlier this year, a Bosnian government commander in the government-held city of Tuzla threatened to deploy a chemical-based "doomsday" weapon as a last-resort defense against Serb attacks, said former State department official George Kenney, now a Balkans specialist at the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace in washington.<P>

Tuzla has one of the largest chemical factories in the Balkans, Kenney said.  although the factory isn't set up to produce weapons, it is capable of producing lethal chemicals.<P>

<hr>

<h3>Source:Agence France Presse</h3>

<h3>Primary Source: Radio Sarajevo</h3>

<h3>Date: 12/6/93</h3>

<h2>HEADLINE:2,000 Bosnian Serb shells, toxic gas hit Teocak:radio</h2>

Sarajevo. Dec. 6 (AFP) - Bosnian Serb forces used toxic gas and fired more than 2,000 shells Monday during an offensive in northeastern Bosnia, Radio Sarajevo reported.<p>

The radio said one soldier was affected by the gas in the attack on the Teocak region, near Tuzla, but it gave no further details........<P>

....In a letter to U.N. Security Council chairman Li Zhaoxing cited by Radio Sarajevo, Silajdzic called for the U.N. to enforce resolutions on Bosnia and accused the Bosnian Serbs of using chemical weapons.<P>

<hr>

<h3>Source:Agence France Presse</h3>

<h3>Primary Source: Tanjug news agency</h3>

<h3>Date:12/1/93</h3>

<h2>HEADLINE: Bosnian Serb commander charges Moslems make chemical arms</h2>

BELGRADE, Dec. 1 (AFP) - The commander of Bosnian Serb forces charged Wednesday that mainly-Moslem Bosnian government forces were making banned chamical weapons in Bosnia-Hercegovina, Tanjug news agency said.<p>

General Ratko Mladic, in a letter sent Wednesday to General Francis Briquemont, commander of the U.N. Protection Force (UNPROFOR) in Bosnia accused the Moslems of producing chemical arms in a factory in the northeastern industrial town of Tuzla.<P>

The arms included warheads filled with chlorine, he charged, according to Tanjug.<P>

The region is "under your protection" and "should have been demilitarised, under terms of agreement signed by the parties in conflict," Gen. Mladic wrote.<P>

He called on Gen. Briquemont "to undertake effective measures to dismantle these installations."<P>

Bosnian Serbs have accused the Moslems several times in the past few months of using chemical weapons in eastern Bosnia, particularly the Zvornik region.<P>

UNPROFOR military observers recently went to the region to probe the allegations but their findings have not yet been published.<P>

<hr>

<h3>Source: SRNA Review of Evening News</h3>

<h3>Date: August 25, 1995</h3>

  DOBOJ - Vojo Kostic from Petrovo died of poisoning by chemical warfare agents which the Muslims threw at the Serb village of Sizje on Mount Ozren, reports SRNA's correspondent from the Doboj hospital. A doctor at the "Sveti Apostol Luka" hospital said that the  second patient in this hospital - if there is no  additional complications - is expected to recover. Serb soldiers in the area of  Borci repelled a Muslim artillery/infantry attack from  Lukavac.<P>

