<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Vukovar, Srbi</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<FONT SIZE="+1">
<em>The following material was published by Slobodan Kljakic in December 1991 and The Museum of Applied Arts in Belgrade in the Summer of 1992</em><P>

On the eve of liberation of Vukovar, civilians, ethnic Serbs, were dragged out of cellars and shelters in which they had been hiding; they were killed in front of their homes in the very center of the town.<P>


<h2>The Statement of Milica Zvjerec, Ana Lukic's neighbor</h2>

Having been requested to say everything known about the case, the witness stated as follows:<P>
<em>I live in 47 Vinkovacka St. in a private house; when the fighting started in Borovo Naselje, I was staying in the cellar with my two daughters.  Ana Lukic lived in my neighborhood, at 37 Vinkovacka St.  She was alone in her cellar, where she sought safety and from where she was able to look after the house and feed the pigs.  her husband and four sons were not there; they had had to run away earlier.  Every other day, I took bread and water to Ana in her cellar because we were neighbors and close friends.<P>

Ana told me that way back in October 1991, she had been visited by the wife of Danijel Rehak (known as "Danika-mongol", who was also named Ana; later on she was also visited by Daniel's sister Magda.  They wanted her to work in the Vukovar hospital.  Ana told them that she was too scared to go there, because artillery shells were falling everywhere.  Several days later some ZNG members came to Ana and searched her house thoroughly.  They searched it from the cellar to the attic, allegedly looking for a radio transmitter/receiver.  Ana told me this a day later, when I brought bread and water to her.<P>

Several days later, Ana told me that her house had been searched again by ZNG members and that they had taken away all valuable items with them, including a clothes dryer, a color TV set, a music line and a bidet.<P>

I went to see Ana and saw that ZNG members had left a lot of cigarette stubs in the ashtray and that they had been drinking cognac, since a bottle was on the table.  Ana was very scared.<P>

Following this event, Ana went to Braca Durdevic local community office, which was subsequently renamed into Braca Radic, in order to complain about the ZNG members who had stolen her property.  She talked there to to Ivica Katic and a certain Bracic; they told her that her property would be returned to her.  They asked her about her husband and sons.<P>

After a while Ana was visited by the ZNG members for a third time; they requested that she start working at the hospital.  By the way, she used to work in the hospital accounts department.  She was afraid to go and said that she couldn't leave her pigs.  When ZNG told her that they would take her pigs away, she agreed to go.<P>

In the morning of 11/7/1991, my children and I moved to the "Obucara" shelter on the ground of Borovo Works.  Ana came to this shelter in the evening of the same day.  She came from a neighboring shelter, the so-called "Komerc".  She told me on that occasion, in confidence, that in the night between November 6 and 7, 1991, she had been visited in her cellar by a ZNG member.  He was tall and fair-haired and she did not know him.  She said that he had come once before alone, two days before ZNG tried to persuade her go to work and when she agreed to do so.  The mentioned ZNG member raped Ana that night; at about 2a.m. she managed to escape from the cellar to the "Komerc" shelter.  Ana was very excited, upset and she was crying.  She told me all this quietly, so that nobody in the shelter could hear us.  She said that the man who had raped her was very rough.  She didn't tell me any details about the rape, because that would have been very dangerous for both of us.  She told me not to see her or speak to her under any circumstances, because she was kept under surveillance.  She told me that after the arrival to the "Komerc" shelter she had been interrogated by Martin Sablic in person.  He was the commander of the "Komerc" shelter and was later put in charge of the "Obucara" shelter.  In the "Obucara" shelter, I was assigned to Dormitory 2 and Ana to Dormitory 4.  Ana told me that she was being followed and that, in order not to get me in trouble, we shouldn't see each other any more.  I had noticed a woman whose name was Anda; she always kept an eye on my movements; on one occasion she told me "I know that you are a Serb."<P>

On November 16 or 17 1991, I was on duty as a cleaning person in the shelter;  I was assigned to lavatory cleaning duty by Martin Sablic, who was known as "Car" (The Emperor).  On that day, when I was passing the dining room, where Martin's office was, I saw Ana Lukic and Vida Jakovljevic.  While passing next to them, I noticed that Ana was very excited and scared; she gave me a signal with her eyes not to approach her.  This made me very worried; as if I had a premonition that something would happen to the two of them.  I took a bucket of water as an excuse and made my way toward the other lavatory; I passed in front of dining room where Ana and Vida were sitting.  This happened at about 11 p.m.;  I am quite confident about the time, since I started my duty at 10p.m..  After this I never saw Ana and Vida again.<P>

In the evening of November 16 or 17 1991, I was in the shelter when a female ZNG member went from one dormitory to another, reading out loud 15 names and ordering that these people report to Martin Sablic in front of the dining room.  Having done this, she said that "anybody failing to report will get a bullet in his forehead."  On the basis of the personal names and surnames she had read, and my personal acquaintance with some of the people on the list, I concluded that all of them were Serbs.  The list included Neducic from Lusac, Jova Markov and thirteen other men.  Jova Markov's wife, Liza, was with him.  These men were taken out of the "Obucara" shelter and never came back.  I know quite well that Neducic and Jovan Markov have not been found to this day.  The woman who was reading the list was in the company of an armed man in ZNG uniform.  I don't know who he is, because he was standing further away from me and I was unable to see him well.<P>

As for Martin Sablic, I can say that he was in charge of the shelter and that nothing could be done in the shelter without his approval.  He kept a record of all people going in and out of the "Obucara" shelter.  Martin was always in the company of Nikola Cibaric, a certain Bartol, a short ZNG member from Zagorje (he always emphasized where he was from), and a tall, fair-haired ZNG member wearing a pony tail.<P>

On the day following the night when 15 men were taken away from the shelter, Jova Markov's wife asked Martin Sablic when these men would return.  I witnessed this conversation because I happened to be passing by.  Martin said that "they should come back tonight by 2a.m., but since commander Nikola was killed - murdered, I don't think they'll come back."  He was referring to Nikola Cibaric, because we had been told that Nikola Cibaric had allegedly been killed.  I have not seen Cibaric after that.<P>
...<P>

Ana Lukic wore a light-blue blouse under a long cotton sweater; on top of that she had a grey-blue track suit top.  She told me that the track suit top belonged to her son.  She wore red slippers on her feet.  That's what she wore last time I saw her;  she told me earlier that the track suit was her son's because she had been wearing it earlier as well.</em><P>

...<P> 

Completed at 1p.m. 
Milica Zvjerec was born on 1/1/1947; she was employed at Borovo Works in Borovo near Vukovar<P>
<hr>

Corpses of Jovan Markov and Uros Neducic were found in the yard of the kindergarten "Pcelica". They were killed on November 18 1991.
Ana Lukic was killed at the railway station in Borovo.  Her corpse was found next to that of Vida Jakovljevic.  They were allegedly murdered by Nikola Cibaric and Bartol Domazet on November 16 1991.

<hr>

<IMG SRC="/info/students/marko/pictures/vukovar7.gif"><P>

Uros Neducic was born in 1943.  He was tortured and slain in the "Pcelica" kindergarten yard on November 18 1991.<P>

<h2>Statement given to the investigating judge by Katica Neducic, Uros Neducic's wife</h2>

<em>...  I am Uros Neducic's wife.  During this war we resided in Vukovar, in Luzac housing estate.  In mid-October, all residents of Luzac were evacuated, allegedly for reasons of security, and moved to Borovo Naselje.  Having got there, we stayed in various shelters - cellars, and on November 18 1991 we were taken out of the shelter by guardsmen and escorted to the "Nova Obuca" shelter.  This was a big shelter containing about 7,000 people.  Uros and I were accompanied by our two daughters.  I wish to say that my husband did not take part in fighting.<P>

Between 11:30p.m. and midnight on the day of our arrival, 11-12 names were read out and all those whose names were read out, including Uros, had to report to a room, the dining room.  Uros was called out and reported as requested.  Some of the men whose names were read out were not present; only Serbs were called out.  I am a Roman Catholic, but I am openly saying that, according to the names read out, only Serbs were involved.<P>

As I have already said, we had just arrived to the shelter; there were many people; soon afterwards we were freed by members of JNA, so that I was unable to establish at that time who else was taken away together with Uros.  I can remember that in addition to Uros, Milorad Neducic and Ljuban Miscevic were also called out, although neither of them was in the shelter; I really cannot remember the names of the men who were called out and taken away subsequently; I was simply unable to take in the names of other men involved.<P>

About 2a.m., Uros and 5 or 6 men were taken out of the shelter.  As he was being escorted out of the shelter, he passed by me and told me quietly that he was being taken to the headquarters.  He took off his spectacles and took out his cigarette lighter, a pen knife and 1,500,000 dinars and put it all in my lap.  His identity card and medical card remained in his pocket.  Uros wore a blue jeans jacket lined with white fur, track suit trousers and boots; the track suit trousers were dark blue.<P>

I only clearly saw one man escorting Uros and others, although there were a few of them, I think three.  The one I saw  didn't have a uniform; he was wearing a black head band, black leather jacket, jeans and army-issue boots; he had a rather curly black hear, which was cut short.<P>

I would also like to say that in the shelter, I was with the mother of Damir Breznjak, a guardsman who treated us properly.  Damir came into the shelter after Uros was taken out and asked me where Uros was.  I told him that Uros had been taken away.  Having heard that, Damir went to the other room, the dining room, and stayed there for a short while;  afterwards he he came out angry and slammed the door behind him.  He said nothing to me, just went by cursing.  Damir could know who else was taken away.<P></em>

The witness subsequently identified the corpse of her husband Uros Neducic, from photographs.<P> 



<hr>

The members of mutually related families of Pavlovic, Pavic, Trajkovic, Toskovic and Travas were hiding in the cellar of the house owned by Milos Novakovic, at 74 Nikola Damonja St., in Borovo Naselje near Vukovar.  All were killed on November 15 or 16 1991.  When the fighters of Yugoslav Peoples Army liberated Borovo Naselje, they found the sole survivor inside the house; Milica Trajkovic, who had been wounded and remained in the cellar, lived to see the liberators.<P>

The following persons were massacred:
<ol>
<li>Nada Pavlovic
<li>Zoran Pavlovic, Nada Pavlovic's son
<LI>Zorica Pavlovic, Nada Pavlovic's daughter
<LI>Milojka Pavlovic, Nada Pavovic's mother
<LI>Teodor Toskovic, Nada Pavlovic's common-law husband
<LI>Radoslav Pavic, Zorica Pavlovic's husband
<LI>Sava Pavic, Radoslav's step-mother, killed in the cellar
<LI>Velimir Trajkovic, Milica Trajkovic's husband
<LI>Milan Travas, neighbor of the Pavlovic family
</ol><P>

<A HREF="/info/students/marko/pictures/vukovar1.gif"><IMG SRC="/home/marko/public_html/pictures/vukovar1sm.gif" WIDTH=196 HIGHT=184></a> Photo:Goran Mikic.<P>

They were all massacred in the courtyard, having been dragged out of the cellar.  Sava Pavic was killed and Milica Trajkovic was wounded in the cellar.  Teodor Toskovic was killed in the field behind the house.  Milica Trajkovic is now the sole surviving witness to these events.  According to her testimony, in addition to her, there were also eight people hiding in the cellar: her husband Velimir Trajkovic, her aunt Sava Pavic, her cousin Radoslav Pavic and the Pavlovic family: grandmother Milojka, Nada's children Zoran and Zorica, Nada's unmarried husband Teodor Toskovic and Milan Travas, a neighbor of the Pavlovic family.  On November 15 of 16 1991, the voice of an unknown man was heard from the entrance to the closed cellar asking whether there was anybody inside.  he was told that there were only civilians inside.  Then the unknown person stormed inside cursing them and made them all go outside.  The last but one was Sava Pavic, who was too scared to leave the cellar and kept saying "I'll come out in a minute, son, in a minute."  The unknown man shot her on the spot.  That was when Milica was also wounded.  As she was falling down, she managed to pull a thick quilt over her head and lay like that for several days until she was taken out of the cellar by her liberators, including her cousin Miroslav Pavic.  Miroslav helped her to get outside and carried out his dead mother, Pava.<P> 

<A HREF="/info/students/marko/pictures/vukovar2.gif"><IMG SRC="/home/marko/public_html/pictures/vukovar2sm.gif" WIDTH=183 HIGHT=152></a><P>
Zoran Pavlovic was found on November 19 1991 in the yard of the house owned by Milos Novakovic, at 74 Nikola Damonja St.  His head had been smashed with a blade of an axe. Photo: Goran Mikic<P>

<A HREF="/info/students/marko/pictures/vukovar3.gif"><IMG SRC="/home/marko/public_html/pictures/vukovar3sm.gif" HIGHT=174 WIDTH=134></a><P>
Members of the Milosevic, Novakovic and Cecavac families were killed on November 15 or 16 at the entrance to the cellar of the house at 72 Nikola Damonja St. Photo: Goran Mikic.<P> 
<ol>
<LI>Miroslav Cecavac
<LI>3-year old son of Sladana Cecavac
<LI>Sladana Cecavac, wife of Miroslav Cecavac
<LI>Ilinka Milosevic
<LI>Branimir Milosevic Milic, Ilinka's son
<LI>Ana Novakovic
</ol><P>

<A HREF="/info/students/marko/pictures/vukovar5.gif"><IMG SRC="/home/marko/public_html/pictures/vukovar5sm.gif" WIDTH=165 HIGHT=123></a><P>
3-year old son of Sladana Cecavac. Photo: Goran Mikic<P>

