<HTML>
<TITLE>Vukovar Hospital</TITLE>

<H2>Medical Testimony of the Vukovar Tragedy</h2>

<FONT SIZE="+1">Croatian Medical Journal, Zagreb 1992<P>

This publication was conceived and produced as a separate edition of the Croatian medical journal.  Like all Croatians throughout the world, we want to cherish the memory of a beautiful town of Vukovar destroyed to the last house, and the battle in which a handful of Croatian soldiers effectively neutralized the third strongest army in Europe for full three months.  As medical professionals, we also want to document honorable deeds and heroic efforts of our colleagues from Vukovar medical center.  Their stories are telling about the achievements of the Croatian medicine, at the same time leaving deep traces for the generations of medical professionals to come.  Their struggle to save human lives, not asking for nationality, religion or political beliefs, bears the greatness and solemnity of the Croatian soldiers defending our homes and our freedom.  For the homeland, the battlefield is one and the same for all.<P>

...  The preparation and printing of this publication was accomplished during the first half of December 1991.  It is a small token of our affection for Vukovar and its brave people, and thus a nonprofit issue.  We expect everybody to treat and use it with respect.  The material may be reproduced under provisions that it is not altered, and that its source is properly cited.<P>

Matko Marusic<P>

<hr>

<em>Ivanka Mihajlovic and Blanka Vagenhofer</em>, General Practitioners, Vukovar Medical Center<P>

<h3>Attacks on the Hospital - Sequence of events</h3>

The old and the new wings with inpatient wards as well as other hospital premises were directly shelled from multiple rocket launchers, mortars and tanks.  At first, particular parts of the hospital were intentionally targeted to be destroyed.  Consequences of the grenade explosions were also visible in the hospital yard, despite the fact that a large white sheet with a Red Cross in the middle was stretched over the AA-shelter after the Red Cross signs on the hospital roof had been destroyed.  The holes in the walls and broken windows were stuffed with bedsides, cardboard and plastic sheets.<P>

In the beginning, the wounded were stationed in the first-floor corridors and descended to the underpass during alarms.  Soon, they had to stay there all the time.  First floor was only used when the basement and the underpass were overcrowded.  At the beginning of October, 80 wounded were examined in a single day.  The hall of the admission room was flooded with blood - it was swept away by a broom.  On that occasion, 40 admitted wounded persons were placed in the first floor.  As grenades hit just that part of the hospital, they were quickly removed to a lower floor.  They lay in twos in beds, on the floor, under the beds...  Practically, they were hardly accessible.  The first-floor walls swayed and threatened to crush down.<P>

We were expecting the first convoy for evacuation.  It did not come.  When the second convoy arrived, the wounded were transferred in the rain to the trucks covered with tarpaulin, with styrofoam on the floor.  For as long as it was possible, lightly wounded were transferred to the ward in the <em>Borovokomerc</em> shelter, but this connection was soon cut off.  All the wounded had to stay in the hospital.  Toward the end of October, the hospital was hit by 250-kg bombs.  The building quivered, the walls swayed as on the waves, the door-posts and window sashes were thrown out.  In the ground-floor, glass from the compartment walls showered upon the patient beds in the hall.  Four sacks of glass were gathered there.  One bomb fell along the outer part of the building setting two cars on fire (one ambulance and one private car).  through broken windows of the Surgical and Internal Medicine Wards, black smoke poured out.  The patients in the ground-floor drew their infusion catethers out, cried for help, jumped, and those immobile crept out of their beds.  Another bomb pierced the loft and the ceiling of the Surgery and Internal medicine Wards, and the ground-floor, and fell unexploded on the bed, between the legs of one patient (P.V.).  The patient with an upper arm injury jumped from his bed.  Extremely astonished, a nurse asked where that oxygen bomb had come from, right onto the bed (she did not even realize at first what it actually was!).  In the Intensive Care Unit in the AA-shelter, a "strong air wave" blew the hair in our faces.  Later we saw the sky through a hole in the ground-floor ceiling.<P>

Over the last 15 days, the Hospital was daily exposed to fierce several hour ceaseless attacks.  In the AA shelter, the patient beds quivered, the boxes we set upon swayed.  During one of the attacks, the concrete fell down in front of the shelter entrance and one patient was lightly injured.  It was the only injury inflicted upon the patients during all those attacks on the hospital.<P>

Two days before the fall of Vukovar, the premises of the Police Station and the Court, that partially protected our building, were set on fire and demolished.  Now, the hospital was a plainly exposed target for the Yugoslav Federal Army (YFA) artillery from across the river Danube.  We expected them to set the hospital on fire.  the wounded were not brought in anymore.  Later we learned they had all been referred to the Borovo Naselje shelter, because all ways to the hospital were cut off.  Conditions in that shelter, however, were inadequate for proper care of the severely wounded.<P>

<em>The End</em><P>

When Vukovar fell, YFA "evacuated" 300 wounded along with some 1,000 civilians, and transferred them to Borovo Selo, a village occupied by Chetniks.  The wounded were not escorted by Red Cross members.  We know nothing about their fate.  Only one nurse has managed somehow to reach Zagreb.<P>

At that time, before the fall of Vukovar, Dr. Bosanac contacted major Mrksic, commander of the Vukovar Garrison, asking him to protect the wounded and the hospital staff from possible insults by the Chetniks.  She mentioned the possible evacuation on Sunday, at 2a.m., to us.  On November 20, 1991 the YFA officers were first to walk through the hospital door accompanied by the former hospital porter, a Serb, now in military uniform.  The hospital was surrounded by YFA soldiers who forbade anybody to get out.  They demanded all the rooms to be searched through and all arms to be given up.  They took complete medical records on all the patients, wounded and dead.  Nine YFA soldiers treated at the Hospital were immediately taken away.  Soldiers walked around with "Scorpions" lifted high in their hands.  They did not contact us nor made any comments.  They were quite correct.  We do not know how they behaved toward the wounded, because we were not allowed to contact the later.  The day passed quietly.  The next evening, the cast-makers M.M. and Z.V., who had taken photographs of the hospital, were taken away, and so was the court inspector.  They were told to give all the photo material up.<P>

The following morning, Dr. Lj.S., anesthesiologist, informed us all to gather in the cast-room at 7:30.  We, the doctors, and nurses were separated from other hospital staff.  YFA offices Veselin Sljivicanin gave a political speech, explaining that they had come to liberate us.  he acquitted Dr. Bosanac of the duty and appointed a new director.  During that time, a part of the wounded were taken out through the emergency exit.  We were not allowed to check who was left and who was transferred to the YFA barracks.<P>

We had four options: to go to Sid, to Novi Sad, to Zagreb <em>via</em> Dakovo or to stay in Vukovar.  We did not see Drs. Bosanac and Njavro anymore.  We brought only the most necessary personal things along and left the shelter with about 180 wounded.  We were crowded in buses and army transporters, and escorted by Red Cross and European Community Monitoring Mission (ECMM) members; we saw them within the hospital premises for the first time.  At that moment, we did not know that they had been forbidden by YFA to enter the hospital the day before.<P>

Patient lists with diagnoses were prepared the day before.  Seven doctors and three nurses were cut off in Borovo.  Dr. Bosanac told us she would wait for their evacuation since she could not leave them and just go.  We did not see her anymore.<P>

We left the ruins of Vukovar.  Three vehicles were lost on the way, their YFA drivers "got lost".  Later on they rejoined us.  In Bijeljina, after we had passed Sremska Mitrovica, a group of some 200 people, civilians and Chetniks (the so-called Arkan's Chetniks) waited and halted us.  The army transporters and buses stopped, we had to go out, where we were insulted, attacked, threatened, in front of YFA and local police who just stood aside and watched.  A Chetnik entered the bus and yelled at an old man that he was Arkan's Chetnik, another one recognized one of the wounded and threatened he could kill him on the spot.  These were incidents on our way back.  As advised by the EC officials, we returned to the buses.  Our ambulances and buses were stoned.  We headed for Dakovo and then for Zagreb.<P>

<h3>The Wounded</h3>

All the wounded were equally treated, regardless of their religion and nationality.  Civilians comprised two thirds of them.  Children were also wounded, the youngest patient aged 6.5 months; she was injured by a grenade.  She survived and was evacuated with us.  We also treated nine YFA soldiers.  Three of them were placed close to Dr. Bosanac's office, with special guard.  During one of the attacks, the watchmen rushed to the room together with the wounded and took those YFA members out.  Then, the outer wall of the room fell down when hit by a grenade.  These soldiers were even much better treated than the Croatian Guardsmen or civilians: they were given more food and cigarettes.<P>

One YFA soldier was all alone, without his parents and brother who had been killed in a traffic accident, and his grandmother had died during the war.  He died from gaseous gangrene, after high above the knee amputation.  He did not even wake up from anesthesia.  There were several wounded who remained paraplegic.  We believed the condition was transitory, consequential to the post-traumatic endema.  There was no overt spine injury.  Unfortunately, neither were there any signs of reinnervation.<P>

Two YFA soldiers died at the Intensive Care Unit; one from a severe head injury.  He was admitted with pulse of 40bpm, unconscious, with hopeless prognosis.  We kept him on the only respirator for 7 days.  The other mentioned above, died from gaseous gangrene.  before that he was given six bottles of blood, although the others received one bottle each, regardless of indications.  Gaseous gangrene caused three deaths, and six patients had to undergo amputation; one of then was an Orthodox priest...<P>

<hr>

<em>Ivica Matos</em>, Department of Urology, Osijek General Hospital<P>

<h3>The Fall of Vukovar</h3>

By November 19,1991, we were aware that Vukovar had fallen.  YFA entered the town, and we were told not to leave the hospital during the night.  YFA guarded the Center, both regular soldiers and Serbian irregular reservists.  Among them there was a number of our neighbors and friends of Serbian nationality.  Several members of the hospital staff were taken away that night.  The night was otherwise silent with only faraway detonations.<P>

<h3>The Evacuation</h3>

The evacuation was organized and surveilled by Serbian Red Cross only.  International Red Cross team spent an hour or two in the hospital yard in the morning.  EC mission members just observed the events.  In the morning of November 20, 1991, the medical personnel was ordered to gather in a room at 7:30.  A YFA officer announced that from now on the military rules were in order, and that Dr. Bosanac is acquitted of her function.  He gave a speech on Yugoslavia and YFA.  During that time, as we later learned, ambulant patients were taken away in buses to the YFA base.  Several members of the hospital staff and husbands of our female personnel, who came to the hospital to be with their children and wives and helped in the hospital, were also taken away.  Upon our protests, few of them were released.<P>

The remaining patients were loaded into the trucks by medical personnel.  The convoy was formed and headed for Petrijevci.  It turned later toward Negoslavci (opposite of the way that was agreed upon).  We were told that the Croatian officials do not want to receive us, and since we had wounded with us we would be headed to Sremska Mitrovica to stay overnight until negotiations were over.  The wounded were transferred to the medical unit of the local garrison.  Two of them were soon transferred to Belgrade by a helicopter because of their condition.  We slept in the busses, because we did not want to be separated.<P>

Next morning, around 11 a.m., we headed for Raca, near Bijeljina in Bosnia.  Banjski Dvori were the place of the transfer to Croatian vehicles.  The YFA left us and Bosnian police took over the control of the convoy.  I was in the front of the convoy and did not see what happened behind, where two ambulances were destroyed and wounded and personnel attacked by a group of local citizens and Chetniks.  EC delegates intervened and stopped the attack.  We felt great joy and relief when we crossed the bridge over the Sava river and finally entered the free Croatian territory.<P>

<hr>

<em>Jozo Tomic</em>, Gynecology Resident, Vukovar Medical Center<P>

<h3>Supplies</h3>

In general, the supply with medical material and food was organized and timely.  For the last 20 days, water was the main problem.  We did not have running water for two months.  Fire-fighters transported water from Borovo.  They were the target of constant attacks, so that three of them were killed and several tank lorries destroyed.  For the last 20 days, we went out during the night and collected rain water and water from wells.  The shortage of water caused sanitary problems.  We were allowed a liter and a half of water a day.  With this, I managed to wash my hair, face and body, shave and use the dirty water to wash my feet.  Washing of the clothes was almost impossible, although we tried our best.  All personnel wore white overalls and I think we succeeded in keping decent outlook.  The kitchen was attacked twice.  The food consisted of tinned meat brought in by civilians or members of the Croatian national Guard.  Several pieces of meat were accompanied by a handful of boiled rice of potatoes.  For the last ten days, when the communication with Borovo was cut off, the bread presented the main problem.  Women made bread without the yeast.  We got one and a half slice of bread per day.  The sterilization unit was attacked several times.  We would repair it and transfer it to some other part of the hospital, but YFA always learned about its new position and attacked it again.  As for the medical supplies, the main problem was the lack of antibiotics, blood and plasma.  People came in to give blood, but we could not use it because they were actually the ones who needed blood transfusions - their blood counts were abnormal after months of starvation.  We did not have enough electricity for all the freezers, so we could not make any supplies and even lost some.  The only test we could perform for the last two months was the blood cell count.<P>

<h3>Medical Staff</h3>

The total of around 300 persons worked in the hospital.  This included the personnel within other shelters that served as small medical units (Olajnica, a good shelter; Police Headquarters cellar; the <em>Universal</em> factory; <em>Borovokomerc</em> in Borovo, with more than 1000 civilians and 200 wounded).  Some 40% of the personnel were Serbs.  In their duties they were correct and loyal.  Whether they were loyal in their spare time I could not say, but there are several indications that the information leaked out of the hospital and was used for its destruction.  Whenever we made any transfer of the material, patients of equipment, the agressor's attack was aimed in that direction.  Approximately 30% of the Serbs had family members on the other side, appearing on the hospital premises in military or paramilitary uniforms.  As an example I will tell the following anecdote: for the last ten days, three YFA soldiers, including one officer, were stationed in the basement room with a nurse who took care of them only.  YFA knew they were there because one day a mortar shell flew directly into the room, hit the cement floor and destroyed parts of the floor and wall.  The room was in smoke and dust.  Luckily, the patients were not hurt.  the nurse took one patient from his bed and the other patients were taken out in the arms of nearby civilian and Croatian Guardsmen patients.  The soldiers were transferred into an undamaged room.  The next morning, we took them to the hall to other patients.  The same afternoon, a grenade of large caliber fell half meter from the outer wall and destroyed their room.  We knew that their deaths would be ascribed to us.  These three soldiers were treated with extra care: they got a pack of cigarettes per day, while our soldiers got only three cigarettes, they got extra piece of meat in their rice.  On of them fell in love with the nurse, and said he would not leave us.  On the morning when YFA entered the hospital, they were immediately taken away.  Another example: one of our patients was a retired orthodox priest, Dorde-Doka Sijakovic, whose leg had to be amputated because of gaseous gangrene.  He was a prominent citizen of Vukovar, beloved by all, regardless of their religion.  He would share one cigarette with Croatian soldiers and doctors.  After the siege, he expressed his wish to be transferred and teated in Zagreb.  I do not know what happened to him.  I could tell many stories like this, about human courage, solidarity and friendship....<P>

<hr>

<a HREF="/info/students/marko/hur.html"><IMG SRC="pictures/home.gif" ALT="HOME" HIGHT=40 WIDTH=80></a>

