<HEAD>
<TITLE> Gospic , Guardian</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="http://www.cdsp.neu.edu/home/marko/public_html/pictures/gospicback.jpg">

used without permission, for ``fair use" only
<hr>
<i>Copyright 1992 Guardian Newspapers Limited</i><p>

<h1>Croats Give an Extra Twist to the Cycle of Brutality</h1><p>

 
<h2><i> by Ian Traynor<br>  Guardian, 2/15/92, London</i></h2><p>



<hr>

<FONT SIZE="+2">Zagreb: Mile Vujnovic was found on a craggy precipice in the woods outside the town of Gospic in December, a corpse covered with stones, his legs bound with rope, his hands tied behind his back, his right fist a bloody mass, several bullet wounds in the chest.  Vujnovic, 70 when he died, had been lying there for a couple of months.  His corpse and those of his two younger companions were rotting.<p>

According to the Croatian police documents shown to the Guardian, the corpses were found on December 3.  All three men were Serbian civilians from Gospic, a town south-west of Zagreb that was split between Serbs and Croats and that is now a rubble-strewn disaster zone.<p>

The Zagreb police say a Croatian police reservist has been arrested for the murders of the trio, which they assert, goes to show that they are serious about prosecuting Croats guilty of crimes against Serbian civilians during the war.<p>

Others scoff at the notion.  Like Milorad Pupovac, a prominent Zagreb Serb, a moderate and a liberal, who is convinced that Croatian police investigations of Croatian crimes against the Serbian minority are purely politically motivated, for foreign consumption.<p>

It is meant they say, to offset the kind of criticism made in yesterday's Helsinki Watch report with its evidence of summary executions and torture of civilians.<p>

The problem with the Vujnovic case is that it appears to be just the tip of an iceberg and that a lot more than three corpses are involved<p>


Mr Pupovac says that up to 180 local Serbs have disappeared from Gospic and its surrounding villages in the past few months, mainly abducted by masked Croatian gunmen while sheltering in basements from shelling.  An earlier figure in widespread circulation is 120.<P>

The dissident Zagreb press has listed more than 60 missing Serbs.  Yesterday's Helsinki report says 29 Serbian corpses, many mutilated, have been recovered, and identified, and that many more are missing.  The weight of circumstantial and witnesses' evidence about the atrocities in Gospic is heavy.<p> 

That is why the Croatian police were ordered to investigate.  But several months after the investigation was launched, it remains inconclusive, and the police say they cannot confirm the testimony of witnesses.<p>

``I state that it is not the truth that 120 people were surrounded and killed in Gospic," says Smiljan Reljic, head of the Croatian CID.  He has been to Gospic himself to supervise the investigation.  The Helsinki Watch report, he thinks, is probably based on rumour.  The Helsinki researchers interviewed local witnesses and relatives of the victims.<p>

In a separate interview, Marijan Benko, Commander Reljic's deputy, said:``We haven't established that 120 people were abducted in Gospic.  We have records of some being missing, but nothing on that scale."<p>

One of the 29 corpses found and identified is that of Branko Stulic, a prominent Gospic Serb who was a local judge.  He ``appeared to have been stabbed in the back by a knife', the Helsinki Watch report says.<p>

As far as Mr Benko is concerned, judge Stulic is missing, but his death has not been confirmed.  And whatever happened to him, ``for sure, the Croatian side didn't do it".<p>

The Croatian CID insists it is doing everything possible to get to the bottom of the Gospic incidents, but there is a war on, it is under-staffed, and with hundreds of thousands of people homeless and many missing, the investigation faces huge obstacles.<p>

Mr Pupovac and the Serbian Democratic Forum he heads have for months been amassing and collating information on the treatment of the Serbian minority in Croatia.  Four months into the police investigation, Mr Pupovac says that not once have the Zagreb police asked him or his colleagues to help with their inquiries by, for example, providing their documented evidence.<p>

``The Gospic investigation has been going on for months and has got nowhere.  They don't intend to do anything about it," says a western diplomat in Zagreb.  ``The Croats are very sensitive on the human rights problem.  But they don't see it as a priority right now."<p>

Mr Pupovac acknowledges and deplores the atrocities committed by Serbs in Croatia, but fears an endless cycle of tit-for-tat brutality.<p>

``The Serbs in Croatia at the moment are without physical security and without the protection of the law," he says.  ``These events are the immediate responsibility of the Croatian state.  It must protect its citizens equally."<p>

President Franjo Tudjman told the Guardian he was determined to ''eliminate atrocities, even on the part of Croats.  We are fully for constitutional order."<p>

But he described the Gospic events as ``a life and death struggle imposed by Serbian extremists in Croatia," and adding a new twist to the Gospic controversy, said:``there is even a possibility that it was some agents provocateurs in order to compromise the Croatian authorities.  We know there were military intelligence agents there, as well as foreign intelligence agents involved in that particular incident."<p>

And while the police complain that they do not have enough time or resources to devote to the case in the midst of a war, the Croatian parliament and Mr Tudjman have this week been preoccupied with the rehabilitation of Cardinal Alojzije Stepinac, the head of the Croatian Catholic Church under the puppet fascist regime during the second world war.<p>

After the war, the communists sentenced the cardinal to 16 years in jail for collaboration.  He served two years.<p>

``Why has the parliament been preoccupied with Stepinac and not Gospic?" asks the Western diplomat.  ``For a long time to come, it's not going to  be comfortable to  be a Serb in this country."<p> 

<hr>


<h1>The crimes committed in Gospic</h1>

<em>Dr. Zoran Stankovic, pathologist</em><P>

From October 16 to 18, soldiers wearing camouflage uniforms and masks on their faces were abducting civilians, mostly Serbs, in Gospic and its surrounding communities, and taking them to unknown destinations.  Later on, the members of JNA and a territorial defense unit from the village of Siroka Kula found 24 mostly charred corpses at a place called Kukin Do.  Some corpses were recognized as those of people taken away from Gospic in the above mentioned period.  There were 15 men and 9 women, and 11 corpses could not be identified nor was it possible to detect injuries which had caused their death.  All of the identified persons were Serbs from Gospic, who had disappeared between October 16 to 18, 1991.<P>

Bullet wounds, lashes caused by the blade of mechanical instruments, piercing wounds caused by the point and blade of mechanical instruments and inward fractures of the skull caused by the blunt side of mechanical implements were some of the injuries identified.  In the case of 18 corpses, it was not possible to establish reliably the exact number and type of injuries, because some of their parts were missing, while the corpses were charred...<P>

<IMG SRC="/home/marko/public_html/pictures/gospic1.gif" WIDTH=393 HIGHT=324 ALIGN=BOTTOM><P><strong> On two nights between October 16 to 18 1991, 24 Serbs were slain and burned in Perusic near Gospic. <em>Photo: Mihailo Bata Jugovic</em></strong><P>

List of identified victims:<P>
<ol>
<li>U-S-2: Branko Stulic, 54 years old, District Court Judge, Gospic.<br>
The victim had been hit by at least six bullets and there was a wound on his neck which had been inflicted by the blade of a mechanical instrument.
<li>U-S-5: Stanko Smiljanic, 54 years old, jurist from Gospic.<br>
The victim had been hit by at least two bullets.
<li>U-S-7: Mira Kalanj, an economist from Gospic, mother of two sons.<br>
The victim was found to have an inward fracture of the occipital bone and fragmented (small and large pieces) parietal bone and base of skull caused by the blunt side of a mechanical instrument.<P>
<IMG SRC="/home/marko/public_html/pictures/gospic4.gif" WIDTH=351 HIGHT=484 ALIGN=TOP> <P> <STRONG>Charred corpse of Mira Kalanj. She was taken away during a raid which occured between 16 and 18 October.  <em>Photo: Mihailo Bata Jugovic</em></strong><P>
<IMG SRC="/home/marko/public_html/pictures/gospic5.gif" WIDTH=272 HIGHT=386 ALIGN=TOP><P><strong> Family photograph of Mira and Duro Kalanj with their elder son.</strong><P>
<li>U-S-11: Dane Bulj, 55 years old, office worker from Gospic<br>
the victim had been hit by at least two bullets.  On the right shoulder, there was a piercing wound inflicted by the point and blade of a mechanical instrument.
<li>U-S-12: Duro Kalanj, 52 years old, Deputy Public Prosecutor, Gospic<br>
The victim had been hit by at least nine bullets.  It was not possible to establish the exact number and type of injuries because the soft tissue of the both rumps and left thigh was missing due to the activity of rodents and the body was in the advanced stage of decomposition, frozen and mostly charred.
<li>U-S-13:  Milan Pantelic, employee of the Gospic Hydrometeorological Bureau<br>
The victim had been hit by at list one bullet.  On the head, there were two cuts with inward skull fractures on the right side of the forehead and right side of the occipital bode.  There were cuts on on his back.
<LI>U-S-15: Milos Orlovic, 49 years old, from Gospic.<br>
The back of his head had been smashed in with the blunt side of a mechanical instrument. 
<li>U-S-16: Radovan Barac, senior postal technician from Gospic<br>
The victim had been hit by five bullets.  Signs of exposure to flame were found on the head, neck and front side of both thighs.
<li>U-S-18 Ljubica Trifunovic, pensioner from Gospic<br>
The victim had been hit by three bullets.  A piercing wound inflicted with the point and a blade of a mechanical instrument was found in the occipital region of the head.  The inner side of the right upper arm was without soft tissue as the result of exposure of the corpse to rodents.  The body [as well as all of the other corpses] was in an advanced stage of decomposition, frozen and charred on the neck, chest and both hands.
<li>U-S-19: Petar Lazic, 42 years old, employee of Industrogradnja, Zagreb<br>
the victim had been hit by four bullets.
<LI>U-S-20: Borka Vranes, pensioner from Gospic, WWII partisan veteran.<br>
She had been hit by five bullets fired from a gun.  Her body was almost completely carbonized.
<li>U-S-22: Dusanka Vranes, senior nurse from Gospic<br>
the victim had been hit by at least three bullets.  A wound which had been inflicted with the blade of a mechanical instrument was found on the right side of the face. On right shoulder, a piercing wound which had been inflicted by a point of a mechanical instrument was also found.
<li>U-S-23: Nikola Gajic, 58 years old, pensioner from Gospic<br>
the victim had been hit by at least one bullet.  A cut overlaying inward fractures of the bones, which had been inflicted with the blade of a mechanical instrument, was found on the right side of his face.
 
</ol>

<h1>The statement of Marija Kljajic, wife of missing journalist Simo Kljajic</h1>

"It all began on 30 August 1991.  Many Serbs gathered and then left Gospic.  My husband and I remained.  We expected that nobody would bother us after all.  My husband disappeared on 12 October.  At 8 a.m., he went out to buy newspapers.  He brought them home and then at about 11 a.m. He went out again to by some groceries.  He was wearing a jacket and trousers.  He never returned.  That was on Saturday, 12 October 1991.  I went to our friends, the Pantelic's to make a phone call.  However, the telephone lines were out of order that day.  On 13 October, I went to the police station in order to report my husbands disappearance.  In November, I was told that 23 people had disappeared and that their whereabouts were still unknown.  On 10 November I left Gospic and went to Zagreb, via Karlobag, Crikvenica and Rijeka.  From Zagreb I went to Belgrade.<P>
My husband was a pensioner and whole Lika knew him.  He was known and respected by everyone...<P>
My husband was a Serb; I am a Croat."<P>

<IMG SRC="/home/marko/public_html/pictures/gospic3.gif" WIDTH=276 HIGHT=419 ALIGN=RIGHT><STRONG> A family photograph of Stanko Smiljanic with his mother Bosa, wife Milica and brother Milan.  Stanko Smiljanic's identity card.</strong><P>

<h1>The statement of Milica Smiljanic, wife of the slain Stanko Smiljanic</h1>

"They came to get my husband at midnight on 16 October.  They barged into the house armed to their teeth; they were wearing camouflage uniforms and green caps with holes for eyes pulled over their faces.  They found us hiding in the cellar and then they started shooting at the ceiling and shouting:'Get up, you bandits!'  I recognized one of them by his voice.  It was Irfan Matajia, a local.  They demanded from us to sign a statement which stated that the Serbs in Croatia were not endangered.  We refused to do so, because it wasn't true.  My husband and brother-in-law were then ordered to get dressed.  They tied them up and shoved them onto a truck.  I was escorted at a gun point to the house of Radovan Barac, where they demanded that I ask him to come out.  Radovan's mother came out instead.  She refused to call her son.  They took them both away.  I was visited on the same night by Luka Sulentic, who was one of the first who had been picked up by the Ustashe; he was released later once it was established that he was a Croat.  Sulentic told me that scores of Serbs had been arrested and taken by trucks to Smiljan.  I spent three months searching for my husband and brother-in-law, Milan.  Several times I addressed in person Zeljko Bolf, the chief of police in Gospic.  I begged him to find out what had happened to Stanko and Milan.  He promised to make inquiries and let me know, which he never did.  I managed to escape from Gospic thanks to a Croatian police officer who helped me get an ausweis (a pass), so that I was able to reach Zagreb, via Karlobag, Senj, Rijeka, Delnice and Karlovac.  From Zagreb, I went to Doboj, and from there to Serbia.<P>

<IMG SRC="/home/marko/public_html/pictures/gospic2.gif" WIDTH=320 HIGHT=415 ALIGN=RIGHT><strong>  Stanko Smiljanic's burned corpse.  he was taken away in a raid on 16 October 1991.<em>Photo: Mihailo Bata Jugovic</em></strong><P>

Stanko had no enemies.  He never engaged in politics; he didn't belong to a political party.  He simply wasn't interested in such things. Now I know that his only sin was his Serbian descent.  Perhaps, the fact that my mother in law was the sister of Nada Dimic, a WWII partisan hero who had been killed by the Ustashe, was one of the reasons for killing him..."<P>

List of missing Serbs, according to the testimony of Milica Smiljanic:

<ul>
<li>Stanko Smiljanic, jurist 
<li>Milan Smiljanic, his brother
<li>Rajko Barac
<LI> Danica Barac, his mother
