<TITLE>The Guardian: Serbs in Croatia</TITLE>

used without permission, for ``fair use" only
<hr>


<h1> Six Women Tremble As They See The 'Door Of Hell' Open</h1><p>

 
<h2><i>Ian Traynor<br>The Guardian , 8/9/95, London, UK</i></h2><p>

<i>Copyright 1995 Guardian Newspapers Limited</i><p>
<hr>

On the top floor of a crumbling Habsburgian tenement in the centre of Zagreb yesterday, six women spent the entire day alternately sobbing quietly, wailing in grief, and hugging the telephone.<p>

They were all Serbs, members of the Croatian capital's much diminished but still large Serb community.  All are cought up in what is already the biggest and quickest single population transfer in four years of balkan war, following the Croat seizure of the rebel Serb enclave of krajina.<p>

"We all have to go now.  There's blood on the streets and no one will help us," said Mira, a retired post office clerk, aged 65.  "Most of us will leave.  We're afraid we'll be liquidated."<p>

Anka Bunarevic, aged 75 said:"For four years we Serbs in Croatia have been living on the doorstep of hell.  The door has just opened."  Mrs Bunarevic looked every inch the stereotype of the Balkan peasant, her crumpled, wrinkled face wrapped in a black shawl.  In fact, she was one of Yugoslavia's most distinguished pathologists, is president of Zagreb's Serb Orthodox Council and has spent more than half a contury not working the fields, but living in this city.<p>

"This is a tragedy for Serbs.  But it is also a tragedy for Croats and for the many mixed families," said Milorad Pupovac, a moderate political leader of the Serb minority.  "It looks like it means the end of 400 years of Serb life in these territories."<P>

Before the war erupted in Croatia in 1991, about 100,000 Serbs lived in the Croatian capital.  The majority of Croatia's Serbs -400,000 of 600,000- were urbanised; many had roots and relatives in rural Krajina.  Mr Pupovac estimates that the ethnic cleansing of the past four years has left some 130,000 Serbs in Croatia's cities, 40,000 in Zagreb.<p>

Serb leaders in Zegreb tried to contact Croatia's prime minister, Nikica Valentic, to get human rights guarantees and assurances of safety for members of their community.  But the Croatian government, in triumphalizt mood, ignored them.<p>

The Serb mothers of Zagreb are enraged by Croatian government calls for Serbs to stay in Croatia.  One 40-year-old pointed to her son, aged six, and said there was no way he would grow up in a climate of harassment and discrimination.<p>

Jovanka, aged 65, was relieved her two daughters had married Croats.  "There is now a lot of assimilation.  Parents are agreeing that their kids at shcool become Catholics, and are changing their names.  Anything for an easy life.<p>

Croatian liberals said they doubted that there was an overt campaign to force Serbs to convert from their Orthodox faith to Croatian Catholicism.  But they agreed there was enormous social pressure in the fiercely nationalist climate for Serb schoolchildren to become Catholics.  Young Serb friends, they added, were changing their names.<p>

Mr Pupovac said there was no violence or large-scale harassment of Serbs in Zagreb, but the entire community was gripped by fear and panic.<p>

"If the Croatian government wants to integrate us socially and culturally, we urban Serbs will remain.  But if the situation stays as it is now, there will be a movement of Serbs from Croatia and it will be the last."<p>

Mladen Klemencic, a Croat political scientist and geographer, agreed that up to 200,000 Serbs could flee Croatia after the latest war games of the nationalist leaders in Serbia, Croatia and Bosnia.<p>

"We need to break the cycle of revenge.  We have to find a way to bring some of them back.  As many as half might come back if we offer the right conditions."<P>

But Natasha Radakovic, spokeswoman for Croatia's president Franjo Tudjman, insisted that masses of Serbs leaving Croatia were doing so of their own free will.  "If there was any ethnic cleansing, it was done by the Serbs themselves.  We did not ask anyone to leave.  On the contrary."<P>

Such emarks inspire a frenzy of shrieking and wailing in the siz Serb women.  "There will be a few Serbs left here and they'll be like animals in a zoo, exhibits for Tudjman to show Western visitors who are concerned about human rights," siad Mrs Bunarevic.<P>

the Serb exodus from Zagreb is getting under way.  One man showed up at the Orthodox church looking for his children's baptism certificates, saying he and 11 other families were heading for Serbia.  Another arrived with a list of 400 Serb families preparing to go.<p>

"Maybe we should just let these politicians have their way," said Jovanka, "divide everything up, separate, and get on with our lives."<P>
 

 
