<FONT SIZE="+1">

<h1> Muslim Mother Longs for the Return of Kidnapped Sons</h1><p>

 
<h2><i> by Vesna Peric Zimonic<br>  Inter Press Service, 10/26/93</i></h2><p>


<hr>

BELGRADE: A year has passed since Safija Catovic's two sons were abducted from a local bus on their way to work.  Nothing has been heard of them since.<p>

"My boys will surely come back one day...they haven't done anything to anyone," she says, as she waits for the return of Ramahudin aged 24 and Sabahudin aged 22.<p>

The brothers are two of 17 Muslims abducted a year ago from a bus taking workers and school children to Priboj, a town in Serbia, some 115 miles southwest from Belgrade.<p>

Priboj lies close to the curvy border between Serbia and Bosnia-Hercegovina, where civil war has raged for 18 months.  The bus route meanders between mountains and the nearby river, and passes through small stretches of Bosnian territory under the control of Bosnian Serbs.<p>

At the end of October in 1992 a group of armed men stopped the bus while it was in Bosnian territory, asked for the passengers identity papers and took away the 17 Muslims, all from the village of Sjeverin<p>

Witnesses said the armed men told the Muslims nothing would happen to them, and they would be exchanged for Bosnian Serbs.  In November there were reports that they had been executed, and others saying they were still alive.  But that was the last that has been heard of them.<p>

The bus abduction is not an isolated incident.  In February this year a train connecting Belgrade and Bar, the Montenegrin port, was stopped as it passed along a half mile stretch of track through Bosnia-Hercegovina..<p>

Some 30 men wearing camouflage and the insignia of the Bosnian Serb army boarded the train and took 23 of the male passengers away at gunpoint.<p>

Even though Dobrica Cosic, Yugoslavia's president at the time, ordered an investigation, nothing has since been heard about the case.<p>

Eight Muslims born in Serbia, five Muslims born and living in Montenegro, one Croat , two foreigners and seven Serbs born in Bosnia are still missing.<p>


The Bosnian Serb army commander Gen. Ratko Mladic denied his regulars had anything to do with the incident but admitted "some paramilitary formations could exist in the area, who respect no-one."<p>

The area where the train abductions took place was not far from where the 17 bus passengers were abducted the previous October.<p>

Better known under its Turkish name "Sandjak," the area has a significant population of Muslims of Slav origin -- 237,000 according to the April 1991 census.  Administratively, it belongs to the republic of Serbia.<p>

As a result of the abductions, Muslims living in Serbia towns and villages near the border with Bosnia-Hercegovina have begun to leave their homes and property, heading for areas where Muslims are more dominant, or for Turkey and Sweden.<p>

The Red Cross in Serbia admits that officially around 1500 Muslims have moved from the border areas or have emigrated, but others argue the total figure is far higher.<p>

Some 50 out of 200 families have left the village of Sjeverin, where the 17 Muslim men were kidnapped.  Their homes were immediately looted or repossessed by Serb "neighbors."<p>

Natasa Kandic, the executive director of the Belgrade-based Human Rights Fund, says that although people have been kidnapped since the beginning of the break up of the former Yugoslavian federation and the ensuing civil wars, but says things have now taken a turn for the worse.<p>

"Most of the early abductees were released when a certain objective has been accomplished," she said, "but the war in Bosnia saw a shift in attitudes.  Some estimates say that about 50,000 people are missing after being taken to the detention camps."<p>

At a recent conference in Belgrade on the disappearances, people told of how friends had disappeared after returning home from holidays in Croatia.  The editor of independent Belgrade-based newspaper <em>Vreme</em> was kidnapped for 38 hours in September, and never learned who his abductors were.<p>

"The era of political terrorism has begun," says journalists and long-time correspondent in Latin America, Dusan Dakovic.  "The war zones are too close, the state of law does not exist in Yugoslavia.  Anybody can do whatever he wants, without fear of being caught of punished," he adds.<p>

All in All, says Kandic, the fate of 200,00 people from all over the former Yugoslavian federation (Slovenia, Croatia, Bosnia-Hercegovina, Serbia, Montenegro and Macedonia) is unknown.<p>

They are listed as missing and no-one is coming forward to say what has happened to them.  The reason is, she says, the war and everything that war brings along with it.<p>

<hr>
</FONT>
