<TITLE>The Guardian: Brcko</TITLE>

used without permission, for ``fair use" only
<hr>


<h1> Killers Focus on a Photographer</h1><p>

 
<h2><i>Hans Moleman<br>The Guardian , 4/26/93, London, UK</i></h2><p>

<i>Copyright 1993 Guardian Newspapers Limited, de Volkskrant</i><p>
<hr>

Enough was enough.  In February after two months in a Belgrade jail, three attacks on his parents house and countless phone calls threatening that they would slit his throat just like a pig, Bojan Stojanovic fled from the terrors of Serbian nationalism.<p>

He is now living in the Netherlands, like thousands of others who have flown from the violence in former Yugoslavia.  Yet 23-year-old Stojanovic is no ordinary asylum seeker.  The young Belgrade photographer made the front page all over the world last year with pictures of Serbian policeman summarily executing a Muslim in Brcko, a small town in northern Bosnia.  The picture has just been awarded first prize in the spot news category of the World Press Photo awards, to be presented later this week in Amsterdam.<p>

The pictures date from May 1992 when the outside world still knew nothing of concentration camps, murder squads and rapes.  They were among the first to show the horrific daily practices of Serbian ethnic cleansing.  They made a huge impression and contributed to international denunciation of Serbia.  The photographs also turned the unknown, occasional Reuter freelancer into a traitor in the eyes of Serbian nationalists.  A good Serb doesn't take photos of the war crimes of his own compatriots.  He himself thinks that he is just doing his job: showing the realities of war.<P>
 
"On May 5 last year, I was on my way from Belgrade to Sarajevo.  Near Brcko we heard something was up.  When we drove into the village, we glimpsed a couple of bodies on a side street.  I grabbed my cameras and, just a bit later, a policeman and a soldier came past, pushing two handcuffed men in front of them."  When the policeman raised his gun to shoot one man, Stojanovic pointed his Nikon and pressed the shutter release with the motor drive on.  There was no time to focus.<p>

He hid the film in his sock, frightened of having his camera seized.  But the policeman and the soldier completely ignored him.  "I think they were bound up with their murdering."<p>

Stojanovic decided to deliver the pictures to Reuters in Belgrade straight away.  Just outside Brcko they saw something else: a white refrigerated van for meat transport and a military vehicle turning off the main road.  They followed and then watched as the corpses of Brcko's murdered citizens were dragged out of the van and dumped in a mass grave.<p>

"Around than, in Brcko and that area, about 3,000 Muslims were murdered," he said with huge, restless eyes.  "We were there with some soldiers and one of them, who had the nickname Adolf, had killed 600 men single-handedly.  But it is not just the Serbs who are guilty.  Everyone is killing everyone in this war."<p>

When the photos from Brcko got through to the outside world, the terror began.  Although Reuters deliberately changed his name in the photo credits, a few days later, a camera crew from Serbian television suddenly appeared in his doorstep.  His passport photo was shown on television and 10 days after the publication of his pictures, a bomb went off outside his front door.  A week later, a Kalashnikov was emptied in his direction from  a passing car.  "I wasn't there but my mother saw them coming.  She ran inside; nobody was hurt but I later counted 26 bullet holes in the wall."<p>

In September he returned to Belgrade having spent the summer working in places like Split, Dubrovnik and Sarajevo.  The police interrogated Stojanovic because in seemed very suspect that with his typically Serbian surname, he had no problems working freely in Bosnia and Croatia.  He heard a bizarre conspiracy theory.  "I was supposed to be working for the British secret service MI6.  My pictures from Brcko were just western propaganda and I had been given $20,000 to bribe the policeman to kill the prisoner."<p>

When the EC tightened sanctions against Serbia, his picture was shown again on television, juxtaposed with the summary of the EC boycott measures.  He got thousands of phone calls at home.  "We'll slaughter you like a pig, you traitor," he was told.<p>

Then he was arrested on suspicion of attempting to murder a woman he did not even know.  He was stuck in jail for two months.  "They beat me with rubber truncheons, tried to break my spirit with three weeks of solitary confinement.  A few days before I finally got out, another inmate tried to stab me with a screwdriver during the exercise break.  I didn't even know the guy.  But the guards did nothing.  I'm pretty sure they told him to attack me."<p>

When he was released in early January, he discovered that at home all his photo equipment, 4,000 negatives, his passport and other personal effects had all disappeared.  With a friend, he fled across the Bulgarian border to Sofia.<p>

"Because I didn't have a passport, I rode across the border at night on the roof of a train."  On February 16, he heard from a Reuter staffer that his picture had been chosen by the World Press Photo jury.  "I was so proud.  It is the first time a Yugoslav photographer has won the prize."<p>

A few days later, somebody threw a hand grenade at his house in Belgrade.  Bojan Stojanovic decided to ask for asylum when he came to the Netherlands at the end of February in time for the prize giving.<p>

Since de Volkstkrant ran this story, Stojanovic has been placed under Dutch police protection following his abduction by two armed Serbo-Croat speaking assailants.  He escaped by jumping from a moving car into a canal.  The Dutch journalists' union, NVJ, is now giving him financial support.<P>
 
