<TITLE>General Trifunovic</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<FONT SIZE="+2">                                             

<h1> SERBIA-CROATIA: JAILED  GENERAL  PUNISHED FOR SAVING LIVES </h1>           
                                                                                
</h2> by Branko Milinkovic, Inter Press Service , February 22, 1995</h2>                                                   

<em>Copyright 1995  Inter Press Service</em><P>
                                                                                
   BELGRADE:  A Serbian  general  who claims he defied orders to save the lives of soldiers and civilians during the 1991 Serbian-Croatian conflict has found himself condemned for his act by both his own side and the enemy.<P>                       
                                                                                
   By defying orders Serbian army  general  Vlado  Trifunovic  also says he     
spared the Croatian town of Varazdin from devastation by artillery bombardment  
by his troops and opposition forces. Despite this, both sides want him jailed.<P>  
                                                                                
    Trifunovic's  case is seen here in Belgrade as proof of the                 
Serb government's determination to bring to heel the dwindling band             
of professional soldiers who might be tempted to defy the politically motivated 
orders of the embattled regime of Slobodan Milosevic.<P>                           
                                                                                
   "The case of  General Trifunovic  is an example of how to destroy the life of
an important Serbian official in order to hide results of an imperfect policy," 
said Slobodan Vuksanovic from the Serbian opposition Democratic Party.<P>          
                                                                                
   Belgrade's military court decided in June 1992 and again one year later that 
 Trifunovic  was not guilty of defying orders and treason. However, the military
authorities insisted on a third trial. The composition of the military court was
changed for the next trial, and he was finally found guilty and sentenced to    
11 years in prison at the end of December 1994.<P>                                 
                                                                                
   Although  Trifunovic  appealed to the authorities, his sentence was upheld.  
There was an immediate protest from opposition parties, independent media, human
rights groups and legal experts against this sentence.<P>                          
                                                                                
   In 1991 Croatia seceded from the Yugoslav Federation, plunging Croatian      
forces into battle with the Serb controlled Federal Army of Yugoslavia.         
 Trifunovic's  barracks in Varazdin were besieged and attacked by the Croatian                                                                                  National Guard. He had no clear orders and was outnumbered 17 to one.<P>           
                                                                                
   He had plenty of artillery, but he knew an artillery exchange would          
inevitably result in civilian deaths and the possible destruction of the town.  
As a result after seven days of light fighting, he decided to negotiate. Using  
Croatian negotiators as hostages, he safely withdrew his soldiers to the Serbian
border.<P>                                                                         
                                                                                
   The enemy in Croatia condemned  Trifunovic  for taking Croat cease-fire      
negotiators as hostages, which they described as a war crime and a breach of the
Geneva Convention. But on arrival in Belgrade,  Trifunovic  was surprised to    
find himself accused of cowardice and treason by his own side as well.<P>          
                                                                                
   Inquiries were held, in which expert witnesses testified that  Trifunovic    
and his soldiers had little chance of survival had they continued to fight the  
Croats. With civilian deaths inevitable, the  general  argued that a safe       
retreat was the best option.<P>                                                    
                                                                                
   Belgrade independent weekly Vreme has also run several interviews with       
 Trifunovic's  troops and their families, who praised his humanity and care for 
the soldiers under his command.<P>
                                                   
 At the first two trials, the military courts agreed with this analysis. But by the third trial the government had swung public opinion against him and his "failure" to fight to the last man against overwhelming odds. <P>                  
                                                                                
    Trifunovic's  lawyer Branko Stanic said the prosecution used every          
opportunity to make the  general  a scapegoat for what was a Serbian defeat in  
Varazdin and Belgrade's overall failure to keep the old Yugoslavia together     
under its control. Stanic believes that Serbian military courts now simply      
reflect the desires of the president and top army personnel. <P>                   
                                                                                
   He cited the fact that two members of the chamber from the first trial were  
removed from the court before the second trial, and when the second trial failed
to find  Trifunovic  guilty, Djordje Dozet, president of the chamber in the     
second trial, was transferred to a lower civil court. <P>                          
                                                                                
   Meanwhile, in the run-up to the third and decisive  Trifunovic  trial, the   
media and the army's newspapers waged a concerted campaign against the          
 general.  One of the judges in the final trial was quoted in the Politika      
Ekspres as urging  Trifunovic  "to commit suicide in order to save his honor."  
He continued to hear the case despite the objections of the defense. <P>                                                                                                                   
   All the opposition parties described the hearing as a political show trial   
aimed at diverting responsibility from the Belgrade government in failing to    
prevent the break up of the federation.<P>                                         
                                                                                
   "The military found a victim in  General Trifunovic,  who was left without   
help and without clear orders," said Milorad Jovanovic from the Democratic Party
of Serbia (DSS).<P>

</FONT>
