<center>
<h2>STATEMENT NO. 34</h2>
</center>
 
Violations of human rights on the recently liberated territories
of the Republic of Croatia are still going on. We are especially
concerned about recent murders.<P>
     
The CHC has received the information relating to the murder which
took place in the evening of February 26 in the village of
Jezerce, near the Plitvice lakes where two elderly citizens were
killed - Dane Kalember, born in 1913 and Milka Kalember born in
1915. Their houses, located only 100 meters from the main road
were burnt.<P>
     
According to our information, the investigation was carried out
by the members of the Ministry Interior and the investigating
judge from Zadar. The bodies of the killed people were not
transported to the Zadar or any other hospital as prescribed by
the law, but the autopsy was carried out by the doctor
immediately at the crime scene which has lately become the common
occurrence when the citizens of the Republic of Croatia of
Serbian nationality are concerned.<P>  
     
Regardless of the fact that the members of the families were
present at the scene of the crime, and that the investigating
judge assured them that they would be able to  receive the
victim's mortal remains after the autopsy, the representatives of
the Ministry Interior have buried them themselves without the
prior knowledge and presence of the relatives.<P>
     
The Committee requests that the public be informed about the
course of the entire procedure, and that the exhumation of the
bodies of Dane and Milka Kalember be carried out, and that the
decent funeral be performed with the presence of the members of
their  families and friends. <P>
     
The CHC takes this opportunity to inform the public and all
interested parties, that the member of our Committee, father
Jovan Nikoli}, is ready and willing to help all citizens of the
orthodox faith with the burial procedures in accordance with
their religious tradition and custom.<P> 
 
Zagreb, February 28, 1996<P>
 
President CHC: Ivan Zvonimir Cicak<P>

<hr>
                                                     
<center>
<h2>STATEMENT NO. 35</h2>
</center>

        Croatian Helsinki Committee for Human Rights is informing the 
        public about the outcome of the investigating procedures relating 
        to the crime which took place in the village of Komi} near Udbine.
        In the village and the hamlet of Poljice lived 198 citizens, 
        according to the census of 1991. At the beginning of August of 1995, 
        a majority of them escaped to Bosnia and Serbia just before the 
        military operations in the region took place.  20 Serb families 
        decided to stay in their village upon hearing a speech of the 
        President of the Republic of Croatia Franjo Tu|man, directed to all 
        Serbs living in the temporary occupied territory of Croatia. 
        The village of Poljice surrended peacefully (meaning that there were 
        not any battles at the time taking place in the village of Poljice 
        during the military operation Storm). The Croatian army entered the 
        village on August 12, with two tanks and three armored vehicles and 
        a few troops of Croatian soldiers. 80% of all premises and objects 
        in the village were destroyed (mined and burnt) and cattle killed 
        between 12 and 14 hours. 7 persons were killed.<P>

        In the village of Komi} the following persons were killed:<P>
<ol>
  <li> Staka <strong>Curcic</strong>, 45 years old (killed with a bullet)
  <li> Mika <strong>Pavlica</strong>, 90 years old (invalid, burnt alive in her house)
  <li> Marija <strong>Brkljac</strong>, 75 years old (invalid, burnt alive in her house)
  <li> Sava <strong>Lavrnic</strong>, 93 years old (?)
  <li> Petar <strong>Lavrnic</strong>, 60 years old (?)
  <li> Rade <strong>Sunajko</strong>, 89 years old, (killed with a bullet)
  <li> Milka <strong>Sunajko</strong>, 86 years old, ( her corpse dissapeared)
</ol><P>
        The corpses of the old lady Save Lavrnic and her son Petar have been 
        laying until now  unburied in the yard, near their burnt house. 
        The monitors of the CHC could not discover the cause of death 
        because the bodies were found in the decomposed state. However, the 
        monitors discovered rope around the old lady's ankles by which the 
        lady's ankles have been tied until now.<P>
        The rest of the citizens of the Republic of Croatia, who were during 
        the military operation "storm" in the village, saved themselves by 
        escaping and hiding in the nearby woods and the UNCRO camp in Titova 
        Korenica. The CHC monitors have managed to collect all relevant 
        documents which would be delivered to the appropriate judicial bodies 
        for further proceedings.<P>
        The mortal remains of Sava and Petar Lavrnic were buried today at the 
        local cemetery in Komic. A member of the CHC for Human Rights, 
        Jovan <strong>Nikolic</strong>, an orthodox priest, carried out the religious and burial ceremony accompanied by his colleagues from the CHC office.<P>

  Zagreb, March 5, 1996<P>
                        
President CHC: Ivan Zvonimir Cicak<P>

<hr>


<center>
<h2>STATEMENT BY THE CROATIAN HELSINKI COMMITTEE FOR HUMAN RIGHTS</h2>
</center>
                           

     Croatian Helsinki Committee for Human Rights (CHC)
informs the public about the situation on human  rights
in  the recently liberated territories of Croatia.  The
Committee has been monitoring the events in the  region
since the military operation "Storm".<P>
     In the region of Krajina, there have been reported
various  cases  of  continuous  looting  and  abuse  of
remaining   local  residents  of  Serbian  nationality,
systematic  mining of houses and additional structures.
This  is  how,  for  example  the  village  of  Kricka,
situated near Drnis, and some other places in the area,
are  the objects of permanent mining of houses  of  the
citizens   of  the  Republic  of  Croatia  of   Serbian
nationality.  These houses were previously  looted  and
burnt.<P>
     When the Committee's representatives; Drago Pilsel
-  Vice President and Petar Mrkalj - Executive Director
together with their  associates from Split, visited the
village,  they talked to the authorities  on  different
levels  in  the  region. They took the  opportunity  to
demand  that the electricity be connected to the  house
of  Milka and Petar Cakic, in the village of Kricke no.
70, Drnis Municipality, since their house is one of the
very  rare  ones which did not have electricity.  These
citizens  of  the Republic of Croatia stayed  in  their
houses  waiting for the Croatian army to  arrive  while
their  son refused to join the paramilitary Serb forces
despite the continuous pressure and numerous calls, but
remained  to  live with his family in Split,  where  he
still lives.<P>
      After  the intervention of the representative  of
the  CHC  for  Human Rights, the family Cakic  got  the
electricity that same day. However that same night  the
unknown persons mined two stories house, built by their
children  and  situated in the vicinity and  completely
destroyed it.<P>
      It is the Committee's opinion that the mining  of
this  particular house was done in retaliation  and  in
order to prevent normalization of the situation in  the
recently  liberated territories, as a precondition  for
the   return  of  the  Croatian  citizens  of   Serbian
nationality  to  their homes. And not  only  that.  The
Committee  considers  this case to  be  an  example  of
pressure put on the remaining residents of Serbian nationality 
living  in  the  region  to  leave  the  area.  The  Committee  
reported  various incidents  of mining of houses in the entire 
recently  liberated region  of the former sectors North and South, 
assaults  against the  citizens, physical abuses, plundering, 
not only with  tacit approval of the uniformed man but with active 
involvement of the officials of the Ministry Interior in stealing 
of livestock.<P>
      The  Committee  therefore  asks  the  authorities  of  the
Republic   of   Croatia  to  energetically  stop   the   further
destruction  of  property and pressure against citizens  in  the
recently  liberated territories and to persecute and punish  the
perpetrators,  and in such a way demonstrate it  willingness  to
respect the rule of law in the Republic of Croatia.<P>

 April 1, 1996<P>
                                   Executive Director<br>
                                   Petar Mrkalj<P>

<hr>


<center>                                   
<h2>STATEMENT NO 38</h2>
</center>

       The   human  rights  situation  for  people  of   foreign
nationality  in  Croatia is unfortunately worsening.   WE  would
like  to  take  this  opportunity to inform the  public  of  the
violations of human rights in Croatia's legislature.<P>
      At the assembly held on March 21, 1996, the government  of
the Republic of Croatia confirmed a decision with respect to the
sale  of  government owned apartments that are  managed  by  the
Ministry  of  Defense(Narodne Novine, Issue No.  24,  March  26,
1996).<P>
     In point II, paragraph 1, the decision claims that:<P>
     Apartments in item 1. of this decision will be sold by the
Ministry  of  Defense  to  those people  who  moved  into  those
apartments during the period from July 24, 1991 until the day on
which  this decision was rendered, on the basis of the  exchange
of  apartments(exchange agreements or true exchanges)  from  the
former Yugoslavia and have lived in those apartments continually
until the day this decision was made, if:<P>
      <ul><li> the person is a part of the Croatian people has Croatian
citizenship;
      <li> the  person  proves that they have  tenants  rights  or
ownership   rights   with   respect  to   the   apartment   they
moved out of;
      <li>  the  person  does  not fall within the  classifications
listed under article 50a, paragraph 3. of the  law about  the sale  of apartments involving  tenant rights</ul><P>

      The  Croatian Helsinki Committee for human rights believes
that this item involves a serious violation of human rights  and
the concrete freedoms of the citizens of the Republic of Croatia
as  guaranteed  by the constitution of the Republic  of  Croatia
because the right to ownership is conditioned on citizenship and
nationality.  That kind of discriminating decision  is  contrary
to not only the Constitution of the Republic of Croatia, as well
as  to  international norms and the agreement which the Republic
of  Croatia  ratified  and  entered into.   It  is  particularly
inconsistent   with   the   Universal   Declaration   of   Human
Rights(1948),  article 17., items (1) and  (2).   The  norms  of
international democratic laws are the achievement  of  a  modern
civilization  and according to article 134. of the  Constitution
of  the Republic of Croatia legally stand above state laws,  and
analogous to that and to sub-legal acts.<P>
      With  this decision the Republic of Croatia has failed  to
respect  the  law  respecting  ownership  as  specified  in  the
European  Convention  for the protection  of  human  rights  and
freedoms(First  Protocol,  article 1.)  placing  limitations  on
citizens who fall within certain categories - those who are  not
of  Croatian nationality ad who do not have Croatian citizenship
-  acquisition  of ownership (purchase of apartments)  under  the
same conditions.<P>
      We  believe  that  it is important to  inform  about  this
flagrant  violation of the European Convention in light  of  the
fact  that the Republic of Croatia recently committed itself  to
respecting  the basic European norms as a precondition  for  its
acceptance  as  a  member of the parliament of  the  Council  of
Europe.<P>
      Therefore,  we think that it is important to remark  about
the inherent danger of this discriminating decision in light  of
the  fact  that  according to the list  of  citizens  from  1991
Croatia's  citizenship was made up of 78% Croats, 12% Serbs  and
10% others.<P>
      The  Committee  is  cautions that this  decision  embodies
nazistic elements, and therefore requires that the part  of  the
decision  which  discriminates on the basis  of  nationality  be
repealed as quickly as possible.  At the same time we demand the
resignation of those who are responsible for the passing of this
kind  of  decision in the Republic of Croatia and that  they  be
held accountable.<P>

Zagreb, April 3, 1996<P>

                                   Chairman of the CHC:<br>
                                   Ivan Zvonimir Cicak<P>

<hr>

<center>
<h2>STATEMENT NO. 39</h2>
</center>

	The Croatian Helsinki Committee for Human Rights(the  Committee  or 
 CHC ) wishes to inform the public of an unusually scandalous event which took 
place on April 13th in Karlovac.  We think that it is necessary to do so, because in 
our opinion this incident is indicative of the social climate surrounding war crimes.<P>  
	On the occasion of the Karlovac County Day celebrations, for the very first 
time, the assembly of the county council recognized the efforts and public service 
of certain of its citizens.  Mate Granic, the Vice President of the government and 
Minister of Foreign Affairs for the Republic of Croatia was declared an honorary 
citizen of the County of Karlovac.  In addition, six other citizens of the county of 
Karlovac and 23 legal entities received awards of recognition for their 
contributions.<P>
	All of the nominations for the awards were unanimously approved by the 
assembly of Karlovac s council, which happens to be composed of 40 delegates(28 
from the Croatian Democratic Union, 7 from the Croatian Social Liberal Party, 3 
from the Croatian Peasant Party, one delegate from the Croatian People s Party 
and one from the Croatian Party of Rights).<P>
	Also among the citizens who were recognized with this award was Mihajlo 
Miso Hrastov, a member of Croatia s Special Police Force and a commander of the 
Special Police Forces of the Karlovac Police Department.<P>  
	He is the policeman who, on September 21, 1991, acting as  a member of 
Croatia s Special Police Forces received an order to go to the Korana bridge near 
Rakovac in the vicinity of Karlovac in order to take charge of a group of prisoners 
who had surrendered to the Croatian forces.  These prisoners where among those 
individuals who were recruited from nearby villages by the Jugoslav National 
Army(JNA) in order to fight in the war against Croatia.  Despite the fact that these 
prisoners were disarmed and therefore posed no threat Mr. Hrastov nor to any of 
the other policemen in his group, Mr. Hrastov gunned them all down - at first with 
a  Ultimax  machine gun, and then once they had fallen down, he shot them in the 
head and other parts of their bodies from point blank range.  Afterwards, the dead; 
Jovan Sipic, Bozo Kozlina, Nebojsa Popovic, Milic Savic, Milenko Lukac, Nikola 
Babic, Vaso Bizic and Mile Peuraca were stabbed repeatedly with a knife.  Only 
two of the victims survived the massacre that took place on the Korana bridge.<P> 
	The perpetrator of the crime - Mihajlo Hrastov - was not deprived of his 
freedom, but was instead taken to the central police station on Doriceva street 
along with the other policemen and witnesses of the crime.  On the following day, 
September 22, no investigation took place.  Hrastov was reassigned to Bijelovar in 
northern Croatia, where he was a member of the elite anti-terrorist police forces of 
the Bijelovar Police Department until March 5th, 1992.  He was arrested on March 
5th, 1992, after a number of articles describing the incident appeared in various 
newspapers.  He was charged with committing crimes against humanity and 
violating international law.  Following a four day trial in the beginning of 
September 1992, the grand council of the county court of Karlovac acquitted him 
of all charges, which was received with a standing ovation from all those present in 
the courtroom.  <P>
	According to the information available to the Committee, the Supreme 
Court of the Republic of Croatia declared the county court s decision void and 
initiated the procedure for a retrial, however, despite the fact that two years have 
passed since the Supreme Court s decision was rendered, the county court has not, 
as of yet, set a date for the second trail concerning the crime that took place on the 
Korana bridge. <P> 
	Mihajlo Hrastov is currently still a commander of the Special Police 
Forces of the Karlovac Police Department.<P> 
	According to other information available to the Committee, about which 
we have already notified the Ministry of the Interior(MUP) following  Operation 
Storm , Mihajlov Hrastov was the self-proclaimed commander of the Special 
Prison in the old school in Ozalj, where citizens of the Republic of Croatia of 
Serbian nationality who had surrendered to the Croatian authorities following 
 Operation Storm  were savagely tortured. <P> 
	The  Public Recognition Award from the Karlovac County Council  
which Mihajlo Hrastov was among the first receive is not the first recognition or 
award he has received.  He was also recognized by the President of the Republic of 
Croatia, Dr. Franjo Tudman, in 1995 on the occasion of the fifth anniversary of 
Croatia s independence, according to Article 98 of the constitution of the Republic 
of Croatia and Article 2, item 1 of the law on recognitions and awards.  President 
Tudman awarded him with the Order of Nikola Subic Zrinski, for his  heroic 
behavior  during the war.  This Committee is not aware of any particular act of 
heroism, except for the two mentioned in this statement, which would deserve this 
or any other high award or recognition.<P>  
	It is worth mentioning that one of the ex-ministers of the war-time 
government warned the authorities of the Karlovac county about the possible 
repercussions that could result from the recognition of Mihajlo Hrastov.<P>  
	Immediately after having received the information about the distribution of 
awards in Karlovac, the professional staff of the CHC gathered all of the relevant 
data and forwarded it to the Chairman of the Committee who on Sunday April 14, 
1996 talked to Mate Granic, the Minister of Foreign Affairs over the telephone.  
He notified him of the implications involved in his(Granic s) receiving the 
Honorary Citizen's Award along with Mr. Hrastov's public recognition, who 
happens to be a suspected war criminal.  Minister Granic said that he did not know 
who Mihajlo Hrastov is, despite admitting to being in charge of the Karlovac 
region during the war. <P> 
	Since there has been no public reaction until today, April 16, 1996, the 
Committee feels obliged to notify the public of the inappropriateness of the 
Croatian government s behavior with respect to individuals who are suspected war 
criminals.<P>
	We are bringing this case to the public s attention, especially since this 
Committee is aware of the fact that Ivica Rajic, who is being sought by the 
international war crimes tribunal at the Hague, is currently to be found on the 
territory of the Republic of Croatia; in a room owned by the Ministry of Defense 
of the Republic of Croatia at the motel Dujlovo in Split, where he and his family 
are being put up. <P> 
	Similarly, Dario Kordic, who is also being sought by the Hague, is 
currently free and traveling without restrictions across the Republic of Croatia and 
is accompanied by a personal escort.<P>
	The Committee therefore encourages the County of Karlovac to publicly 
revoke its recognition of Mihajlo Hrastov and for the President of the Republic to 
explain exactly which heroic act on the part of Mihajlo Hrastov was worthy of 
recognition.<P>
	Similarly therefore, the Committee invites Minister Granic to share his 
thoughts with the public about this kind of recognition by the County of Karlovac.<P>

April 16, 1996<P>

On behalf of the Committee:<br>
Ivan Zvonimir Cicak <p>
<hr>

<center><h2>STATEMENT NO 40</h2></center>

	Aside from its symbolic promotion of worker s rights, 
international labor day (May 1st), has always been an occasion for the 
examination of social conditions in legitimate states and societies.<P>
	This first of May will in be the first real opportunity to point out 
the disfunctionality of the Croatian welfare state. The state has used 
the fact that it has invested vast resources in the war effort over the 
course of the last few years as an alibi to justify the violation of 
citizens basic social rights, however, as the time following the war 
grows longer the time has come to return the standards of social 
welfare to moderate levels. <P> 
	The entry of Croatia into the Council of Europe obliges the state, 
just as it does all of Croatian society, to, within the context of 
democratic integrational processes, devote all of its attention to 
economic and social rights of the citizens of Croatia, and therefore 
expedite the process of integration into the European and international 
financial leaders.<P>  
	The Croatian Helsinki Committee for Human Rights emphasizes 
the importance of making the equality of all persons a reality in every 
sphere of life, in economical, social as well as political.  This is an 
essential precondition for the recently achieved independence of 
Croatia to constitute itself permanently as a value which guarantees 
political freedom and the social well-being for all its citizens. 
	In order to promote the realization of these principles the 
Croatian Helsinki Committee requests the following:<P>
	<ol>
        <li> The cessation of attacks by the high levels of the state against 
trade unions, associations, individuals and activists because of their 
united activities as well as the cessation of their stigmatization as 
political enemies of the Republic of Croatia.
	<li> The cessation of the abuse of the state controlled media for 
the continued stigmatization of the work force, retired persons and 
other categories of socially imperiled citizens because of their justified 
requests for the reparation of the social status in society and for the 
protection of their rights.
	<li> Change in the overall relations towards requests from unions 
for the change of the irresponsible condition of their members, in the 
sense of their cooperative relationship with the state authorities, just 
as the role of the third party in the dialogue between employers and 
employees, has become at the very least, doubtful.   
	<li> Respect for the right to strike and other methods used by 
unions, societies, activists and individuals that are in accordance with 
civilized standards.
	<li> A radical change of the politics relating to privatization.  In 
particular, this is in reference to the rights that are equally shared by 
all citizens of Croatia until the year of 1990, and the protection of 
those small shareholders who s rights are often taken advantage of by 
the numerous nouveux riche and wartime profiteers who continue  to 
plunder and impoverish the majority of Croatian citizens.
     	<li> A thorough and expert revision - overseen by foreign experts - 
of all conflicted privatization procedures.
	<li> Radical cutting of public expenses squandered by the state, 
spending the money of the most impoverished class of citizens, and 
causing the pauperization of the largest portion of the population.
	<li> Developing a respect in practice all of the conditions which 
were placed on Croatia in the integration process with Europe and the 
rest of the world.  They are: the Universal Declaration of Human 
Rights(Article 23); the International Pact on Economic, Social, and 
Cultural Rights(Articles 5 and 6); the 1961 European Social Charter; 
the International Convention about the Abolition of all Forms of 
Discrimination(Article 6); the Declaration about the Abolition of all 
Discrimination against Women(Article 10).
	<li> Developing a respect in the general practice of all the 
international instruments from the International Labor Organization 
(ILO).  They are: The 1958 Convention on Discrimination at Work and 
Choice of Professions (Number 111); the 1981 Convention on the 
Advancement of Negotiations between Union Leaders and Employers 
(Number 154), the 1949 Convention on Freedom of Association and 
the Protection of the Right to Organize and the 1964 Convention on 
the Politics of Employment.</ol><P>
	The building of international standards into the Croatian legal 
system, which like the respecting of the high standards of the western-
European countries will make the following possible:<P>
       <ol>
 <li> The successful protection of individuals who in this war or in 
the previous one bore the brunt of the effort of the political liberation: 
the invalids, exiled, the families of the dead and disappeared and 
others.
	<li> The successful protection of workers who ve lost or are losing 
their jobs, as well as their families.  The majority of those people were 
victims of dishonest and illegal forms of transition in which the rights 
of workers and small stock owners were sacrificed.
	<li> A complete change of the state s politics with respect to retired 
persons, especially were paying out pensions, the various forms of 
manipulation, and in light of the equality of all retired persons with the 
same work record, previous status and other.
	<li> Radical changes in the tax system because the current system 
is preferential to the rich(the few tax brackets and low customs fees for 
luxury items  and the fact that they enjoy the lowest tax rates while 
their employees are taxed at a higher rate)
	<li> Changes in legislation with respect to serious and complete 
protection of children and families, which contrary to what is normally 
said, has not been taken care of yet(for example, the facilitating of 
buying children s  wares, appropriate financial support, adequate baby 
bonuses and paid vacation, help for sick people, invalids and others.)
	<li> Change to the current social security policy based on the 
bureaucratic concept of saving.</ol><P>  
	Because of all of that, the Croatian Helsinki Committee is 
requesting publicly that all departments of the Croatian state, the 
opposition, churches and other social assemblies, commit themselves 
to the furthering of the social standards in the interest of the 
protection of the threatened social and economic rights of the citizens 
of the Republic of Croatia. The Committee believes that this should be 
the main goal of all social groups and not by simply making 
declarations, but to attempt to promote its inclusion in daily and long 
term practice.  In that we see a precondition of the stable, democratic 
and prosperous Croatian state. Only  a true realization of such 
principles would ensure  that these declarations about the social state 
become a part of a truly valid and responsible state and social politics.<P> 
	The Committee takes this opportunity to demand that the 
Government of the Republic of Croatia finally submit detailed 
elaboration of the (short term and long term) program of the economic 
development and social politics based upon it.<P>
        Following closely various cases of human rights violations, the 
Committee came to the conclusion that if  true changes in the area of 
social rights violations do not take place, social issue of the state could 
reduce the state s independence to a mere toy in the hands of domestic 
and foreign financial power-wielders. This would undoubtedly be 
contrary to the original wish of the Croatian population, articulated 
through centuries, without which the Croatian state would not exist at 
all, and at the same time it would open new possibilities to certain 
individuals to claim people s will as their own property and personal 
merit. Besides, such a course of events would surely open new 
possibilities to strengthen and shape all kinds of authority, which lead 
to the even more radical social conflicts and open doors to the different 
kinds of dictatorship, with only one thing in common and that is fight 
against democracy and freedom.<P>

April 29, 1996<P>


For the Croatian Helsinki Committee:<br>
 Ivan Zvonimir Cicak<br>
President<p>

<hr><P>


<center><h2>ANNOUNCEMENT FROM THE CHC OFFICE</h2></center>


	CHC for Human Rights wishes to inform the public 
about the violence of the military authorities of the Republic 
of Croatia towards a Croatian citizen Niksa Violic from 
Korcula, born on December 16, 1976. Niksa Violic is a 
member of Jehova's Witnesses. He is, according to our 
Affiliate for Human Rights based in Split, currently situated 
in the former military hospital in Split in a very grave health 
condition.<P> 

  	Nikca Violic was summoned to Sinj for a compulsory  
military service. Following his arrival to the military 
barracks he gave his own written statement regarding his 
membership of Jehova's Witnesses, according to which he is 
exempt from compulsory military service, wearing of 
uniform and use of arms. Despite his objection, he was 
given his military uniform which he refused to put on. Niksa 
Violic immediately asked to be released from the detention 
and sent home. He refused to accept food as a sign of 
protest against forcible detention at the military barrack. 
The military officers threatened and verbally insulted him. 
He continued to object against compulsory military service 
for the following two days and finally on May 16, at 14.20 
he was sentenced to 4 days prison term at the Lora military 
prison in Split. In the register,  the one he refused to sign, 
there is a description of his behavior at the military barrack 
stating that he refused to associate with other soldiers, 
sleep in the common dormitory and eat with them. Because 
of his "anti-social and intolerant" behavior he was 
sentenced to prison.<P> 

	On May 16, Niksa Violic was put into solitary 
confinement in the Lora military prison. During following 
night (night between May 17 and 18), he was subjected to 
physical and psychological  harassment, which caused the 
clinical death in duration of 4 hours. He was urgently 
transferred by the ambulance car to the military hospital 
(psychiatric department) where he has been located since 
then.<P>

	On Monday, May 20, 1996, military policemen came to the hospital in 
order to take Niksa Violic to the Military Court. The doctor on duty 
energetically refused to allow it. The military police visited him again on May 
22, 1996, and requested that he sign a statement according to which he would 
certify that he was not subjected to any maltreatment. Nik{a Violi} refused to 
sign the statement. The members of the military police threatened to come 
again on Friday, May 24 and take him to the military court in Split, where the 
dates for the trial had already been set.<P>      

	The military police made serious threats, saying that there would be 
nobody there to save him and that he would be killed in case he continued to 
evade his military service. <P>
	
	We take this opportunity to warn the military and civil authorities that 
such behavior is completely unacceptable, and demand that Niksa Violic, 
because of conscientious objection to compulsory military service, be freed 
from his military service, and that he be enabled to carry on with his life 
normally and be guaranteed freedom of movement and all necessary citizens 
rights prescribed by the Constitution of the Republic of Croatia. We also 
demand that the authorities of the Republic of Croatia stop the persons who 
subjected Niksa Violic to torture and harassment (endangered his life and well-
being) from committing any further inhumane acts, and press charges against 
them. <P>

May 23, 1996<P>
							
Executive Director CHC:<br>
Petar Mrkalj<P>
<hr><P>

<center><h2>OPEN LETTER TO PRESIDENT OF THE REPUBLIC OF CROATIA
DR. FRANJO TUDjMAN</h2></center>

Dear Sir,<P> 

	a wave of forcible evictions of the citizens of Croatia is taking 
place in Croatia. This whole problem has been transformed into a 
different legal and institutional process through which flats 
continue to be appropriated. According to article 102a of the Law 
on Housing Relations, the authorities have the ability to proclaim, 
almost anybody they please, to be a public enemy of the state, 
which of course directly implies the termination of his/her tenancy 
rights. <P>
	The most interesting fact about the above mentioned 
situation is that not even a single case has been brought to trial 
nor has any criminal court procedure been carried out so far). A 
criminal procedure is essential to establish certain facts, necessary 
for the precondition to accuse a party of engaging in activities 
against the integrity and sovereignty of the Republic of Croatia. The 
Varazdin County court decision - Gz. 403/95 - 2, signed by the 
President of the Court Dubravka Vincekovic is a clear example of 
why it is deemed not necessary to conduct trial against the 
tenants. Among other things, she states that the mere fact that a 
tenant was a member of the former Yugoslav Army is in itself a 
sufficient reason to proclaim him a public enemy of the Republic of 
Croatia (article 102 a of the Law on Housing Relations). This article 
states that it is irrelevant whether the tenant belonging to the 
Yugoslav army, directly participated in military activities on the 
territory of the Republic of Croatia.   Furthermore the article states 
that "it is not necessary to prove enemy activity against the 
Republic of Croatia by the valid court judgment because it is not 
prescribed by the regulations of the above mentioned law".  The 
court papers for eviction in practice apply to the spouse. This has 
been explained by Dubravka Vincekovic: "In regards to the 
spouse...., for whom there is no evidence of wrongdoing against the 
Republic of Croatia, she gained tenancy rights through the act of 
marriage and henceforth is considered to have equal tenancy 
rights. She shares her husband's fate.  Principle of individual guilt 
has not been mentioned at all.<P> 
	Our Office has registered only 16 of such cases over the past 
few months based on the Law on Housing Relations. This number 
does not represent the total cases present today in the Republic of 
Croatia. It is CHC opinion that the established method is in fact a 
form of "cleansing" of the tenants from the remaining JNA flats.  
Most of these people are elderly citizens who remained in their flats 
during the entire war. The ones that left their flats documented 
their leave of absence by medical certificates or by other papers. 
	This whole procedure created by this Law article 102a of the 
Law on Housing Relations presents unlimited possibilities of 
manipulation and violations of Croatian citizens' rights and their 
fundamental human rights.  These same citizens are not allowed to 
buy the former JNA flats in which they have been living for years 
because they are considered to be enemies of the state but only 
when it concerns this particular issue. In all other segments of life 
they are treated as ordinary citizens and exercise normal citizens' 
rights.  There were cases of attempted forcible evictions. When they 
were not successful, the above mentioned court procedure was 
undertaken.<P> 
	Due to all these circumstances and to indifference of the 
state authorities concerning the aforementioned human rights 
violations, we have decided to bring this issue to the attention of 
the public.<P> 

Respectfully,<P>


Executive Director CHC:<br>					
				
Petar Mrkalj<P>   						 
President of CHC:<br> Ivan Zvonimir Cicak<P>

June 3, 1996<P>

