<h1>TRIAL ON A KRAJINA KILLING</h1>

<em>Split - March, 1 1996</em><P>

On February 27 and 28, in the Zupanski (County) court of Zadar,
representatives of HHO (Croatian Helsinki Committee) and DOS
(Dalmatian Committee of Solidarity), together with Otvorene Oci monitored
the trial of a man accused of murdering a Serb shortly after Operation
"Storm". Also present were members of ECMM.<P>

Zvonimir Lasan, aged twenty-two, was accused by the Republic of Croatia
of the murder, due to ethnic hatred, of Janka Cakic, aged sixty, in the village
of Zecevo (the Hamlet of Cakici, near Kistanje) on 20 August, 1995.  The
charge is based on Article 34, paragraph 2, point 4 of the Criminal Law of
the Republic of Croatia (Act against life and body -murder). Mr. Lasan was
accused of going to the village of Zecevo with two other soldiers, where  
he killed Mr. Cakic in his house.<P>

Mr. Lasan was represented by attorney Mr. Marko Marinovic. The State
prosecutor was Mr. Mate Dorcic and the Judge was the Honourable Mr.
Dubravko Krpina.<P>

During the trial evidence was heard from only three witnesses, Mr. Nikola
Rasic and Mr. Ivan Jakoljevic (who were with the accused in the village of
Zecevo) and Mrs. Lasan (mother of the accused), all of whom were called
to testify by the defense. The written statements from other witnesses were
read to the court, including that of the person who found the body. The
State prosecutor asked the court to call the absent witnesses, but after a
break on the second day, withdrew his request.<P>

Judge Krpina, conducted the trial in a professional manner, directing the
proceedings in an attempt to ascertain the sequence of events and the
motives present. However, he did not challenge the inconsistencies of the
accused or witnesses, in particular the differences in terms of arrival in the
village, purpose for being there and when they first learned of the murder.
Additionally, he did not see the necessity to call the additional witnesses
originally requested by the State prosecutor.<P>

The attorney for the defense, Mr. Marinovic, worked hard to defend his
client, re-directing the witnesses in favor of the accused and emphasizing the
lack of material evidence of the prosecution. Mr. Marinovic was only
inconsistent in his failure to react immediately to Judge Krpina's statement (at the
beginning of the trial) that at the time of the murder Mr. Lasan was no
longer a serving member of the Croatian army. However, on the second
day, he produced documentation that Mr. Lasan is still an active member of
the Croatian army, with a rank of reserve non-commissioned officer.<P>

Throughout the trial, the State prosecutor asked no questions or
clarifications from the accused or the witnesses, despite the presence of
inconsistencies and differences in their testimony and written statements.
Furthermore, in his closing statement, the State prosecutor urged the court
to take into consideration all the circumstances in favor of the accused and
give him a sentence less than the minimum 10 years, for the crime of
murder.<P>

Mr. Lasan was found guilty of murder, although not due to ethnic hatred
and sent to prison for six years, where he will also undergo medical
treatment for drug addiction. This will be finalised in five days.<P>

Local activists feel that the process of this trial and the participatory manner
of the judge and State prosecutor may set a precedent for the upcoming
trials for the Gospic and Varivode massacres. They are anxious to see
guarantees that the law of the Republic of Croatia and the agreement made
between the UN and Croatia, with regard to those people remaining in
Former sectors North and South, are upheld.<P>

<hr>

<center>
<strong>
