<HEAD>
<TITLE>Rape 5</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<FONT SIZE="+1">

<h2>Deposition Made by S.K. on 6 November 1992 at the Gynecology-Obstetrics
Clinic in Belgrade, 26 Visegradska Street</h2>

My name is S.K. I was born 11 July 1968, Nisic, municipality of Ilijas.<P>

I was captured on 26 May 1992 in the forest near my house.
I was with two other refugee girls from Visoko - J. and N.R.
We were captured by ten men in camouflage uniforms; they had
"lily" insignia on their caps.  They put us in a truck and took
us in an unknown direction.  They drove us to Breza camp.
We were detained in a basement with small windows; it was a
dirty, damp and cold place.  They raped us immediately on arrival;
groups of them raped and beat us.  I remained there for two days.<P>

I was then moved to another building, another room where there were
five women and girls: two Nadas, Rosa, Mira and Olja.  I was in that
room until our release on 15 August 1992.<P>

We were in that room almost all the time, except when we were taken
out to watch prisoners being beaten up, tortured and executed.
The torture consisted of slaughter, tearing of bodies bit by bit,
drowning in a pool which looked like a swimming pool - what else was
in it besides water, that I do not know.<P>

Prisoners were forced to hard labour and we were taken out from
our room only to watch killings and tortures, or to clean and do
the gardening.  I did not know the prisoners; they were from 
Breza, Visoko and Vares.<P>

We were repeatedly beaten and raped by scores of men;
sometimes as many as 20 of them violated me one after another.
When we fainted, they poured water on us.<P>

We did not have bath.  There was a bathroom but we were not 
allowed to have a bath or take a shower.  There was a washbasin
were we could wash our faces, and if we managed we could wash
ourselves speedily. <P> 

We were tortured simply by taking us to watch other prisoners
being tortured.  Once, they forced a father to rape his daughter 
who was about 17 years old.  They beat them but the father and
daughter refused to do what they were told.  It was only when they
pressed a knife to his throat that his daughter cried and begged
him to do so in order not to be killed.  He eventually did it 
and I do not know whether he was killed later on, but anyone
who leaves that prison is a living death.<P>

We were fed by pieces of mouldy bread or macaroni, probably 
leftovers, and a soup which was in fact slops.<P>

We, the girls and women occupying that room, could not talk to 
each other since we were never alone; there was always
someone of them with us both when we worked and when we were
in the room.<P>

They constantly mentioned the name Kula, probably an alias.
They kept asking themselves whether he would be satisfied 
with the way and how much they beat and raped us.  They
laughed as they did so. <P>

Later on, when I returned home, I heard that Kula was the
warden and that he was from Semizovici.  I never saw him.<P>

When I was freed, the five girls who were with me in the
room were also released.  Two of them committed suicide
immediately after their release and the rest of them 
left the village with their parents.  They set us free
because we were pregnanat and their purpose was to make
us pregnant.<P>

I am now horrified of confined spaces and wish to go back
home as soon as possible.<P>

Deposition recorded by:<P>

Zorica Stevic<br>
Senior Stenographer<br>
at the Federal Assembly<p>

Deposition made by:<P>

S.K.<P>

</FONT>
