<TITLE> Impact of Sanctions on Yugoslavia 2</TITLE>

used without permission, for ``fair use" only
<hr>


<h1>  Yugoslavia: Serbs Cry Out As Sanctions Cripple Health Care System</h1><p>

 
<h2><i> by Suzanne Nelson<br>  Inter Press Service, 5/19/93</i></h2><p>

<i> Copyright 1993 Inter Press Service</i><p>
<hr>

BELGRADE: The Agisevocs counted their blessings when they were told that their six-year-old son Siafet would be admitted to the Mother's and Children's Hospital in Belgrade after he was diagnosed with leukemia, an often fatal childhood disease.<p>

Then came the bad news.  there was no medication available to treat their ailing son although it could be obtained at a price.  But the cost of even the first treatment is more than the combined monthly salaries of the Agisevocs who come from the troubled south-western Serbian region of Sandzak.<p>

" I never expected this.  We have no savings because we started to build a house, and I don't know how we'll pay for the second therapy -- maybe we'll have to sell the furniture," said lawyer Nedzmija Agisevoc.  With tears in her eyes, she continued:"No matter what the reason is for sanctions, they (the U.N.) should never restrict the importation of medicines."<p>

The overall cost of the medication -- the equivalent of eight treatments -- is 10,400 German marks ($6,500), and what's more it has to be bought overseas.  The first treatment cost them approximately 1,200 German marks ($812) -- more than twice their combined monthly incomes of 600 marks ($375).<p>

" I was shocked when I heard the price," said Agisevoc, adding that her husband -- a factory worker -- had borrowed money and traveled abroad to purchase the medicine.<p>

It is the bitter pill that all Serbs are having to swallow for perhaps in no other sector has the effect of the tightened United Nations Security Council trade embargo on Yugoslavia been more painful than in the realm of health care.<p>

The sanctions, which were put in place a year ago, severely restrict the import of medicines and other health supplies, are directed against Serbia and Montenegro for lending military assistance to the Bosnian Serbs in war-torn Bosnia-Hercegovina. <p>

The effect on health care has been widespread.  At hospitals, patients are being given unscreened blood transfusions or improvised, untested drugs.  State-operated pharmacies are empty of all but the most basic supplies.<p>

At dental clinics, an increasing number of people are opting to have teeth pulled instead of fixed, and they are doing so without any anesthesia -- which costs as much as 10 marks ($6) per shot.<p>

The deterioration in health care is also acutely felt by doctors, who used to boast of having some of the best equipment and training in the developing world.  these days, many doctors pedal to and from work on bicycles retrieved from attics, and their salaries are barely enough to buy milk and bread.<p>


In the past, doctors point out, wealthy Arab leaders would reserve entire floors at the massive military hospital in Belgrade, while a number of women would also secretly fly in from the United States for discounts on facelifts.<p>

Official statistics on the number of patients who have died from causes directly related to the sanctions won't be released until next month, but government officials say the number is climbing.<p>

Psychiatric clinics, emergency wards, kidney transplant patients and malignant and cardiovascular patients are expected to show particularly high mortality rates, said Ljiljana Stojanovic, the federal assistant minister for health care.<p>

Diseases such as hepatitis and tuberculosis are also becoming more widespread among Yugoslavia's roughly 10 million residents -- an estimated 15 percent of whom are said to be undernourished.<p>

The trade embargo, which technically allows humanitarian supplies to cross the border, has in practise resulted in massive amounts of red tape, bankrupt hospitals and pirated medical supplies which disappear en route through neighboring countries.<p>

Additionally, more than 90 percent of the country's domestic drug production, which largely depends on the shipment of raw material, has come to a halt during the last three months, officials say.<p>

And officials say that to add insult to injury, international aid organizations such as UNICAF and the World Health Organization (WHO), have done virtually nothing to plead Yugoslavia's case in the world court of opinion.<p>

"I'm usually not too sharp, but I can tell you, we are not Iraq -- we're going to find a way to tell the world some of its decisions were wrong," said Stojanovic at a recent press conference.  "when all this finishes, it will be like World War II and the Jews -- the world will have something to be deeply ashamed of," she added. <p>

But Hannu Vuroi, head of the World Health Organization's office in Belgrade, argued that sanctions are designed to hurt.<p>

"Sanctions are a political matter, and we're not a political organization.  But it's a little funny that one U.N. body should be bringing sanctions, and another should try to correct the effects (of those sanctions)," said Vurio, a Finnish doctor. .<p>

In any event, Vurio said it was not the sanctions that initially triggered the demise of yugoslavia's health care sector, rather it started with the collapse of Belgrade largest trading partner, the Soviet Union.<p>

Besides, Vurio continued, WHO's humanitarian mandate for ex-yugoslavia -- approved in July 1992 -- is to focus on refugees and displaced people.<p>

WHO's first aid office was opened in Croatia -- one reason the Serbs may slight the organization, Vurio admitted.  Another reason is that only a fraction of the needed funds for Yugoslavia have been pledged by WHO's donors.<p>

"Many donors have specified that (their aid) is not for Serbia, saying 'They're the bad guys in the world'," said Vurio, adding that there are only about 10 non-governmental aid agencies active in Yugoslavia, compared to five times as many in the Bosnian city of Tuzla.<p>

But, privately, corruption is also cited as one reason Yugoslavia may not be getting as much humanitarian help as it would otherwise.<p>

An estimated 20 to 30 percent of humanitarian aid supplies -- especially costly drugs -- are 'lost" in the supply routes between warehouses, regional centres and distribution points, say international aid workers.<p>

Vurio said WHO has tried to combat the problem by driving its supplies straight to hospitals, but some drugs, especially insulin and antibiotics, "probably end up missing."<p>

"We have no figures, but some things end up, shall we say, in the wrong hands," said Vurio, whose office -- which is kept locked even during working hours -- was robbed of its telephones over the weekend.<p>

Yugoslav officials dismiss such accusations as irrelevant or smoke screens for larger issues.  "There's corruption on all three sides (in the war)," said Stojanovic, who said the issue at hand is whether refugees and Yugoslav citizens should be made to suffer collective punishment.  "I don't know of a war in history that doesn't have corruption."<p>

The debate over the morality of sanctions, especially when it comes to health issues, is likely to become increasingly heated.  But for now, suffering only appears to be bolstering intense feelings of patriotism.<p>

Miodrag Miladinovic, a middle-aged Montenegrin, said it's been two months since his 13-year-old son, Tivat, was diagnosed with leukemia.  Because he only makes 250 marks ($155) a month as an army officer, Miladinovic borrowed money from his brother-in-law in Germany to pay for leukemia treatments.<p>

But Miladinovic said he wouldn't suggest doing anything different to "appease" the world and lift U.N. sanctions.  "I wouldn't do anything more (than Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic has done) ... I would do even less," said Miladinovic.  "Certain things have to be respected.  And one of them is (that) Serbs have never allowed someone else to decide their destiny."<p>

<hr>


<h2><A NAME="help">Appeal</a> to Countrymen and All People of Good Will</h1><p>

<H1>LEND A HELPING HAND TO A FRIEND IN NEED</h1><p> 




<hr>

For almost two years now Yugoslavia has been living within an iron international blockade.<p>

Over 10 million people of different nationalities are endangered.  Out of that number 4.3 million are children and elderly and 600,000 refugees - accommodeted mainly with host femilies.<p>

Winter is at the door-step.  Due to the embargo on the import of oil, gas and spare parts for electricity generating plants, schools, hospitals, homes for the elderly and apartment buildings .. will have no heating.<P>
 
Mortality due to infectionus diseases in Yugoslavia has recorded a drastic increase (115%).  Polio has reappeared.  Nutrition of the population is 20% below the physiological minimum.  Anemia among children has increased by 50%.  The poor purchasing power, and hyper-inflation make it impossible for the population (with average monthly salaries of $15) to ensure even the minimum of food requirements (bread, milk, basic food products).<p>

There is a shortage of drugs, medical equipment and supplies, vaccines for children, surgery supplies, disinfectants, hygienic supplies, water filtering chemicals.  There is a lack of infant formulas, warm clothing and footwear.<p>

<h2>Neccessary Information on the Inport of Humanitarian Assisstance into the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia</h2><p>

1. In order to be able to deliver humanitarian assisstance to FR of Yugoslavia donors are obliged to obtain written approval of the United Nations Security Council Senctions Committee.  Requests are submitted to the competent authority of the donor country on a special form (the list of competent authorities is given on the following page).<p>

<UL>
<li>Donors usually have to wait for about two months for the Sanctions Committee to issue its approval which remains valid for three months from the data of issue
<li> Upon obtaining the above approval, transit requests, with a photostat copy of the annexed UN approval are submitted to the embassies of the countries of transit located in the donor country.
<li> When transporting goods to the FRY, it is necessary to carry the approval of the UN Sanctions Committee, approvals of the countries of transit and the specification of the goods being transported.
<li> The Sanctions Committee has approved only the following Yugoslav border crossings:
   <UL>
   <LI> With Hungary:<UL>
                      <LI> TOMPA-ROSZKE, for transportation by road
                       <LI> KELEBIA, for transportation by railway
                      </ul>
    <LI>With ROmania:<ul>
                      <LI> JIMBOLIA, road and rail transportation
                       <LI> STAMARA-MORAVICA, road and rail transportation
                       </ul>
   <LI>With Bulgaria:<ul>
                      <li>KELOTINA, road transportation
                      <li>BREGOVO, road transportation
                       <LI>DRAGOMAN, rail transportation</ul>
    <LI> With Macedonia:<UL>
                        <LI> TABANOVCE, rail and road transportation
                         <LI>BLACE, road transportation
                         <LI>VOLKOVO, rail transportation</ul>
     <LI>WIth Croatia:<UL>
                         <LI>DEBELI BRIJEG, road transportation</ul>
    </ul></ul><p>

2. All humanitarian deliveries arriving in FR Yugoslavia are exempt from customs charges, duties and road charges.<p>

3. When sending modicaments, immediately upon obtaining the approval of the UN Sanctions Committee, donors should inform in writing the Yugoslav Red Cross about the delivery and provide the drugs specification, in order that a prompt sanitary inspection at the Yugoslav border or at the reception point in Belgrade can be insured.<p>

4. Donors must make sure that supplies, especially drugs, are packed in their original packings, that they are accompanied with prescribed declarations, that the dates have not expired, that they have been properly packed for transport and classified per type in vehicles.<p>

5.  For any additional information, assistance or announcement of departure of a humanitarian shipment, donors are kindly requested to contact: <strong>FEDERAL HUMANITARIAN ASSISTANCE COORDINATING COMMITTEE, Beograd, Zmaj Jovina 21, Phone: (381-11) 638-212, 635-285, 630-499, 630-211; Fax: 381-11-636-983.</strong><P>

In order to insure quick acceptance at yugoslav border and firther transport of goods to the final destination donors are kindly requested to contact <strong> YUGOSLAV RED CROSS, Belgrade, Simina 19, Phone: (381-11) 624-189, 622-830, Fax:381-11-622-965; contact: Section for Humanitarian Assistance (Sluzba za Humanitarnu Pomoc)</strong><p> 

