<TITLE> Impact of Sanctions on Yugoslavia 1</TITLE>

used without permission, for ``fair use" only
<hr>


<h1>  Yugoslavia: Suffering Increases in Belgrade Hospitals</h1><p>

 
<h2><i> by Suzanne Nelson<br>  Inter Press Service, 11/16/93</i></h2><p>

<i> Copyright 1993 Inter Press Service</i><p>
<hr>

BELGRADE: Ranko lay propped in bed in a purple tee shirt, waiting for the nurse to finish unwrapping the bandages that bound the smooth round stump where his leg had been amputated.<p>

Two months ago, Ranko, a 27-year-old diabetic from the Montenegrin town of Pljevlja, couldn't find the $30 he needed for a month's supply of insulin. as a result, he lost his leg.<p>

Within days of his stopping insulin intake, his skin started to look different.  then gangrene set in.<p>

"I knew if I stopped taking insulin that something would happen, but o didn't know exactly what," said dark-haired Ranko, lifting his hands in an expression of despair.<p>

Ranko's story is a familiar one at Belgrade's institute of Endocrinology, Diabetes and Metabolic Disorders, where cases of gangrene have increased tenfold in the past year.<p>

Insulin has become increasingly difficult to find in Yugoslavia's  state-run pharmacies over the past two years.  Supplies in private pharmacies -- at grossly hiked prices -- are also now difficult to come by.<p>

The collapse of the economy, the strain of war, hyperinflation and United nations sanctions also mean there's little money available to buy essentials like insulin.<p>

According to the institute's director, Predrag Djordjevic, cases like Ranko's are common.  He said that he used to see gangrene only occasionally but now it is no longer rare.<p>

there are some 50,000 insulin-dependent diabetics in the Yugoslav republics of Serbia and Montenegro.  Together, they need about $30,000 worth of insulin each day.<p>

"How cheap life has become," said Djordjevic, adding that gangrene is just one of the problems facing Yugoslav doctors.  "Nothing is unbelievable to me now."<p>

The imposition of U.N. sanctions on Yugoslavia and the other former Yugoslav republics 17 months ago because of inter-ethnic warfare has had a dramatic impact on the health-care system hare.  Although medicines are not subject to sanctions, hospitals cannot afford foreign medicine, and the local drug industry is not allowed to import many raw materials.<p>

In additions, many supplies never reach Yugoslavia because of the lengthy, complicated paperwork required by the United Nations for importing medicine of hospital equipment.<p>

In the same hospital, Nevenka, a 56-year-old refugee from Mostar,serves as another example of the lack of money and medication.<p>

Nevenka suffered a stroke 20 days ago and has blood-circulation and diabetic problems.  She has no money for medication, and the hospital does not have supplies to treat her.  Nevenka thinks she will never leave the hospital alive.<p>

"We don't know what to tell patients, so we just try to talk about the future," said Alexandra Jotic, a 27-year-old intern.  "We give them education and prescriptions, but no drugs."<p>

The situations is much the same throughout Yugoslavia.  Lack of drugs, run-down or broken equipment, outdated sterilization techniques and even lack of light bulbs have plunged medical care back 30 years or more.<p>

Even in Belgrade's most modern hospitals, patients subsist on a diet of cabbages, potatoes and soup -- trundled to them by attendants who have to grope along unlit hallways.<p>

Far from turning citizens against the Yugoslav government, the frustration and anger are increasingly directed against the West.<p>

Djordjevic, who claimed to speak for some 17,000 Serbian physicians who belong to the Serbian Medical Society, said that sanctions are turning both intellectuals and ordinary people against Europe and America.<p>

"There's no milk for the babies.  Where's the connection with political problems?" he asks.  He adds that he also sees no connection between Yugoslavia's health-are and military budgets.<p>

"I could accept everything -- no gasoline, no car, no chocolate.  But I must have bread," he said.<p>

At the nearby overcrowded University Children's Hospital, pediatric surgeon Zoran Milosavljevic said that children are facing worsening odds of survival.<p>

"Doctors make experiments on rabbits, and politicians make experiments on people," he said.  "I'm not God to say this boy can live and this one will die.  I've worked in this job for 30 years, and it has never been so bad."<p>

<hr>



<h2><A NAME="help">Appeal</a> to Countrymen and All People of Good Will</h1><p>

<H1>LEND A HELPING HAND TO A FRIEND IN NEED</h1><p> 




<hr>

For almost two years now Yugoslavia has been living within an iron international blockade.<p>

Over 10 million people of different nationalities are endangered.  Out of that number 4.3 million are children and elderly and 600,000 refugees - accommodeted mainly with host femilies.<p>

Winter is at the door-step.  Due to the embargo on the import of oil, gas and spare parts for electricity generating plants, schools, hospitals, homes for the elderly and apartment buildings .. will have no heating.<P>
 
Mortality due to infectionus diseases in Yugoslavia has recorded a drastic increase (115%).  Polio has reappeared.  Nutrition of the population is 20% below the physiological minimum.  Anemia among children has increased by 50%.  The poor purchasing power, and hyper-inflation make it impossible for the population (with average monthly salaries of $15) to ensure even the minimum of food requirements (bread, milk, basic food products).<p>

There is a shortage of drugs, medical equipment and supplies, vaccines for children, surgery supplies, disinfectants, hygienic supplies, water filtering chemicals.  There is a lack of infant formulas, warm clothing and footwear.<p>

