<TITLE>Refugees Page, part 1</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="pictures/frback.jpg">

<IMG SRC="pictures/toppage.gif" ALIGN="TOP"><P> 
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>On August 4 1995 the Croatian Army started its operation "Storm" which resulted in the successful "liberation of the temporarily occupied territories".  The "liberation"  prompted the <A HREF="http://www.cdsp.neu.edu/info/students/marko/ref.html">"single largest movement of the population in the former Yugoslavia,"</a> according to the U.N., European Union and UNHCR.</FONT> <P>


<A HREF="http://www.cdsp.neu.edu/info/students/marko/ref.html"><IMG SRC="pictures/refpic2small.gif" WIDTH=194 HEIGHT=142 HSPACE=10></A>
<A HREF="refpic10.html"><IMG SRC="pictures/refpic10small.gif" WIDTH=104 HEIGHT=153 HSPACE=10></A>
<A HREF="refpic11.html"><IMG SRC="pictures/refpic11small.gif" WIDTH=97 HEIGHT=151 HSPACE=10></A><P>
<A HREF="refpic6.html"><IMG SRC="pictures/refpic7small.gif" WIDTH=106 HEIGHT=164 HSPACE=10></A>
<A HREF="refpic8.html"><IMG SRC="pictures/refpic8small.gif" WIDTH=99 HEIGHT=170 HSPACE=10></A>
<A HREF="refpic9.html"><IMG SRC="pictures/refpic9small.gif" WIDTH=145 HEIGHT=111 HSPACE=10></A>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2>During the escape which the Secretary of State, Warren Christopher, called "voluntary ethnic cleansing" and President Clinton "a new hope for peace" the refugees were shelled both by the Croatian artillery and air force, beaten and stoned by angry Croatian mobs in the presence of UN monitors and Croatian police.  At the end of September 1995, over 170,000 refugees have arrived to Serbia and another 20,000-30,000 remain in the Serb controlled territory in Bosnia. In 1991 Serbs were 15% of population in Croatia.  Today they make up 2.5%.</FONT><P>

<FONT SIZE=+2>Ms. Gordana Todorov was in <A HREF="http://www.ecn.uoknor.edu/~nsfdesmm/vojvodina/novisad/ns.html">Novi Sad</a> in <A HREF="http://www.umiacs.umd.edu/users/lpv/YU/HTML/yu.html">Serbia</a> at the time when the refugees from <a HREF="http://sharac.msc.cornell.edu/~marko/KRAJINA/index.html">Krajina</a> were arriving.  She visited the central "collection center" at the SPENS sports center in Novi Sad and numerous other places where the refugees were congregating during several days between 8/7/95 and 8/11/95.  At this time Ms. Todorov taped a number of conversations with the refugees.  The photos shown here were also taken during those visits.<P> 

 The excerpts from the interviews were added to the documents containing larger versions of the photographs.  Unfortunately, because of the initial hostile reactions of the refugees (they accused Ms. Todorov of intending to portray the footage as that of Croatian or Muslim refugees fleeing from the Serbs) Ms. Todorov was unable to record their names or their background stories.  We can only convey as much as the refugees were willing to mention in their taped conversations.  Unless indicated otherwise, the excerpts from conversations are displayed next to the picture of the collocutor.   Additional information  from news articles about the events leading to and during the exodus and the destiny of those Serbs who decided to stay in their homes in Croatia is also included.<P>

Continue to <A HREF="photo2.html">Part 2</a>.<P></FONT>

<HR>

<A HREF="http://www.cdsp.neu.edu/home/marko/public_html/guardian2.html"><IMG SRC="pictures/franjosmall.gif" ALIGN="TOP" WIDTH=116 HIGHT=180> <FONT SIZE="+2">Franjo Tudjman, a Croatian Napoleon.</FONT></a> 

