<title>Urgent! medications</title>


<h2> URGENT!   ***   URGENT!   ***   URGENT! (9/10/95)</h2>

<em>Serbian-American Medical and Dental Society</em>

<h3>FROM H.H. PRINCESS KATHERINE KARADJORDJEVIC OF YUGOSLAVIA</h3>

1) Princess just got an agreement with the JAT for free
shipment of all drugs, medicine and medical supply, from
London (UK) to Belgrade (FRY) -<strong>FREE</strong>!<P>

2) All shipments from U.S.A. ( New York or Chicago) to
London are <strong>FREE</strong>!<P>

3) All drugs or medical supply should go to the ONE doctor
[Dr. Minya McNutt (Minja Meknat)] in Chicago as collecting
depot. Be sure to have a good contact before you ship
anything.<P>

4) Antibiotics and pain medications are the most wanted !!!
 Samples of drugs are O.K.! as long as those drugs are not
expired.<P>

5) All shipments from USA to Belgrade should reach
Belgrade in matter of 2, maximum 4 days.<P>

6) Princess has all necessary documentation for any
medical shipment.<P>

7) All Serbian doctors (Serbian-American Medical and
Dental Society - SAMDS) should make at least 3-4 phone
calls to his/hers colleagues, and urge them to sent
immediately all drugs, medicines etc. to designated address
(doctor in Chicago).<P>

8) We (SAMDS) should make contact A.S.A.P. with Greek
Medical Ass. and ask them for help.  They are willing to do
that, according to Princess. Specifically we should try to
get in touch with Dr. Deliaris.<P>

9) SAMDS officer in charge of receiving and processing
shipments is Dr. Minya McNutt from Chicago.  To obtain
shipping address CALL Dr. McNutt at (312) 528-1781 (she
is fluent in Serbian).  For E-mail contact use:<address>MIROSLAV@UIC.EDU.</address><P>

<hr>

 <strong> International Orthodox Christian Charities (IOCC) is the diaconal, relief and development arm of the Standing Conference of Canonical Orthodox Bishops in the Americas (SCOBA).  Services are provided to people solely on the basis of need, without regard to ethnic or religious affiliations.  We welcome  participation by all.  Contact: IOCC; 711 West 40th Street - Suite 306; Baltimore, MD 21211; USA Tel: 410-243-9820 Fax: 410-243-9824 E-mail:iocc@igc.apc.org</strong><P>

 August 24, 1995<P>
 
 Dear Brothers and Sisters in Christ:<P>
 
      It has been three weeks since the Croatian attack on the
 Krajina created the largest single movement of refugees in the war
 that continues to torment the former Yugoslavia.  According to our
 office in Belgrade, more than 170,000 Krajina Serbs have sought
 refuge in Serbia, while many more are moving east across Bosnia.
 Well over 600,000 Serbian refugees have fled conflict in the course
 of this terrible war.  Their plight is worsened by the severe
 limitations on humanitarian assistance that sanctions have created.<P>
 
      We are pleased that IOCC - in the midst of such tragic
 circumstances - is able to continue its Christian mission of mercy,
 helping anyone who is in need and for whom we have sufficient
 supplies.  Within hours of the onset of fighting in the Krajina,
 IOCC had diverted its existing stocks to aid these new refugees -
 more than $900,000 worth of relief supplies in the last two weeks.
 We were very fortunate that at least one major contributor allowed
 us to divert immediately 30,000 hygiene parcels originally intended
 for UN enclaves to meet the needs of Serbs who have fled the
 Krajina.  We have also been able, during this time, to continue our
 numerous programs that assist people served by Serbian hospitals
 and social institutions.<P>
 
      In addition, as the lead implementing agency for the World
 Council of Churches, IOCC has received major contributions from
 European donors to assist people in the UN enclaves that still
 remain.  IOCC has also appealed to the administration in Washington
 to overturn its policy of refusing to provide emergency
 humanitarian assistance through organizations that operate in
 Serbia.<P>
 
      Attached you will find an update on our activities to assist
 Serbian populations affected by the fighting in Western Slavonia
 earlier this summer and, more recently, in the Krajina.<P>
 
      Our appeal for $2.4 million to assist refugees from the
 Krajina still stands, and we, in turn, appeal to you to find every
 possible way of responding as generously as you can.  The needs
 will be great, and the winter will be bitter.  Please share this
 letter and update with as many people as you can.<P>
 
 Yours sincerely,<P>
 
 Alexander Rondos<br>
 Executive Director<P>
 
<hr>
 
<h3> IOCC Former Yugoslavia Update</h3>

 
 
 (24 August 1995)<P>
 
 International Orthodox Christian Charities (IOCC) is the
 implementing partner of the World Council of Churches providing
 humanitarian assistance in Serbia and those areas of Bosnia
accessible from Serbia.<P>
 
 Total Current Value of IOCC Assistance to Serbian refugees since
 the fall of the western Slavonia UNPA in early May:  $968,169.00<P>
 
 9 May:<br>
 1,600 food parcels, valued at $40,000.00, were delivered to the
 Diocese of Banja Luka.<P>
 
 12 May:<br>
1,600 food parcels, valued at $40,000.00, were delivered to the
Diocese of Banja Luka.<P>
 
1 June:<br>
 1,600 food parcels, valued at $40,000.00, were distributed in
 Kljuc, Petrovac and Sanski Most by the IOCC field office in Kljuc.<P>
 
 10 June:<br>
 1,680 food parcels from IOCC, valued at $42,000.00, were delivered
by the European Community Task Force to Serbian refugees in Pakrac
 and Okucani.<P>
 
 5 August:<br>
2,280 family food parcels, valued at $57,000.00, were sent to the IOCC field office in Kljuc and were distributed to refugees from
Glamoc and Grahovo.<P>
 
9 August:<br>
One hospital kit, valued at $15,000.00, was delivered by IOCC, through Bishop LAVRENTIJE, to the hospital in Loznica which is providing medical care to the Krajina Serb refugees who are crossing the Drina at Sepak and being sent to collective centers around Loznica.  The hospital kit was donated by Metropolitan
 IRINEY.<P>
  IOCC delivered to Bishop LAVRENTIJE 1,000 children's parcels, valued at $20,000.00, for distribution by the Church to refugee children in the several collective refugee centers in Sabac diocese.  These children's parcels were financed by donations from the Northwest Indiana Circle of Serbian Sisters, the Belgrade Club in New York, and the Detroit Serbian Relief Committee.<P>
 
 10 August:<br>
 IOCC sent 20 MT of mixed canned foods, valued at $20,000.00 and donated by HEKS in Switzerland, to Bishop LAVRENTIJE; the food was immediately distributed to newly-arrived refugees in the Sabac refugee reception center.<P>
 
 16 August:<br>
 1,680 family food parcels, valued at $42,000.00, and 1,500 children's parcels, valued at $30,000.00, to Banja Luka.<P>

 22 August:<br>
 IOCC submitted a proposal for to the Office of Foreign Disaster Assistance (OFDA) for $27,500 to provide formula to 1,000 Krajina Serb infants for one month.  This proposal is part of an initial appeal to the U.S. government to change its policy about official U.S. funding for humanitarian assistance activities in Serbia and Bosnian-Serb territories.

 25 August:<br>
 840 family food parcels, valued at $21,000.00, will be sent to Kljuc.<P>
 
 26 August:<br>
 In conjunction with the World Council of Churches, IOCC will begin an assessment of the long-term needs of Krajina Serb refugees in Bosnia and Serbia.<P>
 
 IOCC now has in its Belgrade warehouse 59,000 hygiene parcels, valued at approximately $450,000.00.  These parcels were originally intended for distribution in the eastern Bosnian enclaves of Srebrenica, Zepa and Gorazde.  The Swiss church organization which donated the hygiene parcels has agreed to IOCC's request to distribute 30,000 of these parcels ($228,800.00) in Trebinje and to Krajina Serb refugees in Serbia and Bosnia; distributions will begin next week.<P>
 
 On 9 August 1995, IOCC issued an appeal to the World Council of Churches and its member agencies for $2,447,361.00 to finance a six-month program of assistance for Krajina Serb refugees.  To date, $372,369.00 has been received, as follows:<P> 
<ul>
 <li>Norwegian Church Aid is financing the procurement of 7,650 food parcels and 5,760 hygiene parcels, valued at $210,000.00. These parcels, which are now arriving in Belgrade, will be distributed to Krajina Serb refugees in Serbia and in the Banja Luka region.  The Metropolitanate Relief Fund has donated $10,000.00 to cover local distribution costs.
<li> Church World Service donated $100,000.00 to IOCC to purchase blankets and children's winter clothes; these will be provided to Krajina Serb refugees in both Serbia and Bosnia in September. 
<li> Christian Aid (UK) has donated $25,000.00 to IOCC's relief program for Krajina Serbs.
 <li>IOCC's donors in the United States have contributed $27,369.00 to
 this appeal.</ul>

<hr> 


 
           <h2>     Sarajevo Winter Report/Appeal #3</h2>
 
BACKGROUND  Last February  a few netters in the US and Sarajevo
started the "Sarajevo Winter" project, which wired cash to
Sarajevo for distribution amongst the people of a neighborhood to
help them get through the winter months. We set up a bank
account, found a way to wire money to Sarajevo reliably, and
appealed for contributions. Our Sarajevan team member distributed
the money amongst needy people of his acquaintance.<P>
 
Over the winter we collected and sent a total of $1900 to
Sarajevo, which has been shared amongst a total of 30 people.<P>
 
We also carried $900 to individuals at the request of netters who
heard of our project; and we sent a small amount of money to
Bihac.<P>
 
THE QUESTION OF PROFITEERS  We decided that money sent to
Sarajevo would work against the black market if people could lay
in supplies during those times when the city was relatively open
and prices low. We decided that it was more important to help
people with immediate necessities in this way rather than worry
too much about the profits of those who were bringing goods in
during the siege.<P>
 
We would have sent more money to Bihac, but the situation there
was different than in Sarajevo, and our Bihacan team member
advised that such aid at the time was not useful.<P>
 
END OF THE FIRST PHASE, BEGINNING OF THE SECOND  Supplying money
to Sarajevan friends during the winter was a successful project.
However, the task of distributing the money - and  having large
amounts of money in hand - was a burden to our Sarajevan team
member, and we are not currently soliciting contributions for
that particular activity.<P>
 
However, during the first phase we have identified specific 
needs in Sarajevo and also Tuzla, that can be met through
Sarajevo Winter wires, and are now appealing for help in meeting
them. Our current projects are:<P>
 
1. We are helping a Sarajevan soldier who lost his foot after
stepping  on a mine; this soldier needs remedial surgery, and a
decent prosthesis. His wound is not serious enough to require
medical evacuation, and we are attempting to supply the funds he
needs to get proper care in Sarajevo. We have arranged for a US
doctor to consult with the Sarajevan doctor via email, and the
prosthesis will be built either in the US or Sarajevo, depending
upon the siege situation. NEED: $1,000<P>
 
2. We were able to deliver a number of solar-panel battery
chargers and portable stoves to Sarajevo during the winter, and
have been told that these made a big difference to people. We
would like to procure and deliver more. NEED: $500<P>
 
3. We have begun a project "Tuzla Disabled Online" to allow the
mobility-disabled community in Tuzla to communicate with their
peers in other countries via email. We are hoping to supply two
groups, the Union  of War Invalids and the Association of
Dystrophics, with the hardware needed to bring people online and
also provide training in computer skills. Deltacomm ltd, a
telecomm company in Tuzla, will provide the necessary technical
help. NEED: $2,500.<P>
 
IF YOU WANT TO HELP: Donations for these projects may be sent to
our account by wire or check.<P>
 
Wires: Ask your bank to send the wire to<P>
 
     State Street Bank of Boston <br>
     routing number 0110-000-28<P>
 
with the following information: <P>
 
     PLEASE CREDIT:<br>
     Roxbury Highlands Bank<br>
     account number 90322801<P>
 
     FOR THE BENEFIT OF:<br>
     Sarajevo Winter<br>
     account number 010023701<P>
 
 
Checks: To avoid wire fees, you can send a check, money order, or
bank draft (US funds) to: <P>
 
     Sarajevo Winter (acct. 23701)<br>
     c/o Roxbury-Highland Bank<br>
     515 Centre St.<br>
     Jamaica Plain MA 02130<br> 
     USA<P>
 
The check should be made out to "Sarajevo Winter". <P>
 
If you want a personal receipt, send your contribution to:<P>
 
     Sarajevo Winter c/o Ed Agro<br>
     32 Robinwood Ave #2<br>
     Jamaica Plain MA 02130<br>
     USA<P>
 
For more information, send email to <P>
 
     eagro@igc.apc.org  or pamelacd@aol.com<P>
 
Thanks to all who have contributed to the previous Sarajevo
Winter project, and thanks in advance to all who contribute to
this appeal  --  Ed Agro, Pamela Crocker-Davis, William Hunt
<P>
