<HEAD>
<TITLE>Relations: Bosnia and Iran</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
used without permission, for "fair use" only<hr>

<FONT SIZE="+1">

<h1>Strategy of Flirt</h1>

<strong><em>by Ljiljana Smajlovic</em></strong><P>

<h2>Vreme, Belgrade, FR Yugoslavia, 4/6/96</h2>

<em>"I have been living for 37 years in the Christian environment in atheistic
Europe, living among a handful of scared Muslims, in the atmosphere of lies 
and hypocrisy.  My permanent and open Islamic orientation, in the midsts of 
a communist country, the lack of basic conditions for living and daily humiliation
are the reasons for my decision to leave my home and homeland and emigrate to
Iran."<P>
Meliha Salihbegovic<br>
in her letter to Imam Hommeini, July '82</em><P>

In the pre-war multicultural and multiconfessional Bosnia-Hercegovina, Sarajevo
writer Meliha Salihbegovic was sent in 1983 because of these words straight to 
jail.  The quote is taken from her private letter to Imam Hommeini from 1982,
which in the hands of then Bosnian judicial organs turned into one of the 
crucial pieces of evidence in "the process to Muslim fundamentalists" in Sarajevo
in 1983.  In the warrant for the start of investigation against Meliha Salihbegovic
, issued on March 29, 1983, and signed by investigative judge Abdulah Hadzikaric, 
Ms. Salihbegovic was accused that, between January '80 and March '83, "through
numerous contacts with Alija Izetbegovic, with whom she had lived for a time
in a sharia [Islamic] marriage," she expressed her nationalistic and panislamist
beliefs, glorified the Islamic revolution in Iran and Imam Hommeini.<P>

Those were the dark ages in Bosnia, when Alija Izetbegovic, Omer Behmen, 
Hasan Cengic, Edhem Bicakcic, Husein Zivalj and Ismet Kasumagic (let us only 
mention those accused from the process in 1983 who in the spring of 1990
founded the Party of Democratic Action [SDA] and who have until today remained on
important positions in this political party and Bosnian state) were accused of 
conspiring with the enemy because they had planned to travel to Iran (the
indictment states that "they tried to establish contacts with the institutions
from foreign countries in order to obtain assistance") and because all of them,
except for Alija Izetbegovic, had secretly traveled to Iran in order to take part
in the celebration of the anniversary of the Islamic revolution and the congress
of unification of Sunnis and Shias in Iran, between January 2 and 14, 1983;
their passports were not stamped in hope that in that way they would avoid "complications
in a socialist environment."<P>

Today, it is hard to say with any confidence how much publicity the process
to "the Muslim fundamentalists" or "Young Muslims" received in the Bosnian 
public at the time.  The public knew at the time, although one wasn't allowed
to say that in public, that in Bosnia [the authorities] had been always working
on a so called political balance between the three nations and nationalisms and
 that all three had to be accounted for at all times, both on official positions
 and in prisons.  The public at that time, of course, wasn't able to judge the
 secret Islamic Declaration written by Alija Izetgbegovic, but the accusation
 of betrayal of their own country to Hommeini made quite a splash, moreover
 because the accused didn't deny that they had traveled to Iran although
they denied counter-revolutionary actions.<P>

The Sarajevo process from 1983 has in the meantime been unmasked as a show trial
to the people whose fundamental "sin" was that they didn't believe and think in 
the way that the authorities demanded from them.  Nevertheless, the "Iranian 
connection" still haunts the Iranian travelers from 1983.  The Teheran guests, together with their supporter
who stayed in Sarajevo, Alija Izetbegovic, are today again on the bench for 
the accused, although the circumstances are somewhat different this time.  All of them
are on important positions in the party and state (Omer Behmen, vicepresident 
of the SDA at the time when the party was founded, is today the ambassador
in Teheran) and constitute the so called hawkish wing of the SDA.  All of them 
influence the decisions important for the fate of the country; at this time 
it seems that the most difficult decision facing the Bosnian Muslim authorities
is the decision about the fate of several dozens of  Iranian fighters, widely
known as "Mojahedeen" who had fought in Bosnia on the side of the Bosnian Army.
The Dayton agreement stipulated that all foreign fighters were supposed to leave
Bosnia by the end of January this year.  Bosnian government has claimed several 
times so far that it had fulfilled this requirement from Dayton, but the NATO
calmly responded every time that that wasn't true; one one occasion NATO obtained
material evidence for its claims by arresting three Iranian citizens after the
capture of a terrorist camp near Fojnica.<P>

Bosnian stake in this game of nerves is enormous, but all trump cards are in the 
hands of NATO alliance and Washington.  Sarajevo had waged a difficult battle
throughout the war in order to lift the arms embargo and gain rights to the American
assistance in arming and training of the Bosnian army.  Furthermore, the Bosnian 
delegation swallowed quite a few bitter pills in Dayton only with the help of
water sweetened by promises that the U.S.A. would train and equip its army.<P>

In this moment, Bosnia is separated from that important and significant goal
by fifty or sixty Iranian fighters in its territory.  At least Alija Izetbegovic
acknowledges that many in his latest statement on this topic given to Bosnian
weekly <em>Ljiljan</em>.<P>

It seems that the Americans have made to Izetbegovic an offer he cannot refuse,
but he is still hesitating.  Washington has firmly decided and publicly stated
that the arming and training of the Bosnian Army will only start after all 
Iranians have left, and they are still there.  Probably not for long, since
Izetbegovic has opened a door to compromise by admitting that Iran, which 
indeed proved to be the real friend of Bosnia, "is far away, while our enemy 
is very near."<P> 

Therefore, Sarajevo is hesitating to give in to American conditions, but it 
would be wrong to interpret that hesitation with the immaturity of the
Bosnian regime, its ideological dependence on Teheran, blind loyalty to
the participants of the Islamic revolution or some kind of religious fanaticism.
The sources of that hesitation are complex and related to the role that Bosnia
has (or intends to attain) in the world Islamic community.<P>

Since his first steps on the international scene, Alija Izetbegovic has patiently
built a specific position for Bosnia-Hercegovina among the Islamic countries.  As 
early as July 1991, when Yugoslavia was still "alive" and nine months before
Bosnian independence, Izetbegovic requested that Bosnia-Hercegovina attend the next
conference of the Ministers of foreign relations from Islamic countries, which
would take place in Turkey.  That action caused some commotion in the three-party 
coalition which at the time ruled Bosnia [SDA, HDZ and SDS].  On July 19, 1991, <em>Oslobodenje</em>
asked Izetbegovic whether he had requested the member status for Bosnia, to what
he responded:" In a certain sense that is true, but we all know that, according
to the Statute, Bosnia-Hercegovina cannot be a member of this organization.  Only
internationally recognized Muslim countries can be the members of that organization.
However, some organizations, groups and parties can also be members of that
organization."  It is a well known fact that in the Islamic world three countries
with three different models of state organization and role of religion in the society
are fighting for the supremacy among the Muslims. Those countries are Iran,
Saudi Arabia and Turkey.  Alija Izetbegovic managed to achieve that each one
of these three countries tries to gain his favor and the favor of his Bosniaks.
He has flirted with each one of them, while he managed not to cast his lot
with any one of them. He has received direly necessary aid from all three of them,
always keeping open the possibility that he would in the end ally with only 
one of them.<P> 

Extremely important part of that strategy was the continuous insistence of Sarajevo
that everything happening to the Muslims in Bosnia was exclusively the result of 
their religion, that the world wouldn't tolerate a genocide against the members
of any one of Christian sects, that the Muslims in Bosnia were suffering because 
of Islam and therefore, for Islam.  Magazine <em>Ljiljan</em>, whose editor-in-chief
is Dzemaludin Latic, former professor at the Sarajevo Islamic college (another
one of the SDA founders and accused in the 1983 process), provides 
plentiful evidence about the pretensions of the Izetbegovic's Bosnia to play a
messianic role as the unifier of the Islamic world.  For example, in March 1995,
Resid Hafizovic wrote that "Bosnia and the Bosniaks have unified the whole of 
the Muslim world...  Because of that we hope that Bosnia and the Bosniaks will
in the future transform the collective consciousness of the Muslim world and 
fundamentally transform the relations between the Muslim East and European west.
[The Muslim world] has been yearning  to cast away its spiritual,
economic and military-political subordination imposed by the Christian 
neocolonialist Europe which is today directed by the blood-thirsty governments in
Paris, London and Moscow."  In the latest issue of <em>Ljiljan</em> the president
of Bosnia has the following to say on that topic:" When we talk about allies,
my answer is that both the U.S.A. and the Islamic peoples should be on our side,
and if possible the whole world."  As a sign of recognition, among other to his 
statesmanship, it should be said that Bosnia is very close to that goal.  
Bosnian president has done everything possible to gain the support of the whole
world, not only Islamic countries.  Finally, after all, he will do as he must, 
in order to avoid loosing the support of the U.S.A.<P>

At the time Serb grenades provided a miracle which homogenized the Muslim 
population in Bosnia.  That is the origin of that famous American statement
about the secular Bosnian population who was "pushed into Islam by grenades."  
American blackmail is now on the way to complete that process and unite all 
Bosniaks, even those  who don't have a particularly good reason to be happy 
about the presence of "Mojahedeen" in Bosnia.<P> 
<hr>

Translated on 6/7/96<P>

<hr>
</FONT>
