<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Interview with Adem Demaqi</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
used without permission, for "fair use" only<hr>

<FONT SIZE="+1">

<h1>Disappointed People</h1>
                
<strong><em>by Perica Vucinic</em></strong><P>

<h2>Vreme, Belgrade, FR Yugoslavia, 5/11/96</h2>

The Republic of Kosovo exists only in the heads, hearts, desires and souls 
of Albanians.  In reality, the Republic of Kosovo doesn't exist.  In order to 
become a real state, Kosovo must have authorities which control its 
territory, issue passports, personal documents, the authorities which have
their borders, customs, army, police, judicial system...  to have everything that
makes a state;  Albanians don't have that.  Albanians have built a so called 
parallel system in education, culture and sport; this system ensures that
a part of our children don't waste time hanging out at street corners but that
they try to acquire some knowledge.  That parallel system is only a shadow
of our aspirations.  The same is true for our republic.<P> 

<strong>What would you do if you were the leader of the Albanian national 
movement?</strong><P>

I would transform the whole political process.  I would put tactics before
strategy.  I wouldn't insist on us having a republic, but would try to implement
in practice that which our people voted for in the 1991 referendum: that Kosovo
should be an independent, sovereign republic.<P>

<strong>How would you do that?</strong><P>

In the same manner in which that is usually done in the world: by exploiting
all methods at disposal of a civilized people, by mobilizing the whole nation,
by liberating and recovering those things which were taken away from us in 1989.
That would require sacrifices, but those sacrifices would be much smaller than 
those we have already suffered until now; I think that the Albanians have, since
1990, lost a lot.  Almost 500,000 people have left Kosovo because of terror and
our education, culture, economic and financial institutions have been stifled.
We are a people which lives at the edge of survival.<P>

<strong>Your answer shows that you support a more extreme approach.  You've been
accused of being the inspiration behind more radical currents within the 
Albanian block...</strong><P>

There are two limits I don't want to cross: neither a bloody conflict, a war, 
nor a capitulation.  That means that everything between these two extreme options
is a part of the political scene to which I belong.   My "extremism" is only
extreme for those who are not willing to risk anything but are simply waiting
for events to resolve by themselves.<P>

The fact that some accuse me of extremism, as in a part of the Belgrade press
these days, is another proof that here anyone can shoot you like in a jungle.
Here, Albanians are unprotected, like animals in a jungle; therefore,
you can be assassinated through the papers, there's no one to object to.
If there were the rule of law in this state no one would dare claim that Demaqi
was an agent in Sigurimi [secret police in Stalinist Albania].<P>

I don't have enough information to be able to speculate who is responsible
for the events from the last ten days of April [terrorist attacks on Serbian
policemen and civilians].  I cannot agree with the theory that these attacks
were staged by Serbs: Albanians have much more motivation to stage these attacks
because they are angry and desperate;  since they are unable to express this
anger through institutional channels some Albanians are prepared to do anything
at all in order to change something.<P>

<strong>Do you think that these groups have support from abroad?</strong><P>

These groups are groups of disappointed men and women.  It is hard to guess
from which circles these people come from, since the apathy has spread through
all levels of the society.  There are a lot of people who had illusions that
the world, USA or Europe, would fix everything for us in a month or two.<P>

These gullible people are likely to go from one extreme to another.  I've
always known that no one would serve us anything on a plate.  Having in mind
the rights of Serbs, I believe that we should try to negotiate with them first
and try to point out to them that they can only protect their interests if they
take into account our interests.<P>

<strong>In your opinion, what should Albanians do at this moment?</strong><P>

At this moment, Albanians should abandon multiparty politics, since political
parties only fragment people.  They are wasting a lot of energy at internal
struggle.  It turned out that the Albanians are the wisest people in the world,
wiser that English, wiser than the French;  when these two peoples were in great
danger they united all of their forces until they won a victory.  Albanians must 
not  be wiser than the others.  Multiparty system hasn't produced tangible results
so far.  We should abandon it and unite all our resources.  That way, we 
would form a force which would convince the Serbian regime that we are not joking.<P>

<strong>But then, you wouldn't have democracy...</strong><P>

This is a fake democracy;  we can say whatever we like, but we have reached the point
at which Albanians have no school, no culture, no economy, nothing to eat.
This kind of democracy is ridiculous, a caricature.  Our situation today is worse than
Tito's dictatorship and his totalitarian regime.<P> 

<strong>What in your opinion should Serbia do?</strong><P>

Serbia should wake up and draw conclusions from what happened with Bosnia-Hercegovina;
she should realize what has changed in the world's attitude towards it and not 
allow for that to happen again;  if Albanians are brought to the situation that they
have to defend their essence they will act the way Bosnians did;  they tried
to avoid the war, but were pushed into it.  Therefore, Serbia, as the stronger
side, as the side responsible for all those massacres and this tragedy, whose
regime destroyed former Yugoslavia, Serbia must stop, think and talk to Albanians
openly, so that we can see what we can do together.<P>

<strong>Why don't Albanians take part in Serbian elections?</strong><P>

If the Albanians took part in elections they would accept their slavery.
They would win at most 30 places in a 250 member parliament, they would be
outvoted and couldn't do anything in order to protect their essence.  
As it turned out in Macedonia and the communes within Serbia, 
it is always possible to find ways to enact laws against Albanian interests.
We know that Albanians, if they entered the Parliament could, together with
the opposition, bring down the Milosevic regime.  But the irony is that
those weak parties are making offers which are worse than Milosevic's
promises.  In fact, Milosevic does what the opposition thinks.  He is a lesser
evil compared with what the opposition intends to do.  Let me not mention
Seselj.  All of them agree that Albanians should be given some sort of minority 
rights and that's it.  Our political platform is to seek equal status with Serbs.

<hr>

Translated on 8/20/96<P>

<hr>
</FONT>
<A HREF="/info/students/marko/yuindpress.html"><IMG SRC="/info/students/marko
/pictures/home.gif" ALT="HOME" WIDTH=80 HIGHT=40></a>
<hr>
</BODY>
