<HEAD>
<TITLE>Democracy in Croatia</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
used without permission, for "fair use" only<hr><P>
<FONT SIZE="+1">

<h1> Democroatia</h1>

<strong><em>by Drago Pilsel</em></strong><P>

<h2> Novi List, Saturday March 9, 1996</h2>



                              
                                                                    
                              
       <h2>    Don Zivko Kustic - the Kaptol Avenger?</h2>


      I  wanted to begin today s text with a salute  to  all
women  and  a  look  back at their  difficult  past.   I  am
particularly  motivated  by the  fact  that  on  All  Saints
Day(celebrated on May 19) the Pope dedicated  this  year  to
the advancement of women in society.  Unfortunately, because
of the serious case of libel by Don Zivko Kustic against the
Croatian  Helsinki Committee(CHC) for Human  Rights  in  the
most  recent copy of the weekly Panorama(March 6, 1996),  in
the Bulletin of the Catholic Information Agency(February 29,
1996) and in Glas Koncila(No. 10-1134), I am forced to stand
and defend my victimized colleagues from the CHC, all women,
be  they  religious or not, who's rights the CHC  for  human
rights takes the responsibility of protecting in the name of
all the people who are adversely affected by the actions  of
the aforementioned journalist.<P>

      I have a complaint which I would like to voice, but  I
am  not bitter, and I avow before God and the people that  I
am  do  not  wish  to hurt Don Zivko Kustic, journalist  and
Christian who has meant so much to me in my life, especially
while  I was in Argentina and dreaming of a life in Croatia.
It  is no secret that I play an active and executive role in
the  Helsinki  Committee, but every week I write  my  column
under  my own name, aware of the possibility that the moment
may  come  when that organization will be inclined to  react
publicly  to  stop  Kustic's  attacks  and  libeling   the
Helsinki Committee.<P>

        <h2>The CHC s Statement No. 33 hit the bullseye</h2>

      Statement No. 33 about the violations of the rights to
religion,  the rights of religious people and the  state  of
religious  freedom  in the Republic of  Croatia,  without  a
doubt   hit  the  bullseye .  As one of its  authors  I  can
freely  say that its effect was the intended purpose of  the
members  of  the CHC who have been monitoring  the  problems
listed  in  Statement No. 33 since the  beginning  of  their
public activism.  Religious people and church officials  who
founded and are members of the Committee can attest to this,
because  their  membership in the  Committee  was  justified
since  religious people and theologians must  contribute  to
the  establishment  of a legal state.  But,  this  statement
occurred as a response to the accumulation of  problems  and
negative incidents.  It should certainly not be received  as
being   anti-Catholic , and those who attempt to force  that
interpretation onto the public are very mistaken.<P>

      It  is necessary to note that according to information
received  in  confidence from a high ranking office  of  the
Croatian Bishops Conference, the Catholic church in  Croatia
monitors  every  bit  of information  that  comes  from  the
dealings of the CHC very closely, perhaps more closely than
the members of that Committee are aware.<P>

      Anyone  who  reads  Statement No. 33  carefully  might
disagree with the professionalism of the author, the members
of  the CHC s Commission for Religious Rights and the Rights
of  Religious  People,  and outside contributors,  but  they
cannot  think  that  they  hold any  feelings  of  animosity
against  the  church.  I can attest to the fact  that  these
people  have  a  great  respect for not  only  the  Catholic
bishops,  some  of which they interact with  regularly,  and
because they believe in the unity of the  house of the  same
God  Creator  as honorable with a refined sense  of  justice
and sense for the truth and peace which is no less refined.<P>

      How  does  Zivko Kustic dare claim that   the  CHC  is
seriously accusing the Catholic church  on the front page of
the IKE Bulletin(09/6)?  What gives him the right to mislead
the  public  by saying that Statement No. 33 was printed  in
its entirety in Novi List on February 28, 1996, as well as a
statement  by  Ivan Zvonimir Cicak(page 13)?!   Furthermore,
what gives him the right to deceive the public for the third
time  on  page  16  of the same issue by  saying  that   the
Croatian Helsinki Committee for Human Rights is in  its  own
way,  offering  unsubstantiated and  exaggerated  criticisms
about the state of freedoms in Croatian society  in a manner
which should  open the eyes  of the readers of IKE, and  the
Catholic  Bishops, like the forgers of truth on HTV(Croatian
Television)?<P>

               <h2>Kustic's Confusion</h2>

      No,  just as it is written, Kustic's confusion  does
not  stem  from his role as editor in chief of the  Catholic
Information  Agency.  In the already mentioned,  recognized,
important  and  relevant  weekly  Glas  Koncila,  which   is
published  by the archdioceses of Zagreb, Split, Vrhbosna,
Rijeka  and  Zadar,  which is headed  by  the  Archdioscesan
Chancellery  in  Zagreb,  the author(undoubtedly  Don  Zivko
Kustic)  questions the veracity of the claim that  religious
rights  are  being  violated in  the  Republic  of  Croatia,
despite the fact that it is being confirmed by the President
of the Meshihat of the Islamic Community in the Republic of
Croatia, and many others.<P>

       The  author  of  that  scandalous  text  negates  the
possibility  that  the  Catholic church  is  being  used  to
promote  political motives even though that same  claim  has
been put forth by the same publication several times in  the
past.   However,  it is not the first time  that  they  have
claimed  in  an  unacceptable and  uncivilized  way  that  a
document  from the CHC is composed in such a way so  as  to
appeal  most to those circles who are anticipating bad  news
about  Croatian  democracy.    I  do  not  know  why  it  is
necessary  for the commentary in Glas Koncila  to  encourage
hysteria about international opinions about Croatia.<P>

      However,  in the aforementioned text, I can  recognize
the  conscience of a man who, contrary to the  teachings  of
the  Catholic  church and its highest representative,  wrote
about   unseen humanity of war , as though there  existed  a
humane  form  of  war, who was responsible  along  with  the
editor  of  Glas  Kocila for informing his readers  just  as
Vjesnik(August  7, 1996) did, that the Pope   approved   the
military  action(without mentioning by Croatia by name,  nor
any  other antagonists) because  the solution is to be found
on  the  battlefield .  I therefore see a  man  who  is  not
prepared  to  admit that he was wrong when he  was  late  to
notice  the warnings of serious human rights violations  and
atrocious  crimes  taking place on  the  recently  liberated
territories,  threatening the future peace and long  awaited
justice, of those countless people who fled in the  wake  of
the Serbian aggression.  I see a member of the media who  is
responsible  for the fact that his Archbishop and  publisher
of  Glas Koncila was uninformed and told Italian journalists
that     everything   was   intact    following    Operation
Storm (Cardinal  Kuharic  on the daily  news  show  Corriere
della  sera,  according to Novi List on  August  28,  1995).
Even  though  it  is  true  that Zivko  Kustic,  some  other
journalists  and  especially the Catholic Archbishops  later
complained  about the crimes that were committed during  and
after   Operation  Storm , whenever I look  at  a  corpse  I
wonder how many fewer of them there might have been if  they
had reacted at the right time and in an adequate way.<P>


<h2>Turn to Love and Life, not to Lies and Shame</h2>

      Last week I found myself in the village of Komici near
Udbina  with an accused member of the CHC (and author of  one
of  the aforementioned statements), the honorable gentleman,
a retired Orthodox priest, Jovan Nikolic and a few employees
of   the  CHC  to  arrange  a  Christian  burial  for   Sava
Lavrnic (93)  and  her  son Petar (61) atrociously  killed  on
August  12, 1995, when a group of Croatian soldiers  invaded
this  little  village  near Lika and killed  a  few  elderly
people, and even burned them alive in their own homes while
they  lay in their beds.  The police officers who were there
with us did not hide their disgust and rage because that  is
not the way in which to defend Croatia, the country  we love
and  for  which we were ready to give our own lives.   Night
fell  shortly after Milivoj Lasan, the district  judge  from
Zadar  and  his  assistants (the plaintiff was also  present)
inspected  and  collected evidence from  the  scene  of  the
crime.<P>

      A  few of us were standing around the open grave while
father  Jovan  was leading the prayer for the souls  of  the
buried  when  the moon appeared from behind  the  mountains.
One  could hear the howls of wolves in the distance, perhaps
the  same  wolves that did not disturb the corpses for  over
half  a year because they fed on the remains of seven  slain
cows  that rested in front of Sava s and Petar s  house.   A
single coffin was lowered into the grave.  Inside it, mother
and  son were left in an endless embrace, to contemplate  in
the  peace of Lord, our need to repent and turn to love  and
life, not lies and shame.<P>

     The people who have committed themselves to serving the
citizens, Croatian democracy, ecumenical and inter-religious
dialogue  and  peace  in the Balkans are  being  accused  of
subtly  manipulating the topic of religious rights  in  this
country.  The people from the CHC did not want to release to
the  public  the  names of those people who  manipulate  the
media,  distribute propaganda and encourage totalitarianism,
nazism and fascism,  Chetnik  and  Ustasha  ideologies,  and
even manipulate history.  However, we are prepared to do so
if  the  churches do not resolve this issue within  each  of
their  respective  communities  and  primarily,  instead  of
dealing  with  the  issue through journalists  who  are  not
ashamed  to publish their attacks in newspapers that promote
totalitarian  ideologies  such  as  that  of  the   Ustasha,
including  their  associates who promote neo-nazi  and  neo-
Ustasha  folklore and oppose the teachings of the Pope  John
Paul  II  and the teachings of the Croatian Catholic Bishops
which  were bravely and wisely written in a special document
written in commemoration of the 50 year anniversary  of  the
end of WWII (Novi List, May 6, 1995).<P>

<h2>One Does Not Need to Whisper Into the Ears of Bishops</h2>

      As we have already heard, one does not need to whisper
into  the ears of Bishops and move them to turn against  the
people who simply want peace, good, dialogue, justice and
respect.  The bishops can read for themselves and they  will
recognize the facts and intentions.  However, all those  who
are  familiar with the thinking of Zivko Kustic,  and  still
don't  know  that  he is not the Church's spokesperson,  and
because for all of those who were not able to read the CHC s
Statement  No.  33,  it is important  to  restate  that  the
Committee  does  not  condone the Catholic  church's 
agreements  with  the  government,  specifically  agreements
between   the   religious  Chair   and   the   Republic   of
Croatia (Zivko Kustic in Panorama), nor is it true that CHC's
statement  makes serious accusations against the leaders  of
the  Catholic church in Croatia because of violations of the
religious  rights of those citizens who are not Catholic  or
they  do not defend those people s rights. (Zivko Kustic  in
IKI)   If  necessary,  all of the members  of  the  CHC  are
prepared  to  show their personal income and honorariums  to
prove  that  they are not  fools, nor paid by  some  foreign
circles   just  like I was asked to do last  week  by  a  known
clergyman  and  his  witnesses  who's  identities  will   be
protected.<P>

      It  goes without saying that there will be a lot  more
said about the CHC's Statement No. 33 and Zivko Kustic;  not
simply because it is written in order to help those who  are
determined to pass the law described in Article 40, actually
41 of the Constitution of the Republic of Croatia, including
a  law to regulate the status of religious communities which
is  openly supported by the Catholic bishops and rejected by
the CHC.  Therefore, the CHC is accused of contriving the timing
of its declaration.  If anything was contrived, then it was  on
the  part of the aforementioned publicist who set the  stage
to  perniciously instigate a conflict between the church and
the  CHC  immediately  before the meeting  of  the  Croatian
Archdioceses.<P>

         <h2> Who needs Kustic's change in attitude?</h2>
                              
      The scene is familiar.  Find an enemy from the inside,
publish a story about the left, actually the right pampering
and  abusing  the  bishops, or that other well  known  story
which  goes like this:  single someone out, strike  them,  and  praise
everyone   else    and   avoid   the   social   and   public
dissatisfaction.  Since the HDZ (Croatian Democratic  Union)-
started running a circus in Zagreb it is not receiving as many visitors as it
used  to,  not due to their political values it  represents,
but  due  to their immoral behavior.  On October  29,  1995,
Glas Koncila, the  new face of the church , printed a prayer
on  the front page, for the people who will choose who  they
will  entrust  with  the  power  associated  with  political
leadership.   They  should  therefore  complain  since   the
promises have not been kept and the prayers to God  for  our
nation  have  not been realized.  What about those  who  are
hungry for bread and justice?  We ll see.<P>

     If Zivko Kustic is not hungry and does not see any need
to  feel  any compassion for those whose human and religious
rights  are  being violated, nor respect for those  who  are
constantly fighting to see to it that there is as little  as
possible of such cases, at least on paper, then maybe  there
will  be  nothing in the end.  Yes, we know that he  has  on
several  occasions spoken out against those who have  abused
freedoms.  He admitted that it is hard not to agree with the
comments  made in Statement No. 33.  However,  he  viciously
attacked the dignified members of the CHC, and accused  Ivan
Zvonimir Cicak of abusing the Church and further created  an
atmosphere  that is conducive to the continued violation  of
human rights.<P>

      Does he think he is smarter than our bishops?  If not,
then why did he praise Statement No. 33 right before me and several
witnesses  and even went so far as to say that he  would  be
ready and willing to sign it himself.<P>

      With  his drastic change in attitude, Zivko Kustic  is
trying to direct the Statement at the Catholic church.  Very
low,   unpleasant   and  unacceptable.   Who   needs   that?
Certainly  not the members of the CHC.  Especially  not  the
religious community.  The HDZ?  We'll see.<P>

<hr>

Translated by the CHC for Human Rights, March 13, 1996

