<HEAD>
<TITLE>Resurrection of the Directive</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

used without permission, for "fair use" only<hr>

<FONT SIZE="+1">

 <h1>Sudden Resurrection of the Directive</h1>

<strong><em>by Hrvoje Turkovic</em></strong><P>

<h2>Hrvatski Vijenac, Zagreb, Croatia, 3/7 1996</h2> 

Why did Croatian Television (HRT) (actually its "executive powers") feel an obligation to start every episode of the documentary series <em> the Death of Yugoslavia</em> (director Angus Mac Queen, Great Britain, 1995) with an anonymous editorial personalized in the announcer, which repeatedly tried to convince that the series is incomplete, confusing, biased, unobjective, malicious etc.?  Why was this done, against the prevailing media custom not to give special introductions to programs, but only announce them and later discuss the controversial ones  (as was supposed to be done with this series as well)?<P>

<center>
***
</center><P>

A supporter of this approach would probably, among other, argue that the series was made "very skillfully" ("highly professionally") and that uninformed and unsophisticated audience (usually with short memory) could believe that everything is really the way it was presented in <em>the Death of Yugoslavia</em>, and especially in those parts (very unflattering at that) which concern Croatian participation in those events.  Obviously, it is better to prevent that sort of development than to try later to modify it.<P>

An offended viewer might say that the introductions were obviously the expression of the belief in at the Croatian TV that the Croatian TV audience is made of naive fools and people incapable of making their own judgments, and ready to accept anything as long as it is sufficiently skillfully presented; because of that they had to be instructed about the "nature" of the program, and its "actual" quality.<P>

A lot of people do accept the information served on TV and accept the attitude expressed in leading TV programs as their own.  On the other hand a lot of them accept with criticism and dissatisfaction TV programs and loudly express that (as many opinion polls demonstrate).  As both "facts" stand, both opinions are also right.<P>

Nevertheless, the prevailing opinion is that a <em>mass medium</em>, the one addressing a large and in many ways diverse audience, trying to reach all of it, should count on a possible misunderstanding (since people are not always concentrating, have different educational backgrounds, different TV watching experiences etc.) and clarify things so that "everyone understands".  That's better than to assume refined understanding and than fail to accomplish that.  Because of that, the Television has a right to take as its starting point in broadcast and production of its programs <em>the assumed stupidity</em> (of its intended audience): a program, its attitude has to be clear to the most stupid person in the audience.<P>

Of course the preceding is simply a <em>rationalization</em>, that is a sufficiently convincing justification for a practice which follows from different reasons.  Actually, Television (also our television, HRT) takes into account that the receptory capabilities of the audience are different and prepares different types of programs for different types of audience: children programs for children, amusement programs for an uninvolved viewer seeking relaxation, more involved programs for intellectually demanding viewers, opera for opera lovers, sport programs for sport fans etc.  With this diversity, television attempts to satisfy its diverse audience.  <em>Reduction to the most stupid viewer</em> is definitely not the basis for the production of all programs.  Only some of them.<P>

<h2>Who Is Stupid Here?</h2>   

Therefore, seemingly this <em>assumed stupidity</em> really guided the writers of the editorial about <em>The Death of Yugoslavia</em>; they really didn't care whether the statements regarding the British series truly portrayed the most salient characteristics of the program.  As if they believed that the audience's stupidity is such that it wouldn't recognize even obvious false statements, all because of the trust and the authority of the "editorial room".<P>

For example, in the introduction to the third episode of the series, <em>Doors of Hell</em>, the announcer quoted "... a sentence which exemplifies the viewpoint of the authors:' Wars may be planned on maps and in closed rooms, but they start with a string of stupidities and in chaos.'"  After that he continued:" Of course, the war in Bosnia-Hercegovina did not start like this.  As we know, it was planned and executed in cold blood by the greater Serbian elite in Belgrade, with the help of Yugoslav peoples Army, Karadzic's followers and Seselj's and Arkan's criminals."  Finally, he concluded:" In this confusing British series, the order of events, actions and their significance were not portrayed in a way which would allow an uninformed viewer to form a clear picture of all developments on the Bosnian soil."  Therefore, the editorial, partly openly and partly through insinuations, stated that the authors of the series did not consider the planning of the war important and put more emphasis on the events in the field; those events were confusing and presented in a confusing way; finally that sort of approach was confusing and did not provide "the full picture".<P>

Afterwards you watched the episode and found out the opposite.  The authors, with the investigative passion and in a very convincing and clear manner present exactly how Serb planning <em>prepares and causes seemingly</em> spontaneous, cruel ("confusing") events "in the field".  The investigative passion of the authors comes out in their attempts to uncover in the elite, ideologists and key political leaders, those ideas, decisions, actions, predictions which reveal the merciless logic behind those seemingly so "irrational" and "wild" events.  The series, in spite of the widely held belief, both abroad and at home, that the war in the former Yugoslavia was an explosion of spontaneous primitivism, inhumanity, irrational tribal instincts and primal evil, reveals that behind everything one finds political calculations, struggle for power, skillful recklessness, good and bad judgments; in short, exactly the ingredients of the world politics.  The authors uncover that clearly, convincingly, especially because they try to keep track, as much as possible, of the wide variety of interests and personality traits of the participants, expressed through personal testimonials and mutual portrayals of the protagonists.  The series is professionally impressive exactly because of its meticulously <em>transparent complexity</em>, because it avoids emotional (propagandist) reductionism (although it is choosy and naturally, since it is their and not our program, it gives "their" and not "our" interpretation of the events).  It tries to be <em>revealing</em>: it reveals the engine behind the surface commotion.  That is why it bothers those (among Serbs, Slovenes and us) who insist on that deceptive surface commotion.<P>

<h2>New Hair of Socialism</h2>

Most likely, the series hurts our TV-political caretakers because it cannot be used as a fodder for our interpretation of the events and our slogans.<P>

This is , I believe, also the reason for the obvious carelessness in connection with the introductory editorial.  The purpose of the introduction was not to really <em>unmask</em> the hidden motives of the series: it is hard to believe that the editorial writers were so naive to believe that appropriate outraged commentaries which would immediately be refuted by the series could effectively "unmask" anything.<P>

The purpose is easily recognized in this region: the introduction was the <em>directive</em> (to use this awful term for shaggy socialist practice which is today obviously growing new hair).  That is, the introduction was <em> a lesson which demonstrated how one was expected to talk about issues in public</em>.  In this case, we are talking about the directive which proscribes how one <em>must not</em> talk about key political issues: one must not be emotionally neutral, must not talk "from a foreign point of view", but only from ours, and not any "our" point of view but the one which is identical to the template provided by the president of the state, his spokespersons, spokespersons of the ruling party, media exponents of the state policy etc.<P>

The directive need not be convincing in its content, only in its implications.  Directive must be followed, not because you believe in it (although that is desirable), but because you know that you will experience unpleasant (and in the long term possibly fatal) consequences if you don't, and possibly very favorable consequences if you loudly follow the directive and eagerly spread it around.<P> 

<h2>Appropriate Views</h2>

A careful reader may object at this point: local series of introductions is too small a sample to base the theory about resuscitated directivism on it.  They would be right, if that was the only manifestation of directivism.  Unfortunately this is not the case.  Actually, the beginning of the tenure of Obrad Kosovac, the old reliable news "cadre" from the age of reliable socialist directivism, as the editor of the TV news program, marks the sudden resurrection of directivism.  Anonymous editorials again received their frequent and important spot in news programs, giving, as in the past, a model of how one should think and speak about the key issues of the policies of our rulers; finally, in addition to "editorials" Kosovac also introduced "specific issue oriented" commentators (for example Nenad Ivankovic and Jozo Curic; in the past we had "party intellectuals" who personally followed and judged cultural events: empty directive commentaries were reserved for the key issues of daily politics) who reliably (and with "individual cover") set out the "desirable views".  Ever more frequently, talk shows with mostly leading politicians from the ruling party and important state institutions and caring hosts take the directive approach. Etc.<P>

Of course, not all programs have a coat of directivist paint.  Only those which treat key political issues.  The measure of directivism (interpretation of news and commentary) in a given program is the indicator of the importance of the issue in question.  The more the program slides towards marginal political issues the freer it is from directivism.  However, there is no doubt, directivism has firmly established itself at the Croatian TV (as well as in the statements and public appearances of our leading politicians) when the key political issues are concerned.<P>

If you can bear to be considered a traitor of the nation, an ally of the enemy, destabilizing factor, enemy, that your acquaintances look at you with mistrust and avoid you, you won't follow directives; you will publicly say what you think.  For how long?<P>  


<hr>
Translated on 5/16/96
<hr>
</FONT><A HREF="/info/students/marko/croind.html"><IMG SRC="/info/students/marko/pictures/home.gif" ALT="HOME" WIDTH=80 HIGHT=40></a>
