<HEAD>
<TITLE>Are All the Croats "Yugonostalgics"?</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
used without permission, for "fair use" only<hr>

<FONT SIZE="+1">

<h1>Sons of One Mother</h1>

<strong><em>by Zlatko Gall</em></strong><P>

<h2>Vijenac, Zagreb, Croatia, March 21 1996</h2>

Are the Croats hopeless yugonostalgics?<P>

It seems they are.<P>

This is not a contradiction in terms, but a still strong need to blow up
our flaccid national ego in desperate competition against Yugoslavia.<P>

State controlled Television systematically presents Belgrade problems as
Croatian successes, while the Serbian poverty is a proof for our "wealth"
and, as the President would say, the heap of performed "miracles".  Wave 
of suicides of pensioners in Belgrade is a clear message to the domestic
retired poverty that it could be worse, although the pension checks are
increasingly late.  Lousy Serbian wages have a similar role in the promotion
of the Croatian wealth, while the ironic remarks about Belgrade criminals
who have forced the citizens underground should be a "compensation" for
"ruralization" and primitive character of Croatian cities.  Domestic
"mafiocracy" seems tame and harmless when compared with their Belgrade counterparts,
whose showdowns complete the picture of the metropolis from the "wild east"...<P>

Ironic smile, which has been patented by Ljiljana Bunjevac Filipovic and
quickly adopted by all <em>talking heads</em> at the Croatian TV, has
become an unavoidable part of the iconography of the features "from
the other side of the Drina".  Even when those <em>talking heads</em>
are conveying the statements of Serbian opposition leaders and their claims
that the Serbian state TV is under the control of the ruling party.<P>

Of course, state TV is not the only institution which tickles the national skin
with the <em>peep-show</em> of the naked <em>Yugoslavia</em>.  High circulation "global"
weekly [Nacional] dedicates a weekly column written by the capable pen of Pero Zlatar to 
<em>Serbian affairs</em>, the analysis of the Serbian press. <em>Panorama</em>
has Goran Milic, while the national weekly with a global name [Globus] fights
the competition using exotic media safaris to the reservations of our neighbors,
with whom we had been, until recently, united in brotherhood.  True, the starting
premise of the Croatian press is significantly different from that of the Croatian
TV: instead of propaganda, the press is guided by the market.  Hunger for the news
from the other side is obvious.  In accordance with the categories in which
the state and political leadership places its opponents, one should expect that
the denounced "yugonostalgic" and "Serb loving" circles put a lot of effort
in grabbing a lot of media space for their Serbian brothers.  Wrong.  Although
denounced from the very top [by president Tudman] as convinced yugonostalgics
and Serb lovers, <em>Feral Tribune</em> does not offer space to Bokan [Serbian
extremist paramilitary leader] nor to Milic od Macve [Serbian mystical painter,
one of the founders of Serbian proto-fascist movement].  In <em>Feral</em>,
we can usually read about the <em>Serbs from the bottom</em>, dissidents and
opposition members.  Why?  because of significantly different <em>starting premise</em>
of the editorial team: their goal is to subvert the theories about collective guilt
and justice.  Maybe, that's why <em>Feral</em> is deemed dangerous.  Since, an
interview with Bogdan Bogdanovic [Serbian architect, former mayor of Belgrade,
and a harsh critic of Serb policy in Bosnia and Croatia], unlike Bokan's appearance
in <em>Slobodna Dalmacija</em>, doesn't confirm the theories of the domestic "hard-liners".
Those "hard-liners" find the justification for their resurrection of Croatian
fascism and the Poglavnik in all those Bokans and Arkans, Milics and Seseljs...
whom inhabit the foreign media space.  Besides, let's recall which Serb-Croatian
sessions received the most criticizm among the <em>hardcore</em> Croats.
Our leader smiling to the cameras in the company of infamous Slobo[dan Milosevic,
Serbian president]?  Friendly meetings of Mate Granic and Milan Milutinovic
[Croatian and Yugoslav foreign ministers]?  The exchange of <em>consular offices</em>
between Belgrade and Zagreb...?  No.  The criticism was reserved for the meeting
of Serbian and Croatian intellectuals (or "intellectuals", in doesn't matter)
in <em>Mimara</em> and the dilemmas regarding the visits of Serbian artists.
The thinking is clear: Bokan - yes, Balasevic [popular Serbian singer, active in
the peace movement] - no.  Since the former one is the archetypal Serb at whom
one looks over a rifle aim in an execution squad, and the latter one a harmless
singing reminder of the <em>better past</em> or the more bearable and more tolerant 
future.  Take your pick.<P>

Is it surprising that the recent sport success of the Croatian female handball team
- mostly thanks to Tonci Vrdoljak [Croatian Olympic Committee president, remarkable
because of his racist remarks] who is obviously trying to position himself for
a political <em>come back</em> - and the victory against the Yugoslav team was
turned into a political circus?  Victory by seventeen goals, according to the Sport 
Billy from the Croatian Olympic Committee and the back up media team, wasn't simply
a good sport result which would take our cats to the high society, but the
showdown with the greater Serbian policy, revenge for the crimes committed in Croatia,
and the proof of the Croatian genetic supremacy over "boneheads".  Besides,
no one bothered to hide that, and even the moderate commentator of <em>Slobodna 
dalmacija</em> wrote that the match in Hungary was politicized with a reason,
mentioning somewhere in his text that "the primary purpose of matches is 
sport competition" (sic!).<P>

Tonci Vrdoljak and his henchmen from the Croatian Olympic Committee obviously
turned upside down all the tenets of the Olympic movement which they were supposed to
promote and defend by putting sport in the service of politics. (...)<P>

Still all that media picking through the dirty laundry of our unrecognized
neighbors [Federal Republic of Yugoslavia wasn't recognized by most
major world powers at the time] has one unfortunate side effect: it provides
undeniable proof of the similarities between us.  True, Serbs were more efficient
in attacks on Soros' <em>Open Society Fund</em>, but the attacks at the "sponsors
of anti-Croatianism" which repeatedly come from the Croatian and HDZ [ruling 
party in Croatia] leadership are almost identical.  Serbia started its campaign 
against Soros as a CIA agent and a traitorous benefactor whose gifts stink to
the heaven, by declining the badly needed dollars invested into computers and
education.  Croatia still lags behind "the trend", and Vokic's [Croatian minister
for education] rejection of computers donated to domestic schools is probably
the first indicator of "the harder course".<P>

Demonization of the West, fear of the real integration into European norms of
civilized behavior, mass production of domestic and foreign enemies, use of
Croatian TV as a party propaganda machine, relationship with the Hague Tribunal
for war crimes in the former Yugoslavia... conclude the list of touching 
similarities.  After all, even the activism of Bakovic's [Croatian hard line Catholic
priest (anti-choice, anti-European, pro-war, etc.)] fertility movement has
a counterpart and a "partner" in, who else, Serb Orthodox Church, which, as
faithfully inform the domestic media, is in the middle of a large promotional
campaign which includes round tables with instructive names: <em>Abortion</em>,
<em>Orthodox Marriage</em>...  Claims that  abortion is an evil which had
been introduced from the West are proven by the data about 150,000 legal 
abortions and the catastrophic predictions that "by year 2020, Serbs will have
become a minority in central Serbia".  Sounds familiar?<P>

Sons of the same mother, in primitivism, intolerance, xenophobia, totalitarian
mentality, can not do otherwise.  Everything else is nothing but a rhetoric and a 
cheap political demagoguery.<P>

<hr>

translated on 8/14/96<P>
<hr>
</FONT>
<A HREF="/info/students/marko/croind.html"><IMG SRC="/info/students/marko/pictures/
home.gif" ALT="HOME" WIDTH=80 HIGHT=40></a>
