<title>Krajina Refugees 2 (more recent)</title>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="pictures/frback.jpg">

<IMG SRC="pictures/refpic1g.gif" ALIGN="TOP" WIDTH=480 HIGHT=333><P>

<h2>Contents:</h2>

<ol>
<li><A HREF="#arson">Arson and death plague Croatia</a>, New York Times News Service 9/30/95
<li><A HREF="#lootingrolls"> Krajina looting spree rolls on despite arrests</a>, Reuter 9/29/95
<li><A HREF="#croarrests">Looting arrests: 400</a>, AP 9/27/95
<li><A HREF="#housedestroyed">Croatian government: A third of all houses in Krajina destroyed</a>, Reuter 9/24/95
<li><A HREF="#CROREF"> More burning and looting</a>, VOA 9/21/95
<li><A HREF="#loosehomes">Serbs Set to Lose Homes in Zagreb Land Grab</a>, InterPress Third World News Agency (IPS), 19-Sep-95
<li><A HREF="#indep1"> Zagreb ensures Serbs will never see their homes again</a>, The Independent 9/7/95
<li><A HREF="#indep2">Croatians count toll in a 'clean war'</a>, The Independent, 9/5/95
<li><A HREF="#indep3">Croats burn and kill with a vengeance</a>, The Independent 9/4/95
<li><A HREF="#indep4">Croats slaughter elderly by the dozen</a>, The Independent 9/10/95
<li><A HREF="#indep5">'Christian culture' chugs back into Krajina</a>, The Independent 9/9/95


</ol>
  	   	

<hr>
<FONT SIZE="+2">

<h2><A NAME="arson">ARSON AND DEATH</a> PLAGUE SERBIAN REGION OF CROATIA</h2>

<em>By CHRIS HEDGES<br>
c. 1995 New York Times News Service, 9/30/95</em><P>

   KNIN, Croatia  Nearly two months after Croatian forces drovemore than 120,000 Serbian troops and civilians from the Krajinaregion of Croatia, Serbian villages continue to burn and an averageof four to six Serbian civilians are found dead each day, sayofficials of the United Nations and the European Union.<P>

   The failure by the Croatian government to stem the violence, despite its assurances that the killings and destruction are being carried out by ``renegades,'' has led U.N. officials here to conclude that the attacks are part of a systematic campaign to drive the 3,500 remaining Serbs from the Krajina and prevent those who want to return from coming back.<P>

   ``Since the August offensive, U.N. patrols have documented a systematic campaign of arson, murder and looting by the Croatian military,'' said Alun R. Roberts, the U.N. press officer in Knin.  He said Croatian troops had ``destroyed whole Serb villages, making it impossible for those Serbs who fled to return.<P>

   ``Our U.N. patrols are continuing to find bodies, usually of elderly Serbs, killed in their homes. Despite repeated requests by the U.N. to the Croatian authorities to intervene, they appear to make little effort, and usually do nothing.''<P>

   In an effort to stem the mounting criticism, the Croatian authorities have invited the Serbs who fled to return and the Croatian government said this week that about 370 people had been arrested for looting.<P>

   And the Croatian Parliament has postponed putting a confiscation law into effect, to give Serbs until December to reclaim their property before having it taken over by the Croatian state.<P>

   But much of that property now lies in ruins. Burning houses, including five that were set ablaze Saturday 10 miles northeast of Knin in the village of Strmica, throw jets of flame into the sky.<P>

   Whole villages are charred and gutted, cars sit overturned and stripped on the asphalt, broken furniture lies scattered around the dirt yards and chickens, often the only sign of life, peck and cackle among the ruins.<P>

   ...........<P>

 But U.N. officials said the drive to wipe out Serbian villages was too well organized to be totally haphazard.<P>

    In an internal report published on Sept. 20, officials of the European Community Monitoring Mission said that of 18,232 houses in 240 Serbian villages they had monitored, more than 13,600, or 73 percent, had been completely or partly destroyed.<P>

   ``The Croats have tried over the past few years to distance themselves from the behavior of the Serbs,'' said one European Union monitor, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``But now they are carrying out a campaign of ethnic cleansing as effective, and often as brutal, as that carried out by the Serbs. Only the uniforms are different; the behavior is the same.''<P>

   The killing of elderly Serbs, many of them too weak to flee, has shocked and angered U.N. and European Union monitors here. Many of the victims lived alone in abandoned hamlets, where they would be visited by aid workers bringing food. In recent weeks many have been found dead, usually with a single bullet wound in the head.<P>

   Earlier this month, Croatian special forces made a sweep through the largely deserted Plavno Valley, where some 40 Serbian hamlets lie abandoned or in ruins. U.N. peacekeepers following the sweep found two elderly men dead, one shot in the back of the head and the other with his throat cut. The next day, the United Nations found three more elderly Serbs killed, including a 90-year-old woman.<P>

   ``Evidence of atrocities, an average of six corpses a day, continues to emerge,'' says the latest European Union rights report. ``The corpses, some fresh, some decomposed, are mainly old men. Many have been shot in the back of the head or had throats slit. Others have been mutilated. Isolated pockets of elderly civilians report people gone missing or detained.''<P>

   Only about 100 of the more 120,000 Serbs who fled have returned to the Krajina, and most of those have slipped into the area without official permission, U.N. officials said. Those who try to return through the Croatian government office in Belgrade are rarely given permission, these officials said.<P>

   ``As far as we can see, the Croatian office in Belgrade is quite purposely dysfunctional,'' one European Union official said. ``The object is to keep the Serbs out.''<P>

   The Serbs who remain live in terror, often fleeing to the hills when cars carrying marauding Croats come into their villages.<P>

   ``A few days after the Croats came, I found my 95-year-old father with his throat slashed,'' said Pajic Petar, a Serb who lives in the village of Zorici, about 15 miles north of Knin. ``We buried him with another old man who was murdered. Each day the soldiers come and take more of our animals and our belongings, telling us to shut up or we will die.''<P>

   Looting and arson take place openly in nearly every village. At a gutted Serbian farm Saturday morning, troops from the 72nd Military Police Batallion were trying to push a horse into a trailer. The troops said they would be back in the afternoon to cart away the terra cotta roof tiles.<P>

   Croats in trucks roamed up and down the dirt lanes, parking outside abandoned homes to load sinks, bathroom fixtures, household utensils and farm tools into the back.<P>

   On a hillside outside of Popovici, five miles south of Knin, 89-year-old Djuka Popovic stood timidly near a small one-story stone house. Like most of the elderly Serbs here, she is being stripped of her belongings and her farm animals.<P>

   ``The soldiers force their way into my home and steal things,'' she said. ``They took my television, my clock and my smoked hams. I dread every noise. I dread the sound of the cars and the trucks coming into our village. And I dread the night, when I lie alone inmy house and wonder if I will be here in the morning.''<P>

<hr>

<h2><a NAME="lootingrolls"> Krajina looting</a> spree rolls on despite arrests</h2>
<h5> Fri, 29 Sep 1995</h5>

  	  	
	 KNIN, Croatia (Reuter) - Croatian soldiers and civilians are carrying out a wave of house-burning, looting and killing on former Serb properties in Croatia's recaptured Krajina region, U.N. officials and eyewitnesses said Friday.<P>
  
	 Croatian authorities, under U.N. pressure, have reported arresting 370 people, including some soldiers, for looting and burning houses. But the United Nations said the rampage for war booty by the victors was continuing.  <P>

	 ``We welcome the arrests but there's still far too little sign of effective policing of these areas,'' Alun Roberts, the spokesman at the U.N. Sector South peacekeeping operation based in the Krajina's remote main city of Knin, told Reuters.  <P>

	 ``The few old people left behind in these areas are reporting, in a consistent pattern, harassment and looting.  <P>

	 ``U.N. patrols are reporting the looting to be by persons in Croatian military uniform or by people in civilian clothes often carrying rifles or sidearms,'' Roberts said.  <P>

	 The road from the edge of the Krajina at Karlovac, 20 miles south of Zagreb, to Knin, some 150 miles south of the Croatian capital, is a wasteland of burned-out houses, and aimless abandoned farm animals.  <P>

	 Serb villages in the hills around Knin are practically deserted. Some elderly Serbs who remain said they had seen Croatian soldiers looting houses before burning them.  <P>

	 The United Nations and the United States have warned Croatia it must respect the rights of Serb civilians if it expects to get financial help for postwar reconstruction in the republic.  <P>

	 This correspondent saw small groups of armed men in Croatian army camouflage gear driving into the deserted Serb villages in the Plavno Valley north of Knin in private cars Thursday.  <P>

	 Some of these men went into abandoned Serb houses and emerged with sacks of objects. Asked what they were doing, one soldier replied: ``Looking for somebody. Be careful. You could get lost around here.''  <P>

	 Some abandoned houses had clearly been ransacked. Drawers and cupboards had been emptied, their contents strewn on the floor. Nothing valuable was left.  <P>

	 The authorities had sent men with trucks to round up stray livestock. This reporter saw one of the trucks in the Plavno Valley being loaded not only with horses and cows but also with furniture.  <P>

	 Roberts said that since the Croatian Army captured the area and crushed a five-year-old Serb rebellion Aug. 5, the U.N. peacekeepers had recorded over 120 killings of civilians.  <P>

	 ``The majority were of elderly (Serbs) living in isolated hamlets. Several of these bodies were shot at close range. In these instances on several occasions U.N. soldiers observed Croatian military personnel in the vicinity,'' he said.  <P>

	 ``Over the past two weeks we've seen further examples of looting of houses in hamlets where elderly people are living. ``We're now seeing people who they describe as dressed in military uniform revisiting the locations and removing bathtubs, kitchen appliances and the remaining furniture.  ``Through these actions, the U.N. Sector South is very much aware that the intention is to prevent any means of existence or return,'' Roberts said.  <P>

	 The crime wave resembles what happened in northern Bosnia in 1992, when Croat and Muslim homes were looted and torched by marauding Serb forces who seized the area and carried out a wave of ``ethnic cleansing'' in a bid to make it purely Serb.

<hr>

<h2> <a NAME="croarrests">Croatia Looting Arrests: 400</a></h2>   
<h5> Wed, 27 Sep 1995</h5>               
                                                  
  	  	
	ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) -- More than 400 people, including dozens of soldiers, have been arrested in Croatia on charges of looting and burning down houses of fleeing ethnic Serbs, U.N. officials said Wednesday. <P>

.....<P>

	The arrests, which the United Nations said took place in recent days, are the first action by Croatian authorities against suspected looters. The government initially denied that any Serb homes had been looted or burned.  <P>

	Those detained include 70 policemen, 65 soldiers and 260 civilians, U.N. spokesman Chris Gunness said. Thirty soldiers were formally charged with looting and burning property, he said.  <P>

	``We are delighted that the Croatian authorities are now admitting that such events took place despite initial strong denials by senior figures including (Croatian) President Franjo Tudjman,'' Gunness said.  <P>

	Despite the arrests, looting and the burning of property continued Wednesday, almost two months after fighting stopped, Gunness said.  <P>

	``We have been informed by Croat police of their great concern that looting continues in Krajina, but they claim that with fighting ongoing in Bosnia they have insufficient men to curb excesses in Krajina,'' he said.  <P>

	On Monday, U.N. observers reported seeing uniformed Croatian soldiers stealing from Serb houses in the village of Komcarev Kraj, in southern Croatia.  <P>

	Gunness also said that the United Nations was watching carefully to see if Croat authorities will locate and charge those responsible for the murder of Serb civilians during the Croat blitz.  <P>

	``We found well over 100 bodies, dozens of which were civilians,  and a number of mass graves after the military action. People in   civilian clothes with bullets in the back of their heads were among those discovered,'' Gunness said. <P>
                                  
	No Croatian officials were available to comment on the arrests and the reports of continued crimes against Serb property.  <P>
  	   	



<hr>

<h2> <a NAME="housedestroyed">A third of all</a> Krajina houses destroyed - minister</h2>
<h5>Sun, 24 Sep 1995</h5>

  	  	
	 ZAGREB, Croatia (Reuter) - One third of all housing in Croatia's Krajina region, held by rebel Serbs from 1991 until last month, has been destroyed, a Croatian minister said Sunday. <P> 

	 Much of the other two-thirds had suffered damage, but could be repaired, Development and Reconstruction Minister Jure Radic told the daily Vjesnik.  <P>

	.......... <P>

	 Radic conceded there had been some looting and pillaging after the Croat victory. Isolated looting incidents were still going on as Croatian authorities struggled to reimpose order in the largely deserted region, he said.<P>
  
	 ``I myself saw things being stolen, such as refrigerators and radiators, something our government strongly condemns,'' he said. ``In those places where (Croat) people have already gone back, such problems are almost non-existent.''  <P>

	 Independent eyewitnesses have accused first the Serbs and then the Croats of destroying the homes and stealing movable property of the rival ethnic group to ensure it can never return to dispute control of the region.  <P>

	 Reporters visiting Krajina have found it a wasteland of destroyed villages with burned-out houses, abandoned farms and scattered livestock.  <P>

	 Radic said that of the 123,000 houses and flats in Krajina, which forms an arc along the underside of Croatia's boomerang shape, 35 percent were ruined beyond repair.  <P>

	 He said Serb property would remain in the hands of the Croatian state until a final peace settlement between the warring parties had been reached.  <P>

