<HEAD>
<TITLE>Jovanka and Dorde</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<FONT SIZE="+1">

<center><h1>Jovanka, 71 and Dorde, 68</h1></center>
<em>December 1994<br>
Nevesinje, Bosnia-Hercegovina</em><P>

<IMG SRC="http://www.sailing.org/Yugoslavia/peopref2.gif" ALT="Jovanka's picture"><P><hr><P>

Abruptly expelled from Mostar one night, Jovanka and Dorde walked 25 kilometers through the rain, scared and lugging two suitcases.  "I even left behind my dentures," said Dorde, who has worn a single pair of rubber boots, donated almost three years ago, summer and winter.  The elderly siblings now live in the tiny room of an acquaintance's house.  They can make coffee with a small heating plate, but beg neighbors to bake bread for them.  Jovanka's husband died last year, and she worries about her only child, a Serb fighting against the predominantly Muslim Bosnian army.  "He only writes, 'I'm fine, I'm healthy,' the same thing my husband wrote," Jovanka says, tearfully trailing off into silence.  Both Jovanka, who worked in a tobacco factory, and Dorde, who worked in an aircraft factory, survived concentration camps as children.  "Now we suffer again as old people," said Dorde philosophically; like his sister, he still hopes and dreams of returning to Mostar.  "Who hasn't had liberty taken away from him, doesn't know what liberty is."<P>

<hr>

