<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Slobodan and Marta</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<FONT SIZE="+1">

<center><h1>Slobodan, 48; Marta, 51; Darko, 18 and Sinisa, 17</h1></center>
<em>February 1995<br>
Titel, Serbia</em><P>

<IMG SRC="http://www.sailing.org/Yugoslavia/peopref6.gif" ALT="Slobodan's picture" WiDTH=440 HIGHT=297><P><hr><P>

Slobodan and his family have spent the last six months in a tiny hotel room crammed with a TV, tables and a bunk bed.  Their prize possession is a used washing machine which they bought for US$100 before their savings ran out.  Memories of their hometown, Slavonski Brod, haunt them.  "My job in (Croat-held) Slavonski Brod was to pick up dead bodies from the street, even during heavy bombardments," said Slobodan, a Serb truck driver whose wife Marta is a Croat.  "A neighbor - a good friend - used to aim shoulder-launched grenades at us from his apartment window.  It was funny because all the (Serb) grenades were coming from the other direction (and he didn't fool us).  Once a genade landed in our kitchen."  After six months of fighting, Slobodan and his family escaped.  Carrying a few unobtrusive handbags, the family caught a 6a.m. train to Zagreb with the help of a friend.  But Slobodan didn't feel safe in Croatia.  So the family moved to Serbia, where marta feels uneasy.  Both parents are deeply worried about the future of their draft-age-sons.  "We have no plans for the future," says marta, who spends a lot of time knitting, "but at least there's no war here."<P>

<hr>

<a HREF="iocc.html">Back</a><p>

