<HEAD>
<TITLE>Milena and Bojana</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<FONT SIZE="+1">

<center><h1>Milena, 38 and Bojana, 11</h1></center>
<em>February 1995<br>
Sremska Kamenica, Serbia</em><P>

<IMG SRC="http://www.sailing.org/Yugoslavia/peopref3.gif" ALT="Milena's picture"><P><hr><P>

Refugees from Sarajevo, Milena and her two children live in the dorm-like room of a children's institution.  The youngest child - Bojana - has a malignant brain tumor.  "I need place to stay with a telephone, or an apartment near a hospital in case of an emergency," Milena pleaded.  She anxiously pulled out Bojana's medical records, waiting until her daughter - poised and bored looking - wandered out of the room.  A former store clerk, Milena arrived in Serbia eleven days after fighting began.  Her husband, an accountant and car mechanic, staid behind.  Their home, savings, and belongings are gone, Milena said.  She opened a flimsy shoebox of photographs - all that is left from Sarajevo.  Blakc-and-white pictures of a relative's grim winter funeral sent her into a new bout of silent weeping.  "How can I take care of my daughter living like this?"<P>

<hr>

