<HEAD>
<TITLE>Nada and Dragan</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<FONT SIZE="+1">

<center><h1>Nada, 57 and Dragan, 37</h1></center>
<em>October 1994<br>
Kljuc, Bosnia-Hercegovina</em><P>

<IMG SRC="http://www.sailing.org/Yugoslavia/peopref5.gif" ALT="Nadas's picture" HIGHT=312 WIDTH=421><P><hr><P>

The deal looked simple:  as Serbs, Nada and her husband would exchange their furnished house in the Muslim-held town of Zenica, for the furnished house of a Muslim family in the Serb-held town of Kljuc.  But when Nada and her family arrived in Kljuc in early 1994, they found only one bed.  "There were supposed to be 150 pieces of furniture," complained Nada bitterly, accusing the wife of the other family, a Serb married to a Muslim - of selling the furniture.  "Plus a neighbor has taken the garden, and a girl lives on the ground floor."  With no savings left, Nada and her family depend on humanitarien aid and help from relatives.  Nada's 65-year-old husband pushes a wheelbarrow to the forest to collect firewood.  Their son Dragan, an architect who blinded himself during a suicide attempt, is unable to work.  But life is easier now, nada said.  She has seen bread in Kljuc's garbage bins four times.  In Zenica Nada's family had to keep their cow in a shed with no door to prevent stealing.  One morning, all that was left of their ten chicken were heads.  "We left Zenica illegaly after a bomb was thrown in our garden," explained Dragan, who speaks excellent English.  "Without money we couldn't have gone."<P>

<hr>

<a HREF="iocc.html">Back</a><p>

