<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Mira, Natasa and Momcilo</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<FONT SIZE="+1">

<center><h1>Mira, 30; Natasa, 6; and Momcilo, 3</h1></center>
<em>June 1995<br>
Banja Koviljaca, Serbia</em><P>

<IMG SRC="http://www.sailing.org/Yugoslavia/peopref1.gif" ALT="Mira's picture"><P><hr><P>

Mira and her children left war-torn Croatia in 1991 and fled to Belgrade, where they shared a house with several other families.  In July 1992, Mira decided to return home with her then 2-month-old baby confident fighting in western Slavonia (a United Nations Protected Area) was over.  "We lived just fine," said Mira, whose house was on the front line of the divided town of Pakrac.  "There was no shooting, and it was peaceful."  On the morning of May 1, an exploding grenade awakened the family.  Mira and her family, which by then included her wounded husband, ran to the cellar in their pajamas.  They hid for two days before fleeing by car to a nearby village.  "My little son was saying, 'Don't be afraid, it will pass'," said Mira, breaking into tears at the memory.  The family entered Serbia as refugees for the second time in June 1995.  Mira, a nurse, doesn't know how they will live - her husband, a skilled laborer, may be permanently disabled.  "I feel like I wasted three years of my life (in Pakrac).  All that pain for nothing," Mira said.  "If somebody had told me (war) was going to happen five years ago, I would have said they were crazy."<P>

<hr>

<a HREF="iocc.html">Back</a><p>

