<HEAD>
<TITLE>Croatia Cannot be a Part of the Balkans</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
used without permission, for "fair use" only<hr>
<FONT SIZE="+1">


<h1>CROATIA CANNOT BE A PART OF THE BALKANS</h1>

<em><strong>A. Hauswitschka</em></strong><P>

<h2> Vjesnik, Zagreb, Croatia, 5/24/96, page 5.</h2>

Dubrovnik, 23 May - "South-eastern Europe in the 20th
Century" was the theme of the international symposium which
was organised by Hrvatska Matica Iseljenika (Croatian
Homeland Foundation) and the Croatian Information Centre,
which began on Wednesday at the `Lapad' hotel in Dubrovnik.
The symposium will continue till Saturday, consisting of 25
lectures, reports from Croatia, Macedonia, Bosnia
Herzegovina, Great Britain, Bulgaria, Hungary, Switzerland,
Canada, United States, Belgium, Chile, Belja Tonovic will
speak about Croatians in Vojvodina and Doris Pack about the
future of the Former Yugoslavia.<P>

The symposium will bring forward all former aspirations of
the Croatian people. The aim is to point out that Croatia
does not form apart of the Balkans. The symposium was opened
by Mr Ante Beljo, president of Hrvatska Matica Iseljenika.
Mr Stjepan Cosic spoke about the history of Dubrovnik. Mr
Mladen Klemencic spoke about the political geography of
Croatia, Bosnia Herzegovina and South-eastern Europe and
emphasised that the name `South-eastern Europe' was a better
term for the region, and should replace the negative term
currently used, that is `Balkan'.<P>

In the 1994 edition of Encyclopaedia Britanica states that
the political region encompasses Albania, Romania, Slovenia,
Bosnia Herzegovina, Croatia, Macedonia, Greece, Bulgaria,
Moldavia, Serbia and Montenegro. For the people and
countries which are apart of this region, according to the
encyclopaedia "are incapable to mutually agree or work
together, there is a tendency for local authorities to
misuse power as soon as the central authority weakens, they
try to influence foreign powers, and accept with great
difficulty concepts which are brought about by another
political or community context". In short, being apart of
the Balkans means being apart of the backward part of
Europe.<P>

According to Mr Klemencic Croatia is of course very
frustrated with the fact that Croatia has never accepted
anything associated with Yugoslavia, but according to
Western European views we are apart of the Balkans. On
Wednesday Dr Tereza Ganza-Aras said that in relation to the
theme, "Dalmatia is between Italian Irredentism and Greater
serbianism."<P>

<hr>
</FONT>
