<HEAD>
<TITLE>Attack on Croatian Helsinki Committee regarding round table on Serbs in Croatia</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
used without permission, for "fair use" only<hr>
<FONT SIZE="+1">




<h1>FOR CICAK AND BANAC THE WAR IS A 
CONSEQUENCE OF
A MISUNDERSTANDING</h1>

<em><strong>by Josip Vricko</em></strong><P>

<h2>Vjesnik(Zagreb), Croatia, Saturday, May 25 1996, Front page</h2>

<strong>THE MESSAGE THAT THERE SHOULD BE NO VICTIMS NOR 
VICTORS IS BEING SENT TO THE POTENTIAL PEACEMAKER-
PARTICIPANTS AT THE ROUND TABLE ABOUT THE SERBS IN 
CROATIA BY THE LEADING DUET OF  HUMAN RIGHTS 
DEFENDERS  IN THE NAME OF THE CROATIAN HELSINKI 
COMMITTEE</strong><P>

The Croatian Helsinki Committee for Human Rights(HHO) -- 
admittedly not in complete coordination with the newly 
revampirized demands for autonomy in Eastern Slavonia -- is 
announcing a round table scheduled for 20-21 June under a 
somewhat poetic title  The Serbs in Croatia: Yesterday, Today 
and Tomorrow.   After the HHO, headed by I.Z.Cicak, who is 
specially known in this area, succeeded  in  defending  the so-
called Serb apartments in Croatia(while at the same time, the 
Croats, expelled by the Serbs, suffered in refugee camps), that is, 
after he took care of the Serb today, well, he is already thinking 
of the Serb tomorrow.  The Serb yesterday, or, in the HHO 
context, the Serb-Croat yesterday, is what Cicak-Banac, the 
already famous duet of defenders of Serb rights, is treating in a 
way that could be reduced, perhaps as their planned round 
table, to a (draft) title of  Bruddah, who done set us quarreling.<P> 

	And we were set quarreling, according to the HHO, by too 
soft a word.  That is, as the two signers of an invitation to some 
200 domestic and foreign invitees claim (when the Serb tomorrow 
is in question, nothing is too expensive), the lack of dialogue in 
the prior two Yugoslavias and the Independent State of Croatia 
led to war.  We hated each other for some seventy or so years 
and then, normally, according to Cicak and Banac, hatred 
escalated into war.  How often and and why during the said 
period the Serbs let grow (Chetnik) beards and put on  (Chetnik) 
fur hats is the question that the round table of Cicak and Banac 
will not take up.  And why should it when this war, (too), is a 
consequence of a misunderstanding, whose causes, the two of 
them say in unison, have not been removeb  by the quieting 
down of the war.   But, behold, in two days, the HHO will remove 
all misunderstandings.  There must not be any victims or victors 
is the message of the leading duet of human rights  defenders to 
the numerous (potential) peacemakers.  True, say they,  we shall 
also consider the sources of the conflict,  but this  also  already 
suggests that this will be en passant, while the  conflict,  that is 
the four-year Serb Chetniking in Croatia -- the only proper term 
for wat happened, will not be mentioned at Cicak s and Banac s 
(round) table.  There is no aggression, there are no (Croata) 
victims, let us reconcile ourselves, so that we might live happily 
until the end of our lives, Really,  bruddah, who done set us 
quarreling!? <P>

	The HHO people, of course, have the answer.  The 
nationalist leaders are guilty, and all because, they claim,  to 
open the possibility of creating nationally homogeneous states 
and ethnic cleansing.   Therefore, Cicak and Banac remind us, 
before they definitely reconcile us with the Serbs, both Franjo 
Tudjman and Slobodan Milosevic are guilty.  The duet with olive 
branches, however, is inviting only one of the accused, Dr. 
Tudjman, but not Comrade Milosevic.  He will probably be 
represented, according to the scenario of the HHO, by Aleksa 
Djilas, a particularly agreeable person for this sort of so-called 
peace meetings, or, perhaps, by General Djoko Jovanic -- this 
time, unlike in the good old days without Jovanka Budisavljevic 
Broz, who, too (it is surprizing the Cicak and Banac overlooked 
this), these days expresses a wish to make peace with the Croats.<P>

<hr><P>
							
							

Translated by: CHC for Human Rights<P>

