<TITLE>Young Ustasha tells it as it is</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
used without permission, for "fair use" only<hr>

<FONT SIZE="+1">

<h1>Reply to Partisan Ivan Fumic</h1>

<strong>reprinted from <em>Vjesnik</em></strong><P>

<strong><em>by Velimir Bujanec, politics major and public relations officer of the Croatian Liberation Movement</em></strong><P>

<h2><a HREF="/info/students/marko/globus2.html">Nezavisna Drzava Hrvatska</a>, Zagreb, Croatia, March 1996</h2>

Croatian political daily published on Saturday, January 13, in the readers response column, reaction of gentleman-comrade <strong>Ivan Fumic</strong>, a man who gives himself a title of the "President of the Association of the Antifascist fighters of Croatia."  Obviously, Mr. Fumic forgot to put the word "Socialist" in front of "Republic Croatia" in his letter, a word which has  proudly adorned his organization during the past decades.  The mentioned letter, by the way totally unfounded, was given an interesting title ("To build the future, but with the awareness of the past"), which is the only part of the text I can agree with, since when I think about the Communists, the first thing that comes to mind is their intransigency, and after that their ignorance; consequently it is obvious that the future cannot be built by partisan ignoramuses but only by someone else.<P>

I am not surprised that the aforementioned gentlemen wants to deny me a right to publish my articles on the pages of <em>Vjesnik</em>, but Fumic has forgotten that this <em>Vjesnik</em> is not the old "red" <strong><em>Vjesnik</em></strong> which was controlled by bolseviks and the Belgrade servants; consequently that wish of his, as well as other desperate pleas for the return of Yugo-communist practice in the Croatian media space will not receive a positive reply.  True, I myself am also not happy with the personnel policy in quite a few media outlets, and put my hope in the future in which the communist elements and their deformed character will be pushed away from the political scene.<P>

The law about information policy is the one which in this case enables me to respond, and the hope for a ban expressed by the "antifascist" to whom I address this letter is only one among many proofs that the communists do not respect the rule of law and have a hard time with the changes which happened in 1990; it also demonstrates that deep in their rotten souls one can still find nostalgia for something obsolete.<P>

The boss of the remnants of the partisan groups in Croatia which have been lately springing up in Zagreb and elsewhere in Croatia probably studied history from partisan history books; consequently I'm not surprised that in his stupidity he wants to sell his huge ignorance for mine.  I am not writing this reply because of various "Fumic's" who are anyway leaving the scene (together with various communist plaques and war memorials [most of memorials to the World War II victims and antifascist fighters have been dismantled or destroyed]) but also because of Croatian patriots from the time of the <strong>Independent State of Croatia </strong>[<a HREF="http://www.VisionInc.com/YU/Rat/atlas/atlas-index.html">NDH</a>, Croatian fascist puppet state during World War II] who deserve every respect instead of slander like that expressed in the letter of the "antifascist President".  In the same manner, Fumic would spit on todays Croatian bojovniks [warriors] had not the Croatian state, God forbid, survived.  I want to ask Fumic why he was silent in <strong>1991 and '92</strong> and why he didn't dare write similar offenses on the expense of <strong>NDH, Poglavnik [Ustashe leader, roughly corresponds to Nazi title fuhrer], and Ustashe movement</strong> on the pages of the Croatian press during the Serbo-chetnik aggression against Croatia?  At that time, the supporters of communist tyranny were silent in their fear and waited with excitement to see if the Serb aggression would succeed and whether their "Yugoslavia" would come back.  Taking into account that their wishes didn't come through, they skillfully transformed themselves into so called "Croatian antifascists" and under that name they today promote their activities against the Croat People and especially Croat nationalists.<P>

Every normal person understands that the Partisan bandits who rose in <strong>1941</strong> against the will of the Croatian people who greeted with [happy] tears in eyes the fall of "Yugoslavia" and the establishment of NDH, were Yugoslav criminals.  Their groups were made mostly of Serbs and Croat scum and before <strong>1943</strong> they hardly carried out any significant military actions but were preoccupied with small scale looting, ambushes, rapes and other dishonorable and dirty deeds.  None of those outlaws, especially those who today appear in the Croatian media, even considered the idea of the independent and free Croatia; one cannot consider some meeting which took place in a forest (ZAVNOH [partisan conference at which the "foundations of post-war Croatia" were established]) to be the start of the life of the Croatian independent state, when in history that shameful ZAVNOH is subordinate to AVNOJ [partisan conference which made the decision about federal structure of the post-war communist Yugoslav state], which is the embodiment of everything for which the Croatian traitors fought.<P>

In the Independent State of Croatia, nobody suffered unless he or she was the enemy of the state.  That means that in <a HREF="http://sunset.backbone.olemiss.edu/~mirjana/rat/jasenovac/jasenovac-INDEX.html"><strong>Jasenovac</strong></a> and even in Jadovno [Ustashe run concentration camps] the inmates were mostly the enemies of the state and criminals.  I don't deny the fact that <strong>NDH</strong> was an <strong>ally of Germany, Italy and Japan</strong> at the time [during World War II], but I also want to emphasize that it is questionable whether the NDH leadership had a choice when one knows that other states were openly supporting the re-establishment of "Yugoslavia".  The state [NDH] was in war and had its allies and this is a question about which history, only after a revision, can give its final judgment.  Ivan Fumic doesn't understand that process and nobody expects him to do so, but I ask from him to carefully think before he puts his stupidities on paper in the future.<P>

Partisan outlaws managed to re-establish the horrendous yugo-entity with their crimes and collaboration with the Chetniks of <a HREF="http://www.igc.apc.org/balkans/draza.html"><strong>Draza Mihajlovic</strong></a> [Chetniks were a Serb royalist resistance army; for a brief time in 1941 they fought with Partisans against Germans; however, soon afterwards, the uprising in Serbia was crushed and, since then, the Chetniks had sporadically fought against and collaborated with Germans, Italians and Ustashe and waged a bloody civil war against Partisans]; its foundations were built on the bones of hundreds of thousands of Croats.  After the most recent destruction of Yugoslavia and establishment of the independent Croatia, the conditions are finally ripe to bring to justice all those Yugo-butchers whose arms are covered with Croatian blood all the way to their elbows.  Only after the trial to still living communist criminals (which is also the practice in other post-communist countries) it is possible to consider gradual reconciliation.  Because the victim has to be the one to extend the hand of reconciliation, and not the criminal, although this is not happening in Croatia, although I can say that Fumic is right when he says that I am against that sort of reconciliation.<P>

Finally, Mr. Fumic, <a HREF="http://cypress.mcsr.olemiss.edu/~eesrdan/ndh/ndh-INDEX.html">Ustashe </a> Movement was a national liberation movement which wasn't fascist but only Croatian and nationalist.  In <strong>1991</strong> in <strong>Patriotic War</strong> Croatian young men proudly displayed on their uniforms Ustashe insignia, because <strong><em>"U"</em></strong> [Ustashe equivalent of swastika] in Croatia stands for freedom, happiness and wellbeing.  While entering the villages which we liberated from the Serb aggressor we sang <strong>"Evo zore, evo dana..."</strong>, [Ustashe song celebrating WWII war criminals Francetic and Boban] and I want to ask whether that is "fascism".  Still, Fumic has no way of knowing that, because he hasn't seen the front in the 90's, and in the previous war he was on the other side, among "comrades".

With respect,<P>

<center>
<h2>ZA DOM SPREMNI!</h2>
</center><P>    

<hr>

Translated on May 27 1996<P>

