<title>Graduate Power System Education at Northeastern University</title>

<h1>Graduate Power System Education at Northeastern University</h1>
<hr>

Guiding principles behind power system education at Northeastern University
 include the following:
<ul>
<li> The main emphasis in our graduate courses is on the development of
        thorough understanding of power system phenomena  on both the
        physical
       and the  analytical level.
<li>Realizing the importance of team-work in modern and future utilities 
       our goal is to make   students  capable of communicating with 
       co-workers in other specialties, with equipment manufacturers and with  
       service providers.  Our curriculum is sufficiently broad
       to include  solid foundations in system theory, control,
       digital signal processing, communication and engineering
       mathematics. We insist on a detailed understanding of  important
       problems in these  areas, as a superficial  acquaintance
       with  topics can not prepare students for independent and creative
       decision
       making.
<li>  With the ever increasing importance of computing facilities in power
       systems, it is no longer enough to study the analytical impact of 
       computers in a few dedicated courses. We  integrate computer based
        methodologies in all our courses,  and rely on excellent computing
      facilities available in the Electrical and Computer Engineering
       Department to support  our educational agenda.
<li>  Given the increasing role of analytical software in power engineering
       operation,  our courses will utilize both 
       professional packages, and tools
       that offer efficient  instruction.  
       Software packages used in the curriculum  include 
       EPRI programs (EMTP, EMSTP, SSSP, IPFLOW, VSTAB etc.) 
       that our students are likely
       to use in their professional activities. For easy prototyping and 
       classroom case studies we plan to use software that has been proven in
       educational tasks (e.g. Matlab, Maple), as well as 
       production grade tools (Saber).   
<li>  One of the  goals of the MS program is to quickly 
           compensate for possible deficiencies in
        power system undergraduate education (e.g 
       in-depth  study of symmetric components and power apparatus
        modeling).
</ul>

<h2>Coursework</h2>

In this section we list graduate power engineering courses
sorted according to the requirements of the MS curriculum.
In the MS program we plan for a total of 
44 quarter-hours (QH), 
thus making the course load between 9 and 11
courses (4 QH each).
PhD students are expected to take additional courses outside their areas
of concentration.

<h3>Required Core Courses</h3>
Number      Name                                           Credits<p> 
ECE 3211    Math Methods in Electrical Engineering I       4<p>
ECE 3221    Linear Systems Analysis                        4 <p>
ECE 3241    Applied Probability and Stochastic Processes   4<p>


<h3>Required Subject Area</h3>  
 
Number      Name 		                           Credits <p>
ECE 3308\9  Electric Machinery Theory  II\III              4   <p>
ECE 3432    Power System Operation and Control             4 <p>
ECE 3433    Power Electronics                              4 <p>

 
<h3>Elective Subject Area  Courses</h3>

Number      Name                                           Credits <p>
ECE 3301\2  Power Circuit Analysis                         4 <p>
ECE 3305\6  Computational  Methods in Power Systems I\II   2+2  <p> 
ECE 3404    Motion Control with DC Motor Drives            2   <p>
ECE 3407    Motion Control with  AC Motor Drives           2   <p>
ECE 3412    Power System Planning                          4 <p>
ECE 3415    Power System Protection                        2 <p>
ECE 3416    Electromagnetic Power System Transients        2  <p>
ECE 3417    Analysis of Equipment Failure                  2 <p>
ECE 3424    Electromechanical Power System Dynamics        2<p>
ECE 3381    Classical Control Theory                       4  <p>
ECE 3371    Linear Optimal Control Theory                  4<p>
ECE 3321    Digital Signal Processing                      4<p>
ECE 3341    Electromagnetic Theory I                       4 <p>
ECE 3344    Electromagnetic Theory II                      4<p>
