<h2><a name="ljiljan"><IMG ALT="Ljiljan" SRC="ljiljan.gif" ALIGN=BOTTOM></a></h2>  Ljiljan was founded in 1990, immediately before the first post-Communist elections in Bosnia-Hercegovina.  It was a paper of the SDA [Stranka Demokratske Akcije, Democratic Action Party], the main party representing Muslims in Bosnia-Hercegovina.  It was originally named <em>Muslimanski Glas</em> [Muslim Voice], to be later renamed and turned into an independent weekly.  However, its editorial line still closely follows the SDA's policy. <em>Ljiljan</em> was the first weekly from fromer Yugoslavia available <A HREF="http://www.ljiljan.com/tljiljan.html">on the WWW</a>.  The majority of the articles is in Bosnian, with a small number translated to English. NOTE: The site is currently unavailable (12/18/96).<p>

<ul>
<li><A HREF="ljiljan1.html">Ancient Roots of the Bosniac Nation</a>: a letter to the editor, 7/12/95
<li><A HREF="ljiljan6.html">Honest People, Dishonest Politicians</a>: Turkey finds is Islamic soul, 3/27/96<IMG ALT="new" SRC="star.gif">
<li><a HREF="ljiljan4.html">Exodus from Bosniak Apartments</a>, why are Serbs leaving Sarajevo?, 2/21/96
<li><A HREF="ljiljan2.html">Soros' Orphans</a>: George Soros promotes Serbian aggressors, 2/28/96
<li><A HREF="ljiljan3.html">What Happened in Podgorelica, Near Fojnica, was our Big Mistake</a>: interview with Alija Izetbegovic, Bosnian president, 3/27/96
<li><A HREF="ljiljan5.html">Neo-communists are Trying to Fool Voters</a>: SDA election platform, 6/26/96
<li><A HREF="ljiljan7.html">Bosnian Petrovac will be Renamed!</a>: Ljiljan journalist writes about the plans to settle 20,000 Bosniaks (Bosnian Muslims) from other parts of Bosnia in the municipality which had 15,500 inhabitants before the war (75% of them Serbs), 9/25/96<IMG ALT="new" SRC="star.gif">

</ul><P>

English translation of two undated articles from Ljiljan<A HREF="http://wings.buffalo.edu/11/student-life/sa/muslim/news/ljiljan.1" >Serbian Nationalists and Islam; Serbian Hireling in the American Congress</A><P>

<h2><a name="froslo">Front Slobode</a></h2>  Front Slobode, Tuzla<p>


Front Slobode is an independent informative two-weekly publication from Tuzla.  It has a long tradition.  Before the Bosnian war it was patronized by the then Union of Communists which used it as a party bulletin.  The privatization of 1993 brought new people and considerable changes in editorial policy.  <strong>Front Slobode</strong> dissociated itself from the current ruling party, the largest Bosnian Muslim party, SDA, and became an independent paper with an outspoken oppositional approach towards the ruling structures in Bosnia-Hercegovina. <strong>Front Slobode</strong> stands for a peaceful co-existence between different ethnic groups in Bosnia-Hercegovina.(from <a HREF="http://MediaFilter.org/MFF/PN.html">Press Now</a>)<P>
<ul>
<li>Tuzla:<A HREF = "froslo1.html">Are There Any Pressures on Citizens of Serb Nationality? </A>, 8/11/95</LI>
