<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Turkey and Bosnia</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

used without permission, for "fair use" only<hr>

<FONT SIZE="+1">
<h1>Honest People, Dishonest Politicians</h1>

<strong><em>by Fahira Fejzic</em></strong><P>

<h2>Ljiljan, Sarajevo-Ljubljana, Bosnia-Hercegovina, 7/26/95</h2>

A news that <strong>Boutros Boutros Ghali</strong> would arrive to Turkey in order to 
receive a honorary of a relatively unknown American University in Ankara was
published in the Turkish media during the worst chetnik [derogatory term for Serbs] crimes against the Srebrenica
civilians.  Ghali was supposed to be received on the highest state level and hold
several press-conferences.<P>

<h2>Turkish painful wound - Cyprus </h2>

With this sudden move (or moral downfall of the official policy, as stated by the
independent intellectuals), the opposition and the part of parliamentarians 
were supposed to pull Turkey into  the dirtiest past of "Bosnia's deluge" by
making Ghali's role official with a "Turkish University Doctoral degree".<P>

The purpose of this visit was supposed to be the solution of the Cyprus
problem, the greatest Turkish wound, at the same time as the other great
Turkish wound, Bosnian, was being cut open.  In addition to the 
hospitality of one of the most important Muslim countries which is also among
the most important supporters of Bosnia, Ghali was supposed to be "treated"
yet again with all-Muslim naivete.  Fortunately, Ghali cancelled the visit,
and his productive cancelation at the same time became the best indicator
of the political situation in Turkey this summer in which the secular authorities
of this country of sixty five million inhabitants are trying to find the optimal
course.  This was a trial for the public, especially in the largest cities, Istanbul,
Ankara and Izmir.  Turkish public expressed so far unseen maturity in the 
understanding of political situation in the world.  It is obvious that the 
public is aware that Ghali himself is not the creator of the dirty world
politics, but the local public also understands that it is unhappy with the 
powerful Western circles which, when Islam is concerned, find a common ground
with fundamentalist Orthodoxy.<P>

Many factors in Turkey and elsewhere are not satisfied with the official policy with 
respect to Ghali and Bosnia, from the people, opposition, media and neighboring
countries to Europe with its political, military, cultural, monetary and other 
organizations.<P>

The local TV channel <em>Channel 7</em> made this dissatisfaction public in 
the documentary film <strong>Sarajevo My Love</strong> in a statement of
a boy from Sarajevo whom the
author of the documentary had found this April in a sweet shop in Sarajevo;
the boy said (in Bosnian, without translation):
"In my opinion, neither <strong>Demirel</strong> [Turkish president] nor <strong>Ciller</strong>
[former prime minister, from secular Motherland Party] are the real Turks;
<strong>Erbakan</strong> [present prime minister, leader of the Islamic Refah
Party] is the real Turk."  A foreigner and a Bosniak (here that means someone 
who is loved without questions) dared to blaspheme, which is exactly the essence
of the political debates on the future course of Turkey.  Whether Turkey
will follow the road of its own, authentic, interests or somebody else's
interests;  by playing host to Ghali or delaying his visit for some "better times";
with direct aid to Bosnia or in some other way.<P>

<h2>Public Above All</h2>

Although CIA has predicted (read prepared), in its long report dealing with this
region, great suffering, disturbances and even a war, only demonstrations 
and protests from that part which is known as "vox populi" prevented Ghali's
bandy-legged showing off in Cetinkaya or Taksim.<P>

These reports and the United Nations are certainly connected.  The official
circles didn't find it suspicious that the announcement of the Secretary 
General's visit was made at the same time when the Greek side in its 
parliament openly predicted war with Turks for the rest of "their Cyprus" and
"proclamation of the mosque Aya Sofya and Istanbul as the center of Orthodoxy."
As if they didn't read Ghali's cynicism: while thousands of muslims on the 
Balkans are massacred and killed and while the TV cameras are recording that
with less excitement then in 1992, he would come to pick up a doctorate as
a reward for the expansion of Orthodox borders in the heart of Rumelia and 
Trakia [old Ottoman provinces, todays Serbia, Bulgaria and Greece], 
first Balkan neighbors of the sixty five million [Turkish] muslims and announce
a new war against the muslims and a new expansion of Orthodoxy.  Because, 
wherever Ghali sets his foot, there wars against muslims start.<P>

As a polite host, president Demirel did not refuse to welcome Ghali, although Ghali
hadn't helped him in the past, when on two occasions Demirel tried to visit
Sarajevo.  The role of the "block" was handed over to "Islamic forces", to make
sure that "the West doesn't realize" how much the whole Islamic Turkish community
dislikes Muslim katils and murderers.  Hence, the sharpest criticism came 
from the leader of <em>Refah</em> <strong>Erbakan</strong> and the mayor of
Istanbul <strong>Erdogan</strong>.  However, it is important that a strong
and constructive denunciation came from <em>Bosna Dayanism Vakf</em> as well
as from the patriotic party <em>Anvatan partisi</em>, and numerous deputies
in the Turkish mejlis (parliament), and also those independent intellectuals and
organizations which do not find representation in current political parties.
Official circles felt relieved when it was confirmed that Ghali had received
more than 10 thousands of threatening letters and, afraid for his dignity and
safety, cancelled the visit.<P>

Forces behind the campaign against Ghali's visit to Turkey now realize that 
they couldn't have changed much on the international scene and especially 
not in Bosnia, but they are also aware that they did the only morally and
politically correct thing.  They made it clear to the so called domestic 
official policy that in the future it would have to take into consideration
those opinions which it disliked.  Also, they showed to the influential
political forces abroad that Turkish political factor was not united and was
definitively not obedient and that the international community would have
to keep this in mind in its every future project.  In this way, they showed
the signs of still very strong solidarity of the Muslim world with Bosnia.
Finally, if there were more of this kind of solidarity in other muslim societies
all over the world, if more muslim intellectuals influenced public opinion
among the Millions of Muslims all over the world, the consequences would
have been useful for both us, Bosniaks, and the rest of muslims.<P>

 

<hr><p>

Translated on 7/11/96<P>
