<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>SDA election program: moderate right</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

used without permission, for "fair use" only<hr>

<FONT SIZE="+1">

 <h1>Neo-Communists are Trying to Fool Voters</h1>

<strong><em>by Dzemaludin Latic</em></strong><P>

<h2>Ljiljan, Sarajevo, Bosnia-Hercegovina, 6/26 1996</h2> 

As the election day approaches (OSCE set the definite election date for September 14 1996), the conflict between the political <strong>concepts</strong> for the future Bosnia-Hercegovina is heating up.  Recent incident with <strong>Haris Silajdzic</strong> in Cazin revealed those concepts in a very emotional form together with a lot of additional issues.  All in all, one could say that there are only three important concepts: moderate right, neo-communist and nationalist.  The third concept is connected to the political philosophy and expansionism of the current Bosnian Serb and Bosnian Croat leaderships, which, unfortunately, are supported by the majority of Serbs and Croats in Bosnia-Hercegovina.  There is no need to waste space on this concept, since it is obvious, its goals are clear, and one should fight it daily using all allowable means.<P>

The moderate right concept, which is primarily linked with SDA although, as we will later emphasize, SDA is not the only political party which supports it, presupposes, above all, <strong>resistance</strong> to the nationalist concept, resistance based on the "idea of Bosnia" as a common state in which three peoples are equal and, therefore, free.  In Bosnia, there cannot be a free individual unless the people to which he belongs is also free; neither could all Bosnian peoples be free unless all individuals are also free.  Nationalist Serb and Croat concept cannot achieve its expansionist goals unless it destroys the "idea of Bosnia", <strong>namely</strong>: unless it conquers the people which most faithfully and strongly preserves and fights for that idea, its survival, and political subjectivity.<P>

The moderate right concept has been strongly, especially recently, attacked by the supporters of the neo-communist concept.  Their reactions regarding the attack on the leader of the Party for Bosnia-Hercegovina (SBiH), Dr. Haris Silajdzic, in Cazin, essentially do not touch the problem of freedom (judging from the tone of news reports, they are neither concerned with the politician Silajdzic whom they also cannot stand) but are the consequence of open struggle for power.  If that was not the case, at least someone would have wondered about the <strong>causes</strong> which contributed to the incident in Cazin.  One of the immediate reasons was that, just before the attack, Silajdzic's supporters carried out a <strong>moral assassination</strong> of the highest values of the people which most thoroughly preserves the idea of Bosnia, has fought, and still fights for it.  We have a detailed report about that incident on the following pages.  Cursing of Islam, tekbir and the legal president of this state, in Sarajevo was characterized as a <strong>verbal crime</strong>, while it is actually a very serious assault on the indigenous values of Bosnia-Hercegovina.  <strong>Islam, as other monotheistic religions, would have to be protected by the Constitution of this state and not cursed at meetings of political parties!</strong>  Those who would establish this state without Islam can only be one of the two: enemies of this state and the Bosniaks, or utopians whose intentions lead to hell!  This [Bosniak] people was <strong>attacked</strong> because it belongs to Islam and those who would divide Bosniaks on that basis are <strong>truly</strong> playing with fire!<P>

With its strong attack on SDA and silence in the face of a <em>moral assassination</em> on the highest values of the Bosniak, Muslim man, the supporters of the neo-communist concept are trying to cheat (mostly) the Bosniak people into believing that it is possible, through dry words about the <em>market economy</em> and <em>open society</em>, to achieve a free and integrated state of Bosnia-Hercegovina.  There can be no prosperity nor a healthy open society nor a happy future without the solution of the national question in Bosnia-Hercegovina!  There can be no free citizens unless every nation is also free!  And only that people is free who lives in its faith and on its (therefore also our, common) land.  "This is the Balkans, dear," says a Sarajevo poet.  Every European nation would behave like the Balkan peoples if their national questions were not resolved!<P>

The moderate right concept offers a solution.  I dare say that in the present conditions that is the only solution.  We can observe some developments in that direction.  For example, <strong>Croatian Christian-Democratic Party</strong>, led by <strong>Marko Veselica</strong> and <strong>Ante Kovacevic</strong> has been registered in Bosnia-Hercegovina.  These politicians and their party support, verbally and in practice, whole and common Bosnia-Hercegovina (it is interesting that usually very loud Bosnian opposition did not find it necessary to criticize the founding of this party, although it introduces christian values into politics.  What would have happened if a Bosniak Islamic party were to register itself?!  I think that our oppositionists couldn't wait to fight against the "supporters of the religious totalitarianism" among the Bosniak people!)<P>

Although the strongest parties usually do not enter coalitions before the elections, it is my humble opinion that SDA, which openly supports traditional, religious values, could form a coalition with parties of this kind, provided that a Serb Bosnian party which would affirm traditional Orthodox values forms in the future.  <strong>That would be the strongest Bosnian front which would build a free and integrated state in which all peoples and individuals would prosper.</strong>  And in some future time of <strong>post-nationalism</strong>, when none of the national, including Bosniak, identities is endangered, we will start to build a free civic state and will unite based on the political philosophy which focuses on a citizen.<P> 
<hr>

Translated on 7/7/96
