<HEAD>
<TITLE> Mustafa Ceric and Looting in Liberated Areas</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
used without permission, for ``fair use" only
<hr>
<FONT SIZE="+1">

<h1>Condoms, Koran and AIDS </h1><p>

 
<h2><i> by Sinan Alic<br>  Front Slobode, 8/11/95, Tuzla, Bosnia-Hercegovina</i></h2><p>


<hr>

<h3>39.</h3>

I have to admit that I did not blink once while recently watching a program on TV TPK, actually a recording of a lecture which reis-ul-ulema [religious leader of Bosnian muslims], Dr. Mustafa Ceric, delivered to the wider political leadership of SDA [Stranka Demokratske Akcije, Party of Democratic Action, the largest Muslim party in Bosnia and former Yugoslavia], officers of the 2nd Corps......<p>

I also have to admit that intensive staring into the screen wasn't the result of the speaker's engrossing eloquence nor the stories and facts he told.  On the contrary, I could not believe that so much confusion could creep into a public appearance of a man from whom, taking into account his position and education, one would expect exeptional erudition, unique and unequivocal thinking.<P>

Instead, Dr Ceric's speech was confused, touching on Koran and stories about men who, in the past, have bought the Holy Book for their mothers but did not dare tpuch it; on Americans who "copied something from Koran" and declared that to be democracy; on condoms and injections in order to prove that AIDS won't spread among bosnian muslims; on himself and a story about how some people love hik while others don't; on chetniks who are in our heads and should be thrown out; on alcohol, against which he has nothing, the ban is in the Holy Book; pork etc. etc. etc.<p>

No matter how hard I tried to figure out what reis was aiming at, everything was in vain.  Dilemmas remained.  Maybe that was his intention.<P>

I shook my head for a while, in order to find chetniks in it, so that I could throw them out; chetniks "who are as dangerous as the ones shooting at us from the hills."<p>

I shook it, then shook it some more and still nothing happened.<p>

Was that statement an allusion to something?  I shall not try to interpret it, though it could be interpreted in several ways.<p>

Maybe, that was what reis-ul-ulema wanted.<p>

Then, a friend has asked me:"Have you heard that, in his speech at the City Mosque, rais called for juhad?" I said I had not.<p>

Maybe my friend did not understand correctly!?<p>

<h3>40.</h3>

Unbelievable tragedy of Srebrenica's inhabitants reminded me of the stupidities we did in the first months of the war, the consequences of which we experience these days.<P>

It is not an easy job to find acommodations for approximately 30,000 people in a short period.  How much easier that would be today if the hundreds of dwellings in the towns and villages of Simin Han, Caklovici, Kovacevo Selo, Pozarnica, Smoluca, Jesenica and others haven't been destroyed, demolished and in some cases torched.<p>

No-one can argue today that these events were not a consequence of a vengeful euphoria to which the members of the Territorial Defence and then the inhabitants of the neighboring villages had succumbed.<P>

Although those houses and cottages were private property, in fact, the resources of the state of Bosnia-Hercegovina were destroyed and looted.<P>

If that did not happen, the refugees from Srebrenica would have easily been acommodated, not in tents but in livable houses.<P>

Under the roofs of these houses there were furnished rooms, kitchens full of  house appliances, which based on somebody's "amazing" idea showed up as a war loot at the supermarket next to the market in Tuzla.<P>

It happened!  Let us hope it does not happen again!<P>

<hr>

Translated on 9/7/95

