<TITLE> Yugoslav "Patriotic" Press</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<FONT SIZE="+1">
Yugoslavia.com offers a frequently updated (they claim daily) summary in English of articles from the state-controlled Yugoslav daily papers, <em>Politika</em>, <em>Politika Ekspress</em>, <em>Vecernje Novosti</em> and <em>Borba</em>: <a HREF="http://www.yugoslavia.com/News/ST.HTM"> Serbia Today</a>.<P>  

<h2><A NAME="argument"><IMG ALT="Argument" SRC="argument.gif" ALIGN=BOTTOM></a></h2> 

Argument is a biweekly newspaper, issued by <i>Politika</i>, the largest newspaper and magazine publishing house in Yugoslavia.  <i>Politika</i> has had a history of trying to break out of the government's embrace.  Although now nominally independent its publications mostly follow the line of the support for or loyal opposition to the government.  August 1996: alas, <a HREF="/info/students/marko/nezsvet/nezsvet1.html"><em>Argument</em> is no more</a>!<p>

<ul>
<li><A HREF = "argument1.html"> United Left or the Revolution That Goes On: Opposition Press in Yugoslavia </A> 4/7/95
<li><A HREF = "argument2.html"> Interview with Nikola Koljevic, the Bosnian Serb Vice President</a> 4/7/95
</ul>
<p>

<h2><a NAME="velsrb">Velika Srbija [Greater Serbia]</a></h2>

Velika Srbija is a monthly publication of the  Serbian Radical Party, led by Dr. <a href="/info/students/marko/vreme/vreme10.html">Vojislav Seselj</a>.  It is an independent publication, inasmuch as it is highly critical of the government and the ruling party.  However, the Radicals see themselves as a continuation of the pre World War II Serb nationalists and the World War II Serb royalist guerillas, the Chetnik movement of a "Serbian martyr" Draza Mihajlovic.  They firmly support division of Bosnia-Hercegovina.<P>

<ul>
<li><a HREF="/info/students/marko/velsrb/velsrb1.html">Years of Living Dangerously</a>, interview with Dr. Nikola Poplasen, president of the Serb Radical Party for the Republic of Srpska: on the Dayton agreement, nationalism, borders, roots of the Serb defeat in this war, 3/20-4/5 1996
<li><a HREF="/info/students/marko/velsrb/velsrb2.html">Martin to Zagreb, Martin from Zagreb</a>, communist shake hands with ustashe while Serb heads roll in Croatian courts, 3/20-4/5 1996
</ul><P>

<h2><A NAME="narnov">Narodne Novine</a></h2>

<ul>
<li><A HREF = "narnov1.html"> Peace and Freedom medal for Slobodan Milosevic </A> , 10/13/95
</ul>
<p>


<h2><A NAME="evnov"><IMG ALT="Evropske Novosti" SRC="evnov.gif" ALIGN=BOTTOM></a></h2>

Evropske Novosti is a "european" edition of the Belgrade daily Vecernje Novosti.  The paper was set up 3 years ago to circumvent the international sanctions.  It is strongly influenced by the Serbian government.

<ul>
<li><a HREF="evnovosti1.html"> Serbs in Serbia Bother Him</a>: seccessionists and their pathological hatred, 8/14/95 
<li><A HREF="evnovosti1.html#bela">He is celebrating somebody else's sorrow</a>: disloyal Croats in Vojvodina, 8/14/95
<li><A HREF="evnovosti3.html#magda">Luxury in Prison</a>: Marinko Magda a man wanted by Hungary and Yugoslavia both, ends up in a Hungarian jail, 10/25/95
<li><A HREF="evnovosti3.html#kasagic">The Man For a New Direction</a>: Rajko Kasagic, the new prime minister of Srpska, 10/25/95
<li><A HREF="evnovosti2.html">Lack of Medical Personnel</a>: appalling conditions in a refugee camp in Krnjaca, 1/3/96
<li><A HREF="evnovosti2.html#colonel">Campaign Against a Colonel</a>: American colonel and racist Croatians, 1/3/96
<li><A HREF="evnovosti4.html#mrkonj1">A Difficult Return</a>: in western Bosnia, Serbs return to their demolished homes, 2/7/96
<li><A HREF="evnovosti4.html#mrkonj2">Ghoulish Ruins</a>: in western Bosnia, Serbs return to their demolished homes, 2/7/96
<li><A HREF="patpress1.html#evnov">Muslim Policemen Beaten in Mostar</a>, from Vecernje Novosti, 3/12/96
<li><A HREF="evnovosti5.html">Cooperation - My Deadly Sin!</a>, interview with Rajko Kasagic, recently dismissed prime minister of the Republic Srpska, 5/18/96
<li><A HREF="evnovosti6.html">Two cities - Two Worlds</a>, Serbian reporters in Vitez, Herceg-Bosna, with Serbs and Croats, 6/11/96
</ul><P>

<h2><A NAME="intervju">Intervju</a></h2>

The latest issue of <A HREF="http://www.suc.org/news/intervju/index.html"><em>Intervju</em></a>, in Serbian, is available at the Serbian Unity Congress server.  You can also find selected articles from the past issues of another magazine published by <em>Intervju</em>: <A HREF="http://www.suc.org/news/profil/index.html"><em>Profil</em></a><p>
<ul>
<li><A HREF="/info/students/marko/intervju1.html"> A Warrant for Izetbegovic</a>: did Izetbegovic know about the camps for Serbs?  Who is behind the Sarajevo massacre on Vase Miskina Street?, 2/13 1996
<li><A HREF="/info/students/marko/intervju2.html"> Who am I, What am I, and What I did in the War?</a>: Veselin Sljivicaniin, Yugoslav Army officer indicted by the Hague Tribunal for war crimes gives his side of the story, 3/29 1996<IMG SRC="star.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE">
</ul><P>


<h2>Duga</h2>

<a HREF="http://www.suc.org/news/duga/index.html">Duga</a> (rainbow) is a bi-weekly from Belgrade.  During the "anti-bureaucratic revolution", in which Slobodan Milosevic came to power, and the subsequent "national awakening of the Serbs", Duga excelled by publishing a lot of special editions on the medieval and pre W.W.I Serb history.  Since then it has provided space for both extreme right and left on its pages. Duga carries a regular two page column by Mirjana Markovic, the wife of Serbian president, Slobodan Milosevic, in which she, among other, extols the virtues of Chinese communism and professes love for the oppressed in Angola.  Dragos Kalajic, an unofficial guru of "the new Serbian right" is also a Duga columnist.<P> 

<ul>
<li><A HREF="duga/duga2.html">Sweet Living in Sarajevo</a>. In this article Mr. Kalajic touches on one of his favourite topics, Islam and the Bosnian Muslims.  12/10 1994.<IMG SRC="star.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE">
<li><A HREF="duga/duga1.html">Partnership for Recket</a>: Dragos Kalajic disects "Partnership for Peace", NATO, American policy in Europe and Bosnia, the New World Order, threats of mondialism and much, much more... 6/8 1996<IMG SRC="star.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE">
</ul><P>
  


<h2><A NAME="politika">Politika</a></h2>

BeoNET offers a daily summary of news from <A HREF="http://www.beonet.com/politika.html">Politika</A>, every day at 5p.m. central European time (editor's promise).<P>

<ul>
<li><A HREF="patpress1.html#politika">In Croatia, Even Dead Serbs are Victims</a>, Jasenovac memorial, from Vecernje Novosti, 3/12/96

</ul><P>

<h2><A NAME="borba">Borba</a></h2>

<ul>
<li><A HREF="patpress1.html#borba">Elizabeth Rehn Again Denies Press Reports</a>, biased Western media strike again, from Borba, 3/12/96
</ul><P>



