<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Slovenian Press</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<h2> <A HREF="http://.eunet.si/yellowpage/0/mediji1/mladina/mladina.html"><IMG ALT="Mladina" SRC="mladina.gif"></a> </h2>

<FONT SIZE="+1">Mladina (youth) is the best known Slovenian weekly.  It has gained a reputation for challenging, investigative and provocative reporting in the fromer Yugoslavia. Its reporters were in the forefront of the Slovenian independence movement.  In the independent Slovenia, Mladina continues to be an irritant for the authorities, some of which, like the former defense minister, Janez jansa, were in the past involved with the weekly.
This is the history of Mladina as seen by its editorial board:<P>

<b>MLADINA</b> magazine was established in 1943, on the liberated theritory of Slovenia, as a paper of the Communist Youth Organization. For the safety reasons, it was printed in different locations between Ljubljana, Bela Krajina and Kocevje region.  After WW2, it remained the official mouth piece of the Socialist Youth Alliance of Slovenia.<p>

For a few decades Mladina covered various topics: from more or less favorite
reporting on pop culture that "obsessed" the youth generation, recruiting the 
young generations for voluntary youth work, praising the "great" Yugoslav leader Tito and defending the basic principles of the Socialist regime.<p>
However, in the early '80s, Mladina turned into a buldozer that started to destroy all the sacred symbols and taboos of the Socialist society. Through Mladina's eyes, once so-praised Tito became a nasty despot. Mladina's journalists began to dig and question the position of the federal army, the Socialist regime, the role of the League of Communists...<p>
To put it bluntly, they were the pain in the ass for the power structure. And the federal presidency itself had to meet to find out what to do with these "anarcho-liberals" and "agents of the Western intelligence agencies." After Mladina severely attacked the privileged status of the army (and especially the defense minister who used the soldiers to build himself a villa on the Adriatic cost), the army repressive apparatus decided to go after the magazine in 1988.<p>
Under the allegations of stealing the military secret, the trial against the editor-in-chief and two journalists, along with one army officer, was set up and performed in a foreign language (Serbo-Croatian) in the middle of Ljubljana, the capital of Slovenia. This act unified Slovenes and (in a longer run) led to Slovenia's secession from Yugoslavia. Mladina became a symbol of democratic changes for all Slovenes: from left-wing members of social movements, liberal activists, to right-wing nationalists. Those were happy days for Slovenia: fascists and anarchists holding each others' hands and reading Mladina.<p>

But they were happy days for Mladina as well. Whenever an issue of the magazine 
was banned, the next issue was sold out. The circulation reached over 80,000.<p>
The role of Mladina remained controversial till the recent days. It was one of the rare media that assumed cynical distance towards the rush into Slovenia's independency, and when the ten-day war against federal forces started, Mladina's journalists performed an almost impossible task: they were the only Slovenian reporters to cover the conflicts from both sides. The reporters and photoreporters were on the frontlines all over the country, which resulted not only in a in-deep coverage in the magazine, but also in a book <i>Ten Days of War For Slovenia</i>.<p>

When the war spread to the neighboring countries, Mladina's journalists kept following it. They went to the most dangerous places, and the toll they paid was high: two wounded, one dead. <b>Ivo Standeker</b>, the feature editor, was killed by a Serbian shell in Sarajevo.<p>

Focusing on internal affairs, Mladina has remained  a "pain in the ass" also for the new democraticly elected authorities. Whether conservative or liberal, no politician is safe from its authors' sharp pencils. And as someone once said, Mladina is not only a watchdog. It is a watchdog that barks.

<hr>


