<HEAD>
<TITLE>Interview with Nikola Poplasen</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

used without permission, for "fair use" only<hr>

<FONT SIZE="+1">

<h1>Years of Living Dangerously: Interview with Dr. Nikola Poplasen, president of the Serb Radical Party for the Republic of Srpska</h1>

<strong><em>by Miodrag Nikolic</em></strong><P>

<h2>Velika Srbija [Greater Serbia], Belgrade, FR Yugoslavia, 3/20-4/5 1996</h2>

It is not necessary to introduce Dr. Nikola Poplasen, president of the Serb Radical Party for the Republic of Srpska and a professor at the law faculty in Banja Luka, to those who follow political and other events in the former Yugoslavia.  We had a chance to see his face on TV screens of "their" TV stations as well.<P>

However, since the interest for the Serb Radicals and their leaders is growing, we will list a few details from Dr. Poplasen's biography.  By origin a Serb form Knin Krajina [in Croatia], Dr. Poplasen was born in 1951 in Stanisic near Sombor [in Vojvodina, northern Serbia]; probably because of that Slobodan Milosevic's regime does not allow him to cross over the Drina river.  Until the beginning of the war, Dr. Poplasen worked as a professor at the Sarajevo faculty of Political sciences; in 1992, as the majority of Serb patriots, he put on an uniform and joined the defenders of Serbdom.  After first war experiences in the Niksic brigade, in agreement with <a HREF="/info/students/marko/vreme/vreme10.html">Dr. Vojislav Seselj</a> he took over the organization of the Serb Radical Party in Srpska.  In March 1993, at the Serb Radicals congress in Banja Luka, he was elected the president of the party.  Muslim offensive from Bihac in the fall of 1994 started while he was in Belgrade.  He dropped the party business and quickly returned to Srpska and went to the Bihac front together with his students.  He commanded soldiers in the first lines of combat.  Even today he saves a rifle broken by a fragment of a green [Muslim] grenade; for courage in combat and successful command he won the title of the Chetnik vojvoda.<P>

After the collapse of the Muslim offensive he returned to political activities with the goal of turning Serb Radicals into a significant political party in Srpska.<P>

<strong>A lot has changed in Serb lands since your last interview for "Greater Serbia" (issue 18, June 1994).  Where do you see the causes for Serb defeats starting with the fall of Western Slavonia, all the way to the "Dayton peace"?</strong><P>

There are a lot of causes.  It is known that we today live at the time when the USA uses different methods in order to control independent states; especially smaller states which lie in the American path towards the total control of the East.  We do not have significant influence on that.  Another group of causes is connected with the unsuitable behavior of the Serb side in the recent events, especially during the last two years.  It turned out that the regime in Serbia, led by Slobodan Milosevic and him in turn led by his wife Mira Markovic, has again conducted practical experiments on Serbs living west from the Drina and Danube.  All of us witnessed the initial patriotic orientation of the Serb Socialist Party and its support for the national cause.  That kind of policy is behind successful resistance in Knin and the whole of Serb Krajina; without it,  Serb struggle in the former Bosnia-Hercegovina wouldn't have been relatively successful.  However, at the beginning of 1993, there was an obvious about-turn.  Pressure on the leadership of Srpska to accept the capitulation and the Vance-Owen plan illustrates that.  Why did Milosevic switch to a path of treason? Has his bolshevik ideology finally won over, has he become psychologically unstable, was it his wife's influence, fear of world powers, or maybe all of that combined?  It doesn't really matter at this time.<P>

In any case he is a man who doesn't have a privilege to behave like that and make decisions which endanger the existence of the whole nation.  How did he do that?  At first, Solbodan Milosevic, criminalized the Republic Srpska Krajina as a state.  He systematically stifled any expression of independence in Serb Krajina.  He rigged the elections and ensured the leading role for former criminals like Borislav Mikelic and people like him.  All that demoralized population, even produced disgust among the people of Krajina, broke their unity and blunted their will to fight.<P>

With constant concessions to the pressure from the West, intentional weakening of the army of Srpska Krajina and direct work of the people from the Yugoslav army intelligence service, it was ensured that Western Slavonia would fall without resistance.  Of course that attack wouldn't have been successful had not Milosevic guaranteed to Tudman that what happened would happen.  You may recall that on May 1, the day the Croatian attack on Western Slavonia started, state-controlled [Serbian] TV reported that something was happening in western Slavonia only 28 minutes after the beginning of the attack.  Before that they had reports about the celebration of May 1, and good wishes from plum pickers and cabbage harvesters to the Belgrade leaders for May the 1st holiday.  All that was a rehearsal for the total disaster in Serb Dalmatia, Banija, Lika and Kordun, which followed a few months later.  There was no end to the bloodletting.  These events were ignored by the world and the media in Serbia and Yugoslavia.<P>

All that was repeated in Srpska.  Demands for ceasefires and peace process were rejected until a third of Srpska fell in a short time.  After that, those who had bombarded Srpska, killed innocent victims and destroyed civilian and other targets, took the Serb representatives to a closed military base.  Supposedly, there they came to an agreement in order to avoid further bloodletting.  However, the truth is different.<P>

<strong>We will return to that later.  Do you think that it was possible to avoid the defeat?</strong><P> 

In any case, that was not a military defeat.  It was an pre-arranged scenario whose main participants and planners, both from abroad and among the Serbs, are known.  However, the mechanisms and details of the game are still murky.  Nevertheless, in the near future, Serb people will find out about all those who participated in that game and they will get what they deserve.<P>

<strong>How do you assess the role of Srpska leadership in these events?</strong><P>

Our views regarding that are well known.  We are convinced that in 1992, or 1993 or 1994 at the latest, despite strong pressure from Belgrade, we should have proclaimed union of Republics of Serb Krajina and Srpska.  A terrible mistake, with terrible consequences, has been made.  It doesn't help that the state officials from Krajina and Srpska now say that the unification was blocked by Belgrade.  We should have been defiant and implemented that decision on our own despite a certain risk.  I am convinced that the formation of the western Serb state would have produced a state which would have enjoyed respect in Serbia, Yugoslavia and the whole world.  In any case the powers with interests in the Balkans would have realized that a new state had been formed and that its formation is an expression of the will of the people who lives in that state.  All that would have strengthened patriotism and national consciousness in Yugoslavia and speeded up expected and desirable political changes.<P>

Besides that, it was necessary to pay the officers in the armies of Krajina and Srpska from our budget (instead of the Yugoslav army budget) and tie them to the local environment with war assignments, family life and total living perspective...  Also, we shouldn't have moved our military industry to Serbia and tied our logistics to unreliable surroundings.<P>

(...)<P>

<strong>Some claim that Slobodan Milosevic has saved Banja Luka?</strong><P>

You can hear that here and there.  It mostly comes from Milosevic's people who have a task to hide the committed treason and turn the thinking to the opposite direction.  Here in Srpska, almost everyone understands that almost all officers serving in the Srpska army (there were a few exceptions) also had assignments in the Yugoslav army, were paid by the Yugoslav army and could have been blackmailed in different ways because of that.  Besides, a large number of them hails from mixed marriages, has relatives (even immediate families) and summer houses in Croatia and has been indoctrinated with a thick layer of brotherhood and unity which can easily be controlled from the offices of JUL [reformed Yugoslav communists], and intelligence services.  I mention this because, according to my informations, the whole [Bosnian] Krajina and Posavina, all the way to Brcko were supposed to fall within two weeks, like Serb Krajina in Croatia.  The area around Banja Luka and the city itself remained in Serb hands thanks to disobedience of several commanders from Prijedor-Sana area who had deserted their positions and brought some units back to defend their birth places.  All that prolonged the capture of [Bosnian] Krajina, slowed down and changed the American plans and the Serbian authorities' willingness to go along with those plans.  Instead the previous [Contact group] plan was only modified at our expense thanks to already mentioned Milosevic's characteristics.  A number of reporters from Dayton and participants in the negotiations testify that Milosevic was extremely generous.  A day and a half before the end of negotiations, when Izetbegovic was ready to offer the division of Sarajevo, Milosevic refused that offer and gave the whole Sarajevo to the Muslim side (a published map of the Muslim offer shows that Izetbegovic envisaged the whole city as a common district under international control).  In addition to that Milosevic refused to trade parts of Sarajevo for the town of Gorazde, because he assessed that a great concentration of Serbs in Gorazde, those disobedient western Serbs, would make new problems for cooperative Serbia.  You can imagine the situation in which some 30,000 Muslims receive a 20-30km wide corridor and 800,000 Serbs living west from Brcko get only a 4km wide corridor.  That is Slobodan Milosevic's policy in Dayton, the one he called a victory of peace and human tolerance.<P>

(...)<P>

<strong>So far, we have been talking about the past.  The war has been replaced by "Dayton peace".  What do the Serb Radicals think about that "peace"?</strong><P>

The Dayton peace, as every other peace, is an interlude between two wars.  A true peace would have been achieved a long time ago in these territories, actually there wouldn't have been a war, had it not been produced in Western European and American kitchens with initial approval from Moscow and later from Belgrade.  Therefore, everything achieved in Dayton is an extension of the imperial policy of the greatest world power, its subjugation of independent areas on the globe.  Dayton papers have certain characteristics which will in the future be studied as a historic curiosity.  Above all, in a lot of ways they cannot be implemented.  The jurisdiction of Bosnia-Hercegovina overlaps those given to the entities and vice versa.  Then, it will be impossible to organize the elections unless basic human and voting rights are openly violated.  Dayton papers also ensure total military dominance of the NATO troops, while the civilian affairs are mostly controlled by the representatives and institutions from the EU.  Therefore, Dayton papers have a built-in potential clash between Europe and America.  We can see that this is so from the opposing statements given by the European Union representatives  and people from the American administration.  Dayton papers are based on the concept of Muslim-Croatian federation in opposition to the Serb entity.  this is an attempt to form a untied state which keeps falling further apart with every new day.  While the Serbs are preoccupied with the historic need to establish their own state as a safeguard against genocide to which they have been exposed in history,  muslims and Croats hate each other and that determines their relations and behavior.  Americans and Germans will really need a lot of force, pressure and skill in order to maintain a situation without killing and military clashes.<P>

<strong>Is the Dayton agreement favorable for Serbs or not?</strong><P>

I would just like to state several facts without trying to assess any of them.  I've already mentioned that the Serbs were decimated from the air and brought into a situation when they had to sign something.  Prior to that, all Serb attempts to seek a peaceful solution had been blocked, until the total genocide in Serb Krajina had been arranged, and a third of Srpska fallen.  Only after that, our representatives were taken to a military base of the power behind these events to supposedly "negotiate".  See, the title of the Dayton agreement is "peace agreement about Bosnia-Hercegovina," and in that sense it should be a document which outlines certain positive and negative sanctions and norms.  Instead, it is more of a political than a legal document, since in its key elements, it allows the possibility for arbitration, i.e. political decisions.  Another characteristic of the Dayton paper is that it puts Bosnia-Hercegovina under foreign rule.  Foreign rule is visible not only from the presence of the IFOR troops and international police forces, but also in various institutions, commissions etc.  Every commission envisioned by the Dayton paper is chaired by a foreigner who can side with the representatives of either nation and provide majority necessary to pass a so-called legal decision.  However, in some of the most important factors, national equality is totally ignored.  For example, Mr. Bildt, according to the Dayton papers is supposed to appoint to the common Civilian commission people whom he finds cooperative.  Foreigners decide who can take part in elections, who cannot, whether a political party should be banned, whether some individual can run for an office and all other aspects of the elections.<P>

As far as we are concerned, it is important that we didn't sign the Dayton agreement, and if we had a choice, we wouldn't have.  Nevertheless, the Serb Radical Party recognizes current authorities in Srpska; we consider that the Serb Democratic party won the majority in democratic elections and is entitled to make decisions.  Our authorities empowered Milosevic to sign the agreement and he not only prepared a tragedy for us but also for the whole of Yugoslavia and Serbia.  However, in view of current situation, we believe that we should make sure that Srpska keeps all the attributes of statehood given to the entities in the agreement and to gain more if possible; that the border between two entities should become as much as possible like an international border so that in the future in a more propitious moment when Serbia and Yugoslavia find their patriotic conscience and Russia finds its soul we can join the motherland.  We are convinced that in that historical context neither Knin nor Gracac nor Okucani were irrevocably lost.  But in the present situation it would be suicidal, unnecessary and unproductive to keep fighting.  I think that it is necessary to switch to political means for struggle and to use arguments of another kind:  truth, diplomatic skill, reason etc.  Also one should keep in mind that our defeat wasn't a military defeat but the result of outside intervention and bargaining.  It should not be forgotten that the main goal of the NATO bombardment was to totally demoralize Serb army and destroy its organizational unity.  However, we haven't lost all hope; with a lot of firmness and more patriotism I think that we shall see a better future.<P>

(...)<P>

<strong>According to the Dayton peace agreement, the former Bosnia-Hercegovina is supposed to function as a union between the Muslim-Croat federation and the Republic of Srpska.  It there a precedent for this arrangement in the political practice?</strong><P>

No, such a political system does not exist anywhere, neither in theory nor in practice.  Both entities, "the republic of Srpska" and "the Muslim-Croat federation" have some elements of statehood.  Nevertheless, only our propaganda treats them as states.  Bosnia-Hercegovina was recognized as a state, but on the other hand the Dayton agreement stipulates that each entity has its own army and police and that the army and police of one entity can not cross into the territory of the other entity without its permission.  The next article states that the military force is supposed to preserve territorial integrity of Bosnia-Hercegovina.  These two "solutions" absolutely exclude each other.  Simply, the Dayton agreement is an unrealizable document which strives to preserve a confusing and chaotic situation.  The document is an expression of the world power's intentions and it does not fulfill the needs of the local population.  From the beginning, the Serb Radicals have been striving for the lasting peace in the Balkans and they are convinced that the lasting peace is only possible with a firm border towards our un-brothers, Croats and muslims.  There had been no problems nor bloodshed between Serbs and Croats until they started living in a common state.  It is not a problem if someone from Prijedor or Banja Luka wants to go to Zagreb, even five times a day.  But he  has to do it with a passport and, in case there is a problem, our citizen can contact his embassy or a consulate and resolve the problem.  At French-German border you have to speed up in order not to disturb the flow of traffic.  But if there is a dispute between France and Germany, not even a bird will be able to cross that border.  I don't understand why some people suggest that we will remain in a conflict laden situation and that a cooperation would not be possible after the establishment of a border.  We will cooperate according to mutual interests.  Serbs will have to decide what is in their interest and where to cooperate.  The same is true for Croats.  If they find mutual interests then a "soft" border will be acceptable.<P>

The world destroyed Yugoslavia as a multiethnic state and quickly recognized some of the successor states and now insists on Bosnia-Hercegovina as a multiethnic state.  This only sets the scene for another bloodshed in the future.  We really do not want bloodshed, but a peaceful and civilized life in the future, and that is only possible with a firmly established border.  Because of that we insist on treating the inter-entity border as an international border and intervene in all cases where the inter-entity border is treated as unnecessary and porous;  above all, we insist that the Serbs be treated as an equal partner.  One can not speak about the return of some [refugees] and not others.  Consider the example from the <a HREF="/home/marko/public_html/otoci.html">trial of that Ustasha soldier</a> who had butchered an old woman and was acquitted at the trial with the justification that the woman had reached under her apron.  He said that she might have wanted to pull out a gun to kill him and because of that he butchered a seventy-years-old woman.  In that sort of environment not one of the Serbs from Serb Krajina can return to his hearth.  At the same time there are pressures to allow the return of Croats and muslims to their homes.  I simply insist on equal treatment, as was stipulated in the Dayton agreement.<P>

(...)<P>    
  

<strong>It seems there is no hope for a Serb state west of the Drina river.  Do you see a chance for getting out of the Dayton mouse trap?</strong><P>

There is hope and there is a chance.(...)  We must realize that our national demise (as a state, economic, political and biological self-destruction) will be total and irreversible if the leftist parties win in the coming elections.  Leftist forces do not stand a chance in a fair contest.  However, pressure and blackmail are horrible.  JUL [reformed Yugoslav Communist party] and SPS [Slobodan Milosevic's Socialist Party] members are visiting directors and businessmen, in order to blackmail and threaten them.  They combine money and fear.  Exactly what they did with some officers during the war.  But they don't have grass roots support.  Banja Luka TV viewers had a chance to see a UN spokesperson speaking at the promotional rally for the United Left [UL] about the future links between nations to the audience of thirty boys with average age of 75 - true remnants of the past.<P>

(...)<P>

<strong>The Dayton agreement envisages the return of all displaced persons.  The majority of Serbs does not have an intention of returning to the territory under Croat or muslim rule.  How will that influence election results if, for example IFOR, escorts a group of muslims or Croats?</strong><P>

As far as I know, the problem of active and passive voting rights in the forthcoming elections hasn't yet been solved.  I'm not saying that that problem cannot be solved, but the present approach makes it unsolvable.  For example, if those  registered to vote at a particular place in 1991 have a right to vote at the same place in this elections, 98% of Drvar inhabitants will vote for a patriotic option and reach a decision to join Drvar, and many other towns, to Srpska.  Gentlemen say that that is possible in theory, but than the Dayton paper doesn't apply any more.  If the Dayton paper was a given solution which we were forced to accept and do accept in order to prevent bloodshed, than the problem of voting rights has to be solved within the framework of that solution.  There is also the problem of people who live in Serbia, those scattered from Chicago and Europe to Sidney in Australia.  It is not a simple undertaking to inform people, organize voting, count the votes and do all of that correctly.  (...)  Further, a large number of Serb  from the territories of the former republic of Croatia and the republic of Serb Krajina has been living in Srpska for years.  They have been here for several years and now someone is going to (it seems that has been done already) take their voting rights away, while someone who has decided to stay in Chicago will have that right.(...)  The solution for this problem should be based on the present situation: all those citizens who live in Srpska and have appropriate documentation should vote where they are now.  Persons who feel connection to Bosnia-Hercegovina but live in Yugoslavia and other states, should vote if they wish and should be able to do so.<P>

See how far this cynicism goes.  Srpska leadership has been accused for the exodus from Sarajevo.  At the same time, a few days ago, federal police entered Ilijas in which about ten elderly Serbs remained and killed all of them.  It seems that Srpska leadership should have forced the remaining Serbs to stay in Ilijas and be slaughtered as well.  Really, there is no end to that irony.  those who had to leave Ilijas  are supposed to vote for the local authorities and can not even get close to the town.  That has nothing to do with basic democratic principles (...)<P>

(...)<P>

Listen, if you are asking if muslims should return to Prijedor, let me ask you whether Serbs should return to Knin?  Why should I, although that is demanded from me, speak against my own nation?!  Again that old syndrome: I can only be a humanist if I spit on my nation and work against its interests; otherwise I'm a nationalist.  I have to say that I don't belong to leftist currents who used to pride themselves on their empty internationalism and humanism...  I do accept that all people are the same: two arms, a head, two legs, a right to live; in that sense we are all equal.  We are also human beings but besides that we should remember that we live in this area and that our culture is Serb, not Japanese.  It could be that two individuals are drinking Coca-Cola, but each one of them drinks it in his own way in his own territory.  I can not accept unequal approach, to discuss return of some while the others are set aside.(...)<P>

Repatriation is a natural process.  I understand that some persons want to die at the same place they were born, but the return has to be organized and to apply to everyone.  I do not support Milosevic's motto: "all Serbs in one state," Serbia from Belgrade to Kragujevac [city in central Serbia].<P>

<strong>What do you think about the Hague war crimes tribunal and extradition according to its criteria?  The latest indictment is against Mr. Milan Martic?!</strong><P>

The purpose of the Hague tribunal is obvious.  Mr. Martic is a great patriot and I have a lot of respect for him.(...)  I absolutely support his statement regarding the Hague tribunal indictment.<P>

"Hague tribunal" is a theater, not a court.  remember that the prosecutor general, Mr. Goldstone was a high official of the South African republic at the time when that state occupied a part of the neighboring state and that several hundred persons were killed during that occupation.(...)   Another detail: from its start, the tribunal has been braking its own rules.<P>

People are being arrested in order to testify.  Complete farce.  Goldstone reminds me of a character in the novel "Fortress" by great Serb writer Mesa Selimovic.  That character tries to convince his collocutor that the whole people should be arrested and only those who can prove that they are not guilty of anything released.<P>

(...)<P>

<strong>What are the views of the Serb Radical Party regarding the media?</strong><P>

Public opinion is one of the most important factors in the democratic society.  In that context media should be highly professional.  Professionalism also means that the media should have in mind in which state they work.  I don't understand some media in Serbia who spit on Serbs and Serb people more than the media in Rome, Vienna, Berlin and Washington, and all that is followed with large donations from abroad without any control.  I also have to mention that the present media situation in Srpska is unsatisfactory.  Coverage and links between radio and TV stations as well as the attitude of relevant authorities are totally unsatisfactory.(...)<P>

<strong>Serbs have been lost in the war both in the media field and in diplomacy, while Croats have found powerful and rich allies.  Is that Serb failure, perhaps, the reason for the Serb defeat?</strong><P>


These is a lot of truth in that.  Croatian television has several thousand employees; it is led by the fanatics of the neo-Ustashe state; it has unlimited financial resources in the west, especially Germany.  They have been spending and keep spending as much as they need (...).  However, it is sad that for a long time Serbian TV has been working together, almost in sync, with the Croatian TV.<P>

As far as the Croatian allies are concerned situation is somewhat different.  Croats found themselves on a gigantic wave of the American-German empire surging towards the East.  Because of that, it seems that Tudman has surpassed with his success both Starcevic and Pavelic.  The price for that is the total loss of independence. (...)  Croatia will become a German colony and will rapidly sink into poverty at the level of poor African and Latin American countries.  Several percent of the population, rich servants of the West will rule a huge poor majority which will work for miserly wages or be unemployed.  All that is the result of "thousand years long" search of Croats for a master.(...)  Serbs would make a fatal error to re-establish any sort of a common state with them.<P>

<strong>Last year, you published a book under title "Radical nature of western Serbs."  One of the chapters of that book is entitled: we are for the society of rich Serbs.</strong><P>

I think that that is possible.  Srpska has satisfactory agricultural potential and relatively satisfactory industrial potential and infrastructure.  But society of rich Serbs should be also a spiritually rich society.  We should cultivate our rich spiritual and cultural tradition which will be a strong support for our individual and national life in the future.(...)  During the communist dictatorship a Serb was proud if he didn't know anything about his own culture while he hurried to congratulate his neighbors on Catholic Christmas or Muslim Bayram.  Actually that was a policy of anationalization under the mask of internationalism which was advertised to Serbs as a higher value with respect to their traditional culture and respect of own national and cultural customs.<P>

Serb radicals are convinced that a strong reliance on tradition is a jumping stone into a modern, civilized society (...).  Traditional Serb culture can proudly stand shoulder to shoulder with English, French, German culture...(...)<P>

  
<hr>

Translated on 5/1/96<P>

