<FONT SIZE="+1">
<h1> <a NAME="kasagic">The Man For a New Direction</a></h1>

<h2> by Sl. Pesevic, Evropske Novosti, FR Yugoslavia, 10/25/95</h2>


Rajko Kasagic, until recently the president of the District government in Banja Luka, is the fourth prime minister since the founding of the Republic of Srpska.  In the past, this duty was performed by Dr. Baranko Deric, Dr. Vladimir Lukic and Dusan Kozic.<P>

<h2>Fighter From the First Day of the War</h2>

Who is Rajko Kasagic?  He is a lawyer, a man who spent most of his working years on positions of responsibility in the former state company "Jelsingrad", mostly working on legal matters.  He was, that should not be hidden, a member of the Communist League for more than 20 years, with prominent social engagements in local sport teams, the boxing team "Slavija" for example.<P>

His liking of martial arts perhaps compelled him to join the veteran fighters of the Serb Democratic Party (SDS), whose member he has been since the founding.  After the convincing victory of the parties with "the national prefix" [in the first post-communist elections in 1990] in Bosnia, he became the president of the District government in Banja Luka, where he remained (survived?) for almost five years.  His leadership style in this political body was authoritative, the meetings were short and productive; he will probably bring this leadership style to his new office as the prime minister of the Republic of Srpska.<P>

Some foreign media have already stated that the new prime minister is a member of the hawkish wing of SDS, a man who is too loyal, both personally and politically, to the president of RS, Dr. Radovan Karadzic.<P>

Kasagic stated a while ago, at the Parliament session in Bijeljina, that he wouldn't make changes in the government, but that "in the near future, with help of SDS, will evaluate the present government members and make changes where appropriate."  He, therefore, won't hurry with changes of ministers; the respect of "SDS's opinion" clearly shows that Kasagic is a disciplined party member.  The trust implied in his appointment to the highest office in the government is the best indicator of his personal loyalty to Karadzic.<P>

During his first radio address to the public, broadcasted on the waves of Radio Banja Luka, Mr. Kasagic dedicated the bulk of the speech to the increased accountability on all levels "because the former regime has almost put us to sleep".<P>

<h2>Responsibility</h2>

"It is hard to build a new system, but we have to do it," said Kasagic.  "For example, the District government in Banja Luka, demonstrated that it is possible to replace officials in state owned companies whose performance is not satisfactory.  I will fight against resistance to dismissals, if the authorities establish that a civilian is culpable, regardless what he might be responsible for.  We'll have to appoint people who can work better.  We'll have to build the system of accountability.  Mr. Pacanac phoned me this morning to congratulate me on my appointment to the new office.  I asked from him only one thing:  his greatest contribution to this state would be to keep the criminals in the jail."<P>

With this words, the new prime minister announced the changes in the leadership and the fight against all kinds of criminal activity.  Once the peace takes hold Kasagic will work for stronger links with the mother Serbia and Yugoslavia; he will also demand from the military authorities to demobilize the older soldiers, who can then immediately take part in the process of the economic renewal of RS.  He believes that, in peace, one quarter of the present number of mobilized soldiers will be sufficient to defend the borders!<P> 

  
</FONT>

<hr>

Translated on 1/16/96

<hr>


<a HREF="/info/students/marko/yupatpress.html"><IMG SRC="/home/marko/public_html/pictures/home.gif" ALT="HOME"></a>

