<TITLE>Dragos Kalajic: Bosnian Nationalism and Dzemaludin Latic</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
used without permission, for "fair use" only<hr>

<FONT SIZE="+1">

<h1>Sweet Living in Sarajevo</h1>

<strong><em>by Dragos Kalajic</em></strong><P>

<h2>Duga , Belgrade, FR Yugoslavia, December 10 1994</h2>

(...)The realization of a poet's vision proves and demonstrates that it wasn't
a product of imagination but a deep premonition about the
future events.  Far reaching character of Karadzic's intuition, which has seen
the forthcoming tragedy of Sarajevo while the others, a mob, snoozed with
the illusions of "progress" and "brotherhood and unity", is well known 
and recognized.  However, no one has noticed that Dzemaludin Latic [considered to
be the ideologist of the main Bosnian Muslim party, Party for Democratic Action (SDA)]
has also expressed similar ideas.  In the poem <strong>Behar in Sarajevo</strong>,
published in the book <strong>Dom Davudov</strong> in 1989, Latic clearly
sensed the future developments:<P>
"I can't tell if you're more beautiful during the day or at night/
Sarajevo when the blossom covers you./  Suddenly, as if someone waved
a hand/ a wind blows and the flowers disappear.../  Like our lives."<P>

In the poem <strong>Sarajevo, sprzila te munja</strong> [Sarajevo may a
lightning destroy you], Dzemaludin Latic cursed the Sarajevo of "brotherhood 
and unity":<P>

"Cowards swears and curses:/  Sarajevo, may a lightning destroy you,/
and black crows mourn you!"<P>

In the eyes of foreign correspondents from Sarajevo who supply material for the western shapers
of the public opinion, Dzemaludin Latic is some sort of an Islamic Savonarola.
They dislike his condemnation of Western rubbish, drugs, pornography, prostitution
and promiscuity.  Reading those alarmist reports against the signs of Islam that
disturb the illusion about a secular, democratic and multicultural character
of Izetbegovic's authorities, we can easily surmise what sort of "democratic
values" these prophets of mondialism actually talk about.  Latic should be 
given credit for his loyalty to the basic tenets of the Islam which he 
reveals because of his devotion to the truth.  Those condemnations of Latic's
calls to loyalty to Islam demonstrate the final degree of secularisation 
of the Western civilisation whose advocates imagine that it is possible to
be a Muslim, a Christian or a Buddhist without any corresponding content and
obligations.<P>

Defaming Latic, western observers usually state, with outrage, his recognition
of the pathological nature of mixed marriages:  "Mixed marriages between Bosnian
muslims, Serbs and Croats, in itself a symbol of misunderstood common life,
are usually relationships condemned from the start; in them there are a lot of
conflicts and the children are frustrated because of their origin."  A cynic,
while reading aforementioned expressions of outrage because of Islamic condemnation
and intolerance of mixed marriages, like those described by the <em>International 
Herald Tribune</em> correspondent concerned for the future of the "Bosnian
multiethnic society", could laugh in the face of Washington advocates of 
the transformation of Bosnia to Muslimania.  The aforementioned mentors of
Islam should first learn about the basic tenets of Islam.  If they think that
one can be a Muslim and at the same time reject all formational principles
of <em>Koran</em>, they are very wrong.<P>

Latic's ideas are soundly based on <em>Koran</em> and are among the most
basic obligations of Muslims.  It isn't possible, nor imaginable, that Muslims
take from the <em>Koran</em> only those ideas which would agree with the will
of mondialists and reject the rest, above all the obligation for the struggle 
against the most monstrous order in the history of the world which is advocated
by the Washington free masons of European misery.  The inherent nature of 
<em>Qoran's</em> and every other religious message is that it doesn't allow partial
relationship with a believer: if one is a believer, he or she must follow and
respect everything that is in the holly book.  Otherwise, one leaves the religious 
community.  Besides, Latic only warns Muslims about their duty to follow 
<em>Quran</em>.  Those who ignore Latic's warning obviously do not have a right
to call themselves Muslim.<P>

While I'm thinking about Latic, I'm praying in my heart to the Serbian God
to assist his noble struggle on the Allah's way of the rebirth of Muslim
people.  Feelings of personal friendship and political enmity coincide in
my prayer. Before this war, anyone who had a will to see through illusions regarding
the future could have realized that the birth of Muslimania was certain
with only two unknowns: the time and its territory.  Today, we know
that Muslimania has been <em>de facto</em> established and that its territory
will be much smaller than the Islamists have expected.  Serbs have suffered a lot
in the hands of Muslims, but they did receive one good thing for which they
should be grateful: thanks to impatient and imprudent attack of Islamists
on power and the state of Bosnia's size, Serbs woke up from seventy years
of dreaming about "brotherhood and unity".  Some other, more sly Muslims
in power in Sarajevo would have kept Serbs in a semi-conscious state, and made
sure that it was too late for liberation when the Serbs woke up.<P>

It is much better to deal with real Islamists then with hidden and quasi
Muslims.  When the borders between the Republic of Srpska and Muslimania,
between Serbs and muslims, are finally established, then it will be possible
to form future political alliances against common enemies.  One should 
remember that today Islam is the largest and best prepared enemy of "the new 
world order".  The only exception on the map of world Islamic uprising
are the Bosnian muslims who are forced to serve Washington policy.
But that slavery will end with the war and final demarcation of the border.
Classical formula of politics says that the enemy of our enemy is our potential
friend.<P>

<hr>

translated on 9/19/96<P>
