<HEAD>
<TITLE>Mrkonjic Grad and Sipovo</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<FONT SIZE="+1">

<strong>date=3/12/96</strong><br>
<strong>title=bosnia / serbs return</strong><br> 
<strong>byline=doug roberts</strong><P>

<a NAME="VOA">Groups of Serb men</a> stand along the roadside in the heart of this 
market town, chatting and sipping small glasses of potent plum 
brandy.  For the moment there is little else for them to do and 
most readily acknowledge their feelings of depression at the 
devastation all around them.

Croatian forces stormed into Mrkonjic Grad and surrounding areas 
during the final stages of the Bosnian conflict last autumn -- 
and virtually the entire Serb population fled.  But at the Dayton
peace conference in november, it was agreed this region would 
revert to Serb control.

The croats eventually withdrew, handing over to British troops of
the IFOR peace-keeping force -- but  not  before an orgy of 
looting and burning that rivaled, or even surpassed, the 
devastation wrought in the former Serb districts of Sarajevo. 

Mounds of garbage line the streets outside scorched and 
window-less apartment blocks here.  British officers estimate  
more than half the homes in Mrkonjic Grad were partially or 
totally destroyed -- and the returning Serbs have found almost  
none  of the possessions they left behind when they fled the 
area. 

They began to return early last month -- only a handful at first,
to check on their homes and property.  But during the past few 
weeks the pace of the repatriation has steadily accelerated.  
British commanders estimate about 21-thousand Serbs have returned
to this region so far.  Hundreds are now arriving each day and 
many more are expected as soon as the winter snows melt. 

The United Nations refugee agency and private aid groups are 
providing the returnees with some basic supplies:  plastic 
sheeting, stoves and emergency rations.  But there is  no  
evidence yet of any significant reconstruction efforts -- and it 
is clear the civilian recovery program envisaged in the Dayton 
peace plan is lagging behind schedule.

For the time being, the task of restoring essential services in 
Mrkonjic Grad is largely in the hands of British combat 
engineers.  Water and electricity are now back on -- a field 
hospital was provided for the local population and two of the 
town's bakeries are back in operation. 

The British are being assisted by US army civilian affairs 
experts who are combing the region to assess the damage and 
determine what is needed to restore industrial and agricultural 
production to pre-war levels. 

To some, these operations might seem beyond the scope of IFOR's 
main tasks -- to separate the warring factions, provide security 
and ensure freedom of movement and to oversee the clearance of 
the minefields and the unexploded ordnance that litter the 
countryside.

But the British regional commander, brigadier Richard Dannatt, 
believes efforts to help the civilian population are entirely 
consistent with the broader objectives of the dayton agreement --
to ensure a degree of political, economic and social recovery 
that will make a return to war in bosnia unthinkable. 

<hr>

<a NAME="eltel">The Electronic Telegraph</a><br>
  Monday 18 March 1996<P>
  
<h2>Homes and jobs vital for lasting peace in Bosnia</h2><p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<h3>Robert Fox visits communities shattered by war and desperate for the chance to lead normal lives</h3><p>

 THE meagre fare in the market - a few trays of eggs, bottles of slivovitz, a crate or two of beer - is about the only sign of economic activity in Sipovo.<p>
 The Bosnian mountain village, with its predominantly Serb population of 6,000, was  on the line of advance as Croat and Muslim forces stormed through western Bosnia last September.<p>
 The Serbs fled, abandoned by their army, and, in the ensuing chaos, houses, schools, factories and hospitals were looted and burned.<p>
 Under the Dayton peace accord, the highland towns and villages round Sipovo and Mrkonjic Grad are to be handed back to the Serbs from Croat-Muslim control.<p>
 By next Tuesday, all transfers of territory under Dayton, of which this is by far the largest, have to be complete. From next Wednesday, the Bosnian Serbs will be allowed to station a limited number of army units on this area.<p>
 Since the beginning of February,  British troops of Ifor, the Nato-led peace implementation force, have been helping Serbs get back to their homes. Nearly 20,000 have returned out of a population of nearly 60,000 before war began nearly four years ago.<p>
 Most now face the task of turning this devastated wilderness back into something approaching normality.<p>
 "I really believe we will have peace now - I'll stay," said Nedela Kusman running one of the stalls. "The houses are burned and there is no food and no aid but we'll survive somehow." <p>
<p>
<h4>'I would really like to see the factory start up again as much as anything'</h4><p>
<p>
 Piled beside the houses are rotting clothing and broken furniture - items the looters rejected. Roads, power lines, water supply and telephones are destroyed.<p>
 To rebuild the villages round Sipovo could cost hundreds of millions of dollars, a sum unlikely to be forthcoming from the international community.<p>
 "One gets used to anything, I suppose, and we are trying to sort ourselves out here," said Milana Ilic, who worked as an engineer at the Trico clothes factory, which employed 7,500. Now it is stripped of its fittings, from the textile machinery to the doors and window frames.<p>
 "I would really like to see the factory start up again as much as anything," she said.<p>
 "I am going to stop here, and never move again. We want no more war here, and anyone is free to come back as far as we are concerned, provided they don't have blood on their hands.<p>
 "We just want to live in peace and quiet."<p>
 But she is doubtful about whether Dayton will deliver the peace she wants and is particularly worried about the complicated Bosnia-wide elections planned for later this year.<p>
 "Why are you so obsessed with elections? I don't care a damn who runs the municipality as long as we have enough to feed and clothe ourselves. I didn't vote last time because we've always had our leaders imposed on us, no matter who we vote for. It's a game of chess where the king and queen are pieces very far away."<p>
<p>
<h4>We're sleeping in a garage, and we'll stay on for a bit while we decide whether we can make a go of life here</h4><p>
<p>
 Down the road in the village of Jezero, not a house is inhabited. By the crossroads, scene of one of the key battles in the advance of the Muslims and Croats, every building is without roof, windows or doors. What the artillery and tanks did not destroy, the looters did afterwards.<p>
 The only two people in the place are Nejo and Jelena, a waiter and secretary in pre-war life. "We've just been digging for these potatoes, the only food we've had in the past five days," said Nejo.<p>
 "We hitch-hiked here from a refugee camp in Brcko. We fled just before the attack in September. We brought a little bit of food, but that ran out. We're sleeping in a garage, and we'll stay on for a bit while we decide whether we can make a go of life here, or give up and go away for good."<p>
 It is believed that several thousand Serbs who have returned over the past month have left again because of the lack of any means of support.<p>
 "The main point of effort now for Ifor forces must be the political, social and economic reconstruction of the country," said Brigadier Richard Dannett of the 4th British Armoured Brigade.<p>
 Apart from the problems of resettling Serbs, the brigadier senses rising  tension between the Muslims and Croats. Muslims are being shut out of some areas but in the next month the Muslim farmers will want to be back on their land for the spring sowing.<p>
 "This means we have only three weeks at most to get this sorted out, otherwise we could be in for real trouble," said Brig Dannett.<p>
<p>
