<HEAD>
<TITLE>Croatia in the British Media, Conclusion</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

used without permission, for "fair use" only<hr>
<font SIZE="+1">

<h1>Excerpts from: Croatia in the British Media, Part 5</h1>

<strong><em>by  Tom Frankovich</em></strong><P>

<h2> Hrvatski Obzor, Zagreb, Croatia, 10/16 1995</h2>

Chris Gunness is one of the U.N. officials most active in the attacks on Croatia.  Even a superficial observer can spot the significant difference in Gunness' attitude with respect to the operations of the Croatian army and to that of the Bosnian Serbs.  While during the operations "Flash" and "Storm" this U.N. spokesman was very active and harsh in his criticism of the Croatian authorities, during the Serb aggression on Zepa and Srebrenica he was hardly audible, and when he appeared in the media he was extremely mild with respect to the Serbs as can be seen from the following example.  On 7/12, Gunness stated the following for the BBC: "We don't have any reports that some people were taken.  The Serbs simply told us that they would check all captives and take out the suspected Bosnian Army members."  Similar statements by Chris Gunness are totally opposite to what he had said during the Croatian operation "Flash", when he fiercely accused the Croatian authorities of "violating the human rights of the people" by "forcing the military age man to stand in a line during the night," and because those men were later taken to collection centers.  Furthermore, his criticism of the Croatian authorities are often simply slanders, which are never backed up by firm evidence.<P>

The comparison of the TV material shot during the Serb aggression on Srebrenica and Zepa and during the operations of the Croatian Army which led to the liberation of the so-called krajina is interesting and telling.  While during the mass escape of the expelled people from Zepa and Srebrenica, the scenes shown of the TV screens in Britain were biblical scenes of a huge mass of desperate people (there were even a few shots of collection centers taken from a plane), during the escape of the Serbs from the so-called krajina, although the reports kept talking about more than 100,000 of people, the refugees were systematically shown close up, so that one could see about 10 vehicles at most.  The cameras were, of course, aimed mostly at the elderly and the pregnant women or the women with small children.  Never on the armed men which were withdrawing with them. Another interesting fact was that the news about the "fall" of Zepa were carried by the BBC two days before the actual fall of the town, and in spite of the denial by the Bosnian government, while the news about the military successes of the Croats and Bosniaks are broadcast with a delay of a day or two and some totally ignored.  For example, on June 13, a commercial TV station Channel 4, broadcast in its main news programme a report about the Croatian-Bosniak successes in capture of Jajce, Donji Vakuf and Drvar, while the BBC didn't even mention this news.<P>

Certainly, we should mention the series of articles by <a HREF="/info/students/marko/ref2.html#indep1">Robert Fisk</a>, published in <em>the Independent</em>, as weel as the articles of a former central European editor of that paper, now the correspondent from Bonn, <a HREF="/home/marko/public_html/craw.html">Steve Crawshaw</a>.  While Fisk, in a series of anti-Croatian articles regarding the operation "Storm", sent one of his articles, as was stated in the paper, from <a HREF="/home/marko/public_html/fisk1.html">"Lipovac, Serbia",</a> Crashaw called the Croatian liberation of the so-called krajina, "the rampage of Croatian <a HREF="/home/marko/public_html/craw.html#fascists">fascist</a>" and "ethnic cleansing"; he also accused president Tudman of spreading the ethnic hatred.  This is not surprising if one knows that Crawshaw has shown obvious enmity towards the Croatian president and that during the time when he had been the Eastern European editor in <em>the Independent</em> the critics of independent Croatia (Lovric and <a HREF="http://jefferson.village.virginia.edu/pmc/issue.595/review-1.595.html">Ugresic</a>) received the largest amount of space in that paper, unlike those who did not share that sort of opinion.<P>

In conclusion, let us mention that several recognizable aspects can be discerned in the reporting of the British media about Croatia and Croatians.  These are the political, historical, information-selective, and interpretational-linguistic aspects.<P>

The political aspect comes out of the official position of the British government which at times spills over into the media, either through 
informational briefings of foreign desk editors in the ministries of defense and foreign affairs, or through direct reactions of certain government officials in the press and their appearances on the Radio and TV.  The fundamental characteristics of this aspect are the claims that the main "culprit" in the breakup of Yugoslavia is Croatian secessionism, that the war in the former Yugoslavia is a "civil" war and not an expansionist war, that president Tudman's intention from the beginning of the war was to, in agreement with Milosevic, "divide" Bosnia, and the so-called "neutral" approach to the events in the Balkans.  The last characteristic is especially interesting.  Dating from Carrington's "neutral approach" to the so-called "warring parties", that diplomatic joke has been in the journalistic sphere totally perverted and taken to its absurd conclusion.  In this context, in stead of standing for objective reporting and siding with the truth, "neutrality" was distorted and for the majority of British journalists it stands for , above all, siding with one side for a while and than with the other.<P>

The historical aspect is visible in the invocation of Ustashe movement and the crimes against the Croatian Serbs in the WWII.  In that, British journalists use the data obtained directly from the Serbian propaganda.  For example, they persistently write about hundreds of thousands of victims at Jasenovac, while it is claimed that the checkerboard [Croatian coat of arms, also used by Croatian fascists during the WWII] and the Croatian currency are Ustashe [Croatian fascists] symbols.  The purpose of all this is to justify so called "legitimate fear" of the Serbs and their rebellion against the Croatian authorities.<P>  

The information-selective aspect is determined by the fact that at the beginning of "the yugoslav crisis" almost all correspondents were based in Belgrade.  However, even later, after some of them finally moved to Zagreb, they would continue to very rarely use the statements of the Croatian officials or use the official Croatian media sources.  Those who represent minority opinions (Puhovski, Lovric, Drakulic, Ugresic) and naturally, the representatives of the rebel Serbs, are significantly overrepresented in reporting and articles from Croatia.  In the later phases of the wars, this aspect can be seen in the selection of the reported news.  For example, earlier mentioned Serb claims about the "fall" of Zepa and Srebrenica and the delay or skipping of the news about the military success of the Croatian-Bosniak forces.  Besides, some news are recycled and repeated for a few days (incident in Stupni Dol [where allegedly Ivica Rajic, one of the men indicted by the tribunal in the Hague, led a Croatian militia unit in an attack in which 12 civilians were killed]).<P>

The interpretational-linguistic aspect in the most pronounced in the BBC news but can be also found in other media outlets.  The BBC thus, when Serbs are in question, consistently try to avoid the direct naming of the side responsible for a bombardment or an attack.  For example, they often use formulations of this sort: "Today, the Croatian capital, Zagreb, has been the victim of a rocket attack," or "Three persons died today in the center of Sarajevo as a consequence of an artillery attack," or "There has been fighting today near Velika Kladusa in western Bosnia."  Although in all three cases, the identity of attackers was well known they are deliberately not mentioned.  We mentioned earlier the case of the banishment of Croats from Fojnica, when they became unidentified "people" in a report.  More recently, reporters wrote that "Croatian forces claim that they have captured Jajce."<P>

The word "claim" implies the doubtful nature of a news item.  In parallel, in the same article, we can find that "the Serb report to the UNHCR states that between 45,000 and 50,000 people were evacuated or are fleeing toward Banja Luka.  The word "state" is neutral and does not question the truthfulness of a stated claim.<P>

All these aspects point out that one of the goals of such media approach to the wars in Southeastern Europe is definitely to spread the blame equally between the Serbs and Croats, to remove the distinction between a victim and an aggressor.  Once these distinctions are removed, both the war and with it all the crimes committed by the aggressor become more abstract and, as <em>Times'</em> diplomatic correspondent Eve-Ann Prentice said, "all sides become the victims of the war."  Thus, the goal is to transform the expansionist wars of the Serbs against the other Yugoslav peoples into some sort of a natural catastrophe for which no one is responsible, as if it were a flood or an earthquake.<P>

Without a doubt, that is the forging of history and avoidance of the truth.<P>

<hr>

Translated on 3/20/96<P>

