<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Srebrenica, second time</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
used without permission, for ``fair use" only
<hr>
<FONT SIZE="+1">

<h1> Are There Any Pressures on Citizens of Serb Nationality?</h1><p>

 
<h2><i> by Sinan Alic<br>  Front Slobode, 8/15/95, Tuzla, Bosnia-Hercegovina</i></h2><p>


<hr>
<h2)Silence is a Sign of Approval</h2><p>

The words of the Bosnian Army commander, General Rasim Delic, said in the Parliament, were encouraging; he announced an inspection of the troops of the 28th division, which was performed soon after;  he also talked about the Army measures against anarchy in the ranks.  For the uninformed, the troops mentioned in Gen. Delic's speech were the members of the Bosnian army who fought their way through the Bosnian Serb lines after the fall of Srebrenica; they were mostly transferred to the administrative territory of the Tuzla-Podrinje canton.<p>

However, in the period between the inspection, i.e. the total control of the troops which came from the surrounded Srebrenica, we encountered armed groups who roamed through the counties and municipalities in the Tuzla-Podrinje canton, solving their accommodation problem by force of arms.  On the receiving end was mostly the population of Serb nationality.  One person was murdered and frightened people found shelter with their neighbors, Muslims and Croats.<p> 

<h2>Why Silence?</h2><p>

Although we are yet to be given official data or hear a beginning of a discussion of this problem, we must ask a question: wasn't it possible to predict the behavior of the people coming out of a several year long siege?<p>

The silence of all political parties is typical; the cases we encountered in the recent past announce that retribution as a form of deviant behavior is knocking on our door.  If it enters, no-one will be happier than the shepherd from Savnik [Karadzic] and the mad General from Kalinovik [Mladic].<p>

We should raise this topic publicly, not to hide the unbelievable tragedy of Srebrenica, and then of Zepa, but to keep a legal and lawful state organization and avoid a trap: to respond to crimes with equal measure.<p>

<h2>Beaten up and Paralyzed Women</h2><p>

According to the reports - true still not complete - at disposal of the Serb Citizen Council [SGV- Srpsko Gradansko Vijece] of the Tuzla-Podrinje canton, more than 100 cases of violent assaults on the property of the citizens of Serb nationality and the citizens themselves have been registered so far.  besides one murder in the presence of three Policemen from Srebrenik in the village of Jasenica, tens of citizens were beaten up.  A majority of incidents occured on the territory of the Tuzla municipality in the villages of Simin Han, Crno Blato, Srednja Dragunja...<p>

The facts are merciless and we must not close our eyes in front of them: Vidosava Polemis was beaten up, thrown out of her house and the house looted.  Luka Polemis, Mila Pantic, Mirko Lazic, Bozidar Pantic and Drago Rajic shared her destiny, the difference being that their houses were also demolished.  While this happened in Simin Han, the same scenario was repeated in the village of Srednja Dragunja: Bozica and Mico Miljic, Jovo and Mitra Miljic, Mara and Ilija Maksimovic, Gospava, Petra and Vasilije Vasiljevic were beaten up and forcibly expelled from their houses.<p>

Among the families thrown out of their houses is a Croat family.  Out of three beaten women, 2 remain paralyzed; an attempt to set a Serb house on fire has also  been recorded, while a Croat house was torched.<p>

<h2>Who is Alija Konjanik [Horseman]?</h2><p>

The village of Crno Blato is a special story.  Pressures on the local Serb population here date from the beginning of the aggression of Bosnia-Hercegovina and the arrival of first refugees.  The most aggressive of them is a certain Alija, known better as Konjanik [Horseman], a refugee from the village of Sapna, near Zvornik [town in eastern Bosnia].  After the arrival of the latest refugee wave from Srebrenica, eleven forced expulsions and one robbery were recorded in Crno Blato.  One wonders if that would have been the end of it if the police had not intervened on time.<p>

In the middle of July it was especially tense in the territory of the Srebreni county, about 40 km from Tuzla, in boroughs of Jasenica, Tinja and Spionica.  Chaos was spreading progressively.  Refugees who moved to this territory in 1992 and 1993 were guiding the new arrivals, directing them to the Serb farms and houses.  Mistreatment and expulsions from houses were registered in seventeen cases (that many were reported to the Serb Citizen Council).  Terrified by the assault of armed men who were out of control, the inhabitants of these villages found shelter with their friends in the cities of Tuzla, Lukavac and Mramor.<p>

The territory of the Zivinice county also had its share of dangerous events.  In the village of Vrhojevici, ten families were forced out of their houses in the period between 19 and 21 July and eight of them were robbed; the attackers usually demanded money.  Similar events took place in the villages of Dunjevici, Podgajevi and in Zivinice itself, 23 cases in total.<p>

<h2>Culprits in Uniform</h2><p>

It is interesting that, although determined to protect law and order in this country, the mayor of Zivinice did not succeed in that.  He was helpless in his attempts to return people into their homes, only because the culprits were the members of the Bosnian army.  The culprits were the soldiers of the 28th Division whose inspection had been announced and then performed by Army General Rasim Delic.  We should expect that we'll find the culprits in another line-up, in front of the face of justice.  Of course, every generalization is dangerous.  They know that in Zivinice, where they emphasized that there had been no problems with the unit whose commander was Zulfo Pusilovic; however, they openly said that one of the culprits and the leader in forced expulsions of the citizens of Serb nationality was a well known boxer Kabasi, also a member of the Bosnian army.<p>

Because of all that, the inspection of the 28th division is an encouraging event.  Although we were attacked and some of our compatriots were exposed to beastly torture, a law and order must rule in the state of Bosnia-Hercegovina.<p>

Especially in its Army.<p>

<hr>

Translated on 9/1/95

