<HEAD>
<TITLE>Serbs Everywhere</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
used without permission, for "fair use" only<P><hr>

<FONT SIZE="+1">
<h1>Nebojsa from "Globus" in Knin</h1>

<h3> Hrvatski Obzor, Zagreb, Croatia, 2/26/96</h3>

Ninoslav Pavic used to be the most fierce persecutor of Croatian patriotism and Croatian "nationalists" on the pages of <em>Vjesnik</em> [Once the most respected Croatian daily.  During the communists, and again today, under the state control].  He was copiously and too often quoted and used in the Belgrade [former Yugoslav capital; Serbian capital as well] press.  Had he then, some seven-eight years ago, sent journalist Nebojsa Taraba to write a news report about Knin, the readership would have "enjoyed" in a parade of brotherhood and unity which would in the near future express itself as the worst Chetnik ideology.[Note: brotherhood and unity was an official policy in the former, "communist", Yugoslavia under which all expressions of nationalist or patriotic feeling were deemed dangerous and frequently prosecuted.  The policy of brotherhood and unity also tried, half-heartedly, to develop a feeling of common Yugoslav patriotism].<P>

The times have changed. What about the people? Once the public informer for greater Serbianism on the pages of <em>Vjesnik</em>, Ninoslav Pavic, was a man who would in the (these days rather faded) media memory be remembered as the most reckless public informer, whose texts could have been literally copied by the communist prosecutors in their persecution of "nationalists". He is today the majority shareholder and the ideologist of a "national weekly", loudly and professionally advertised <em>Globus</em>.  Ninoslav Pavic is a man who has made a fortune from the Croatian suffering and the lies about the Croatian suffering.<P>

Today, in a former <em>Vjesnik's</em> building, top officials from all newly established and "transformed" [i.e. privatized] companies regularly come to kowtow to Pavic.  They say that a certain Zagreb prophet foretold a horrible suicide for him...  But forget about prophets.<P>

Let us instead read what Pavic's journalist, Nebojsa Taraba, wrote in the last issue of <em>Globus</em> about Knin [the former capital of the so-called Serbian Krajina; it was liberated and thoroughly looted in the August of 1995.  Since most of its Serb population fled in front of the liberators, the town remains mostly deserted]: "Almost six months after the liberation, Croatian royal city of Knin, as the politicians and a few journalists often used to call it, neither with its image nor contents cannot justify such an elevated ephitet."<P>

Obviously, for Taraba, a historical fact, that is the royal Knin, is such because certain "politicians and a few journalists" say so!  Once he is done with cynicism and historical lies in the introduction, Taraba proceeds to turn the liberation of Knin into a looting expedition;  he finds the evidence for this in the piles of old furniture which had been thrown out on the streets by the people who had broken into somebody else's apartments and had brought in the stolen furniture from other apartments.  To the worst possible picture of the conditions in Knin, Taraba adds bizarre details which show that "those who today live in Knin have never lived in larger towns." For example, <em>Globus'</em> reporters in Knin, the town which, according to them, had been populated by highly urbanized Serbs, in telephone booths found   "prepaid telephone cards with plenty of impulses left on them."  Taraba concludes: "It seems that even the most banal things like a phone, are an unbelievable novelty to these people."  In short: Croatian barbarians had thrown out civilized Serbs out of Knin.  The same civilized Serbs who ,only a few yards away from those telephone booths, in their hospital-prison cellars, mutilated and killed Croatian prisoners.  They did this in criminal fits powered by impulses which they had known to orderly utilize the same way as the telephone impulses in telephone booths.<P>

Those criminal urges were for years strengthened by the former <em>Vjesnik</em> executor and the current owner of the "national weekly", Ninoslav Pavic and other communist <em>nebojsas</em> [a Serb name].<P>


<hr>

Translated on 3/10/96<P>

