We present a protocol that efficiently allocates resources in a communication
network among voice and data users.  The proposed protocol gains efficiency
over methods with separate channels for voice and data
by taking advantage of idle periods in the voice activity.  An exponential
on-off voice activity model is used to determine the performance
of distributive or centrally controlled systems.
In addition, communication systems considered in this work can use either Code
Division Multiple Access (CDMA) or Time Division Multiple Access (TDMA)
as the underlying multiple access technique.  In either case, the protocol
is a valid mechanism for integrating voice and data in a multiple access
channel.  Comparisons are made between mathematical analyses using
a Markov model of the servers and simulation results using a communication
network simulation tool.  Results for both CDMA and TDMA systems are
presented.

</DOC>
