<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Bosnian Casualties</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

used without permission, for "fair use" only
<hr>

<h1>Half of Bosnia Without an Address</h1>
<FONT SIZE="+1">
<h2><em>by Prof. Dr. Ilijas Bosnjovic</em>, Oslobodenje (European Weekly Edition), Sarajevo, Bosnia-Hercegovina, 8/24-31/95</h2>

Relatively long period of peace after the WWWII was beneficial for the population development in Bosnia-Hercegovina.  The population has grown from 2,564,308 in 1948 to 4,377,033 in 1991, or by 71 percent.  In the former Yugoslavia, only Macedonia has recorded a larger growth (76 percent), while the other republics had a significantly smaller growth: Croatia 26%, Slovenia 37%, Serbia without provinces [of Kosovo and Vojvodina] 38%.  Large population migrations, the largest in the former Yugoslavia, are also characteristic of Bosnia-Hercegovina.  Until 1991 the number of emigrants was larger than the number of immigrants by 1,712,488 inhabitants.<P>

<h2>Peasants Became Workers</h2>

...<P>

The industrialization and other socio-economic changes in the period after the WWII have determined the mode of population development in Bosnia-Hercegovina:  the process of the so-called demographic transition has been started; in this process, the natural population growth is reduced, the population ages with time and, after a while, begins to decrease in number; in other words it begins to die out.  Although the population of Bosnia-Hercegovina has partly preserved its vitality until 1991, the signs of demographic transition were even then clearly noticeable, as in the whole of population as well as in the three major ethnic groups individually.  This process has to a largest extent engulfed Serbs, then Croats and then Bosniacs.<P>


<h2>2.5 Millions of Refugees</h2>

The 1992 war has caused great demographic disturbances in Bosnia-Hercegovina.  The normal population development was interrupted and all trends in that development were deformed.  Since the end of June 1995, over 2.5 million people have left their permanent residence; in other words they have been forced to migrate.  Out of that number a little bit less than 1.3 millions of persons have sought refuge abroad (refugees) and the rest have found temporary accommodation within Bosnia-Hercegovina (displaced persons).  These demographic disturbances are differently distributed among the different ethnic groups in Bosnia.  43.2 percent of the total, or 540,000 persons were Bosniacs, 31.2 percent, or 390,000 were Serbs and 17.8 percent or 222,000 were Croats while 7.8 percent or 97,000 were the Yugoslavs or people from other ethnic groups.  The breakdown of numbers of displaced persons according to their ethnicity is as follows:  Bosniacs 702,000 or 54 percent, Serbs 340,000 or 26.2 percent, Croats 1555,000 or 11.9 percent and Yugoslavs and others 103,000 or 7.8 percent.  In addition, the direct and indirect demographic losses due to the war amount to 352,000 persons. Out of that number, 279,000 were killed, died during the war or are missing, 15,000 were added due to the increase in mortality [with respect to the prewar levels] and 58,000 can be ascribed to the reduction in the number of births.  Bosniacs make up more than a half of total war losses, or 9.4 percent of their population before the war.  Serb losses are 32.5 percent of the total losses, or 8.3 percent of the Serb population before the war.  Croats constitute 10.9 percent of total losses which corresponds to 5 percent of the Croat population.  Yugoslavs and people from other ethnic groups make up the rest: 5.3 percent of total losses which corresponds to 5.4 percent of their prewar population.<P>

<h2>Vitality of the Bosniac Population</h2> 

Out of three major ethnic groups in Bosnia-Hercegovina, Bosniacs had the greatest demographic losses during the war and take up the largest proportion of displaced persons.  Their participation in the losses and forced migrations is significantly larger then the percentage of the Bosniac population at the beginning of the war [according to the census taken in 1991, Muslims (Bosniacs in this article) were 44 percent of the total population, Serbs 31 percent, Croats 17 percent and Yugoslavs and others 8 percent of the total population].  However, this population has preserved its demographic vitality.  This can be seen from the fact that Bosniacs account for 56 percent of the wartime births on the whole territory of Bosnia-Hercegovina.  Likewise, their share of the number of children younger then 14 is also large (57 percent).  This is a so-called children demographic foundation on which both the reproductive capacity and the development potential of the population is based.<P>

The changes mentioned above occured before the end of June, 1995.  Since then, war events have further influenced the demographic situation in Bosnia.  Approximately 40,000 persons were expelled from Srebrenica and Zepa and the fate of another 8 to 10 thousands is still unknown.  Ranks of expelled and missing Bosniacs have been increased by that number.  Forced expulsions of Bosniacs and Croatians from the Banja Luka area still go on (about 50,000 people).  On the other side, 115,000 to 200,000 Krajina Serbs have fled Croatia.  On their way to Serbia a part of this population will stay for a longer or shorter time on the territory of Bosnia-Hercegovina outside the control of the [Muslim-Croat] Federation.  Whether some of these people will permanently settle in that part of Bosnia-Hercegovina, it is hard to predict, since they have a tendency to migrate to Serbia.  However, the measures whose goal is to keep the military capable men in Bosnia have been implemented.  It is possible to make an estimate of the largest possible number of man in that population: between 17 and 19 years of age, 2,500 to 3000, 20 to 39 years of age, 22,000 to 29,000 and 40 to 50 years of age, 7 to 9 thousands, which adds up to 31,500 to 41,000 men.  We can only guess what proportion of that number will stay in Bosnia or join the military service.<P>

<h2>Demographic Amputation</h2>

If we consider the situation after this war in its totality, the demographic future of Bosnia-Hercegovina is uncertain.  Even without war destruction, the demographic transition [aging] of the Bosnian population presented a problem in itself.  It is a sickness of the whole demographic tissue and we can only be fought in peace.  In Bosnia-Hercegovina, the countermeasures must consist of well planned and decisive actions based on coordinated efforts of all Bosniacs, Serbs and Croats.  In your circumstances this is the only way for each one of the three major ethnic groups to avoid depopulation and extinction, which to a smaller or larger extent threaten all of them, although this threat would become reality earlier for some of them and later for others.<P>

Besides grave consequences of the war which were discussed above, the amputation of particular parts of the united demographic body has been carried out.  In that situation, the destructive influence of demographic transition [aging] has a clear way and their malignant influence is stronger, especially in the environment in which the loss of reproductive capabilities has already started.  The connection of the problem of demographic transition [aging]  with economic, urban, social and ethnic factors in Bosnia-Hercegovina, will make any separate [ethnic] population policy ineffective.  Those policies would have an absurd goal: to revitalize amputated parts of a united demographic body!  Because of these reasons it is only possible to talk about a global population policy in Bosnia-Hercegovina.  It would aim at all ethnic groups in Bosnia and its main goal would be to reverse the negative results of the war and than to stop the depopulation in the cases where the reproductive biological potential has been reduced to the critical limit; finally, it would aim to harmonize the further demographic development of Bosniacs, Croats and Serbs.<P>


<hr>

Translated on 2/11/96<P>
</FONT>
