<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Croatian Authorities and the Hague Tribunal</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
used without permission, for "fair use" only<hr>

<FONT SIZE="+1">
<h1>Defenseless Defense</h1>

<strong><em>by Kresimir Meler</em></strong><P>

<h2>Oslobodenje-Svijet, Sarajevo-Ljubljana, Bosnia-Hercegovina, 4/11/96</h2>

Tihomir Blaskic has arrived to the Hague.  With his arrival, after several 
months of haggling, the question whether the Croatian authorities will 
fulfill their obligations with respect to the international community and
extradite Croatian citizens indicted for war crimes to the Hague tribunal
for war crimes committed on the territory of the former Yugoslavia has been
only partially resolved.<P>

The problems began when the Croatian authorities received from the Hague 
a rather unpleasant letter.  It contained a very detailed indictment against
the seven most influential members of HV(O) [HV stands for Croatian Army, 
while HVO stands for Croatian Defense Council, Bosnian Croat militia], and 
Croatian Democratic Union (HDZ) of Bosnia-Hercegovina.<P>

The accusations, as we have found out, were very serious.  Tihomir Blaskic
was indicted because of the failure to prevent war crimes against the Muslim
village of Ahmici in the Lasva valley.  Both the Croatian authorities and 
the authorities of the so called Herceg-Bosna reacted very promptly.
At the beginning they expressed surprise "that the indictment against Blaskic 
and another six Bosnian Croats [has been] sent to Zagreb, since it is well known
that Croatia has nothing to do with him as he resides in Bosnia-Hercegovina 
at the moment".  Even the Croatian president got involved.  Seemingly bitter,
he kept stating that "Blaskic and company couldn't have committed war crimes 
since they were simply defending their homes and that Croatia, even if it wanted,
cannot deliver the accused to the Tribunal in the Hague since they are not
at the moment on the Croatian territory."<P>

<strong>Hypocritical statements</strong>:  Public appearances of other top
officials from the ruling party [in Croatia] followed the president's statement.
The president of the Croatian Supreme Court reached the summit of hypocrisy
when he stated: "In a defensive war it is impossible to commit war crimes.
We are talking about self defense, and self defense can never be a crime."<P>

It would have been fine if the Croatian authorities stopped after these strange
statements.  Unfortunately they went a step further.  Perhaps exalted
 with Blaskic's activities in Bosnia, the Croatian president pulled him from his
 position at the time in the (para)sate in "which he had no influence", and 
 appointed him to the position of the chief inspector of the Croatian Army.
 In addition to that, the Ministry of Defense awarded to Blaskic and Dario 
 Kordic (who had also been indicted for the crimes in the Lasva valley), perhaps
 as a reward, apartments in newly built buildings in Vukovar avenue, almost
 across the street from the Ministry of Internal Affairs [Police].  And while
 Croatia hasn't even considered extradition of Blaskic to the Hague, pro-government
 papers were raising a lot of noise because FR Yugoslavia was persistently refusing to 
 extradite its war criminals.  With open malice, the papers commented that
 "Milosevic is afraid to extradite the war criminals because their testimonies
 could result in his indictment."<P>

 Serbia was accused of hiding and, furthermore, celebrating war criminals; 
 the proof for that was the former major and today colonel Veselin Sljivicanin.
In that, the commentators "forgot" some tidbits: Croatia, not Serbia, was the first
one to call its criminals "heroes" and "fighters for national rights".
Tihomir Blaskic had been promoted before Sljivicanin, and unlike Sljivicanin,
Blaskic also received the protection.  Finally, Sljivicanin has been after Vukovar
on a relatively insignificant position, unlike Blaskic.  Even when Sljivicanin was 
transfered to Belgrade, he was given a new job at the Military Academy, which
is not a high position in the military hierarchy, regardless of the flashy
title of the principal.<P>

<strong>Inappropriate comparisons</strong>: in the meantime, as slowly as possible
and after numerous sharp rebukes from president Clinton, Warren Christopher and 
"traditional Croatian friends" from Germany, Croatian government began to work on the
so called constitutional law which was supposed to enable extradition of Blaskic to
the International Tribunal.  Of course, the authorities did not forget, not even 
for moment, to quote in the media under control of HDZ the statements of the
high officials of the Tribunal such as the one that "FR Yugoslavia is a criminal
state since it is refusing to extradite war criminals."<P>

It turned out that the truth is a relative notion for the government-controlled
media in Croatia.  Still the most interesting events were to follow: the constitutional
law regarding the cooperation of Croatia with the International Tribunal came
in front of the representatives in the Croatian Parliament. On the first day 
of the debate one of the representatives made an inappropriate comparison:
"To accuse Blaskic for war crimes is that same as accusing New York Police 
Department chief because on a particular night a certain number of murders occur
in Bronx!"  This comparison might stand if that police chief, as was the case
with Blaskic, was commanding those who had committed crimes and was responsible
for their actions.<P>

Then, Vice Vukojevic, the president of the legal committee in the Croatian 
parliament, demanded that "the lower house of the Parliament postpone 
the debate about the proposed Constitutional law until the Statute of
the International Tribunal for the war crimes in the territory of the former
Yugoslavia since 1991 and the tribunal's rules regarding the evidence and 
procedure are modified.  This request, which has been submitted by the 
Croatian government, concerns the modification of the rules according to which
the tribunal can only sentence the accused to those sentences existing
in the law of the states in which territory the crimes had been committed."
Brought to its absurd conclusion, this demand is equivalent to post-war
Germany demanding that it decide about the rules and procedures of the
Nurnberg tribunal in 1945.  It is questionable how much this would be in
the interest of Blaskic and company, since Bosnian laws prescribe harsher
punishment for war crimes, including death penalty.  It was also 
mentioned that "neither the UN charter, nor the Statute of the International
tribunal for War Crimes define who is an aggressor and what is a war crime;
and that is a very elastic category notion."  This is a blatant stupidity
since all that was defined at the Geneva Conference before World War II.<P>

<strong>Meticulous "treatment"</strong>: The statement of the Minister
of Justice, Miroslav Separovic, from the time when both 
Blaskic and Kordic had had apartments in Zagreb for a while and Blaskic 
was the chief inspector in the Croatian army demonstrates the extent 
of the cynicism of the  Croatian authorities: "I don't know where 
Blaskic and Kordic are at the moment, but I know that both of them
have legal representatives."  By the way, his ministry has found the defense
attorneys for both of them and has been paying the attorneys as well as
covering the cost of  Blaskic's defense from conditional freedom, which
amount to DM 230,000 per month.  If we add Separevic's endless wonder that
the international community "demands from Croatia, as well as from Serbia,
to extradite war criminals, although Croatia was a victim," the Croatian
authorities idea of the rule of law becomes even murkier.  Especially since
Blaskic is for a while a Croatian citizen and then he isn't.<P>

Finally, only a few days before Blaskic's departure to the Hague (supposedly
voluntary) which (by chance?) happened after the American Defense Secretary
William Perry's visit to Croatia, Croatian president attempted one more time
to blackmail the international community.  Without blinking he stated that
"the remaining accused are not in the Croatian territory but in Herceg-Bosna.
The resolution of their problem will depend on the solution of the problem
of others who took part in war clashes, both Serbs and Muslims."<P>

If the other statesmen behave in the same manner (why would they give up
"their" men while Tudman keeps his?) the justice will not prevail.  It
is exceptionally cynical that Tudman doesn't recognize the existence of 
the Federation in practice and claims for the people walking in front 
of his eyes that they are somewhere else.  Of all that, the most interesting
fact is that Croatia, in spite of promises that it will cooperate with the
tribunal, does everything in order not to extradite those Croats
most responsible for the crimes or to extradite them after a detailed 
"treatment".<P>

Do Croatian leaders adore international scandals, or are they afraid that 
a lot of dangerous evidence will surface in the Hague?<P>
<hr>

Translated on 6/7/96<P>
</FONT>
<hr>
<a HREF="/info/students/marko/musbos.html"><IMG SRC="/info/students/marko/
pictures/home.gif" ALT="HOME" WIDTH=80 HIGHT=40></a>
<hr>
</BODY>
