<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Why is Michael Steiner Ashamed for Sarajevo?</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
used without permission, for "fair use" only<hr>
<FONT SIZE="+1">

<h1>What is Steiner Ashamed of?</h1>

<h2>Oslobodenje-Svijet, Sarajevo-Ljubljana, Bosnia-Hercegovina, 6/27/96</h2>

Last week, deputy high representative of the international 
community in Bosnia-Hercegovina, ambassador Michael Steiner,  harshly criticized the authorities
in Sarajevo bringing up the alleged violations of the human rights
of Serbs who had remained in the reintegrated parts of the city.
The interview, which Steiner gave to journalist Amra Kebo and which was published
in two parts in <em>Oslobodenje</em> [daily], provoked strong reactions and
initiated discussions about this "hot" topic.<P>

We decided to reprint parts of that interview together with the reactions from
prominent Sarajevo politicians.<P>

Steiner started the interview with these words: I am ashamed for Sarajevo. 
I am personally ashamed because I have promised to the Sarajevans of Serb
nationality, doctors for example, that they would be able to keep their jobs.
I saw, however, that two weeks after the transfer of authority [from the
Republic of Srpska to the Federation] in Ilidza, a pediatrician to whom I promised
that he would be able to keep his job, was fired.  The events which are taking 
place in the parts of the city which have been transferred under the Federation 
jurisdiction are shameful for this city.  I wonder why President Izetbegovic
doesn't say something about these events.  Where is that pride of multiethnic
Sarajevans?  No one has been able to explain to me why it was impossible to
protect 8,000 Serbs who remained in Sarajevo from criminals.  
Every day we are informed about <a HREF="/info/students/marko/AIM/aim01.html">attacks on Serb owned property and houses</a>; 
everyone knows about this and no one can claim
that the police can not stop this.<P>

Really, I wonder why Reis-ul-ulema Mustafa Effendy Ceric [head of Bosnian
Muslims], who consistently speaks about the return of refugees, and who
demands the implementation of the right to return, doesn't raise his voice
against such a situation?  The towns of Ilidza, Ilijas and Vogosca 
 have since the transfer of authority been filled with refugees
who had begun to create parallel local authorities, to enter Serb houses and
expropriate Serb property; the refugees decide how many rooms Serbs need
and move in the rest of the house.  Every night windows of Serb houses are
smashed, houses are constantly looted...  Victimized Serbs go to police, report
the theft, the police files a report and nothing happens.  Please, don't
tell me that the city which managed to defend itself for three years from
Karadzic's troops cannot protect 8,000 people.<P>

What I don't understand is that at the beginning of the war demonstrations
for the multiethnic life in Bosnia took place in Sarajevo.  Why aren't there
demonstrations today?<P>

<strong>You mean, the demonstrations which took place immediately before
the criminal Serb attack on the city?</strong><P>

Yes, those demonstrations.  Then, the whole city stood up against those
who were against the multiethnic life in the city.  The situation today is
very close to ethnic engineering.<P>

No one can claim ignorance.  All reports are regularly sent to the government
officials.  President is silent about this, reis as well, there are no 
demonstrations by those who had always supported that Sarajevo spirit of
multiethnicity and common living.  Instead, 8,000 Serbs, who stayed in the city
despite tremendous propaganda by [the Bosnian Serb authorities in] Pale,
are scared to death and are beginning to leave the city.  What then?  I am
ashamed for this city, ashamed for my work.<P>

<strong>Can you comment the incident on Kobilja Glava where some Bosniaks
were sowing a field which had previously been cleared of mines.  When they came a 
month later to check their crop one of them lost a leg!  The whole field
was again mined.  Who did that?</strong><P>

I don't see how these events are related?  I often hear from people that
they support multiethnic Sarajevo.  However, the situation is exactly the
opposite.  The suburbs are full of refugees and no one is willing to take
responsibility for their moving in.  But they are there and are exacting
revenge on the local Serbs because of their previous suffering.  The 
consequence is that this society is moving towards a monoethnic society.<P>

No one can accuse me of trying to hide the situation in the Republic of Srpska.
However, it is difficult to defend the rights of Bosniaks who are calling
for the right of return throughout the country, if in
the capital, day after day, we can witness the implementation
 of the policy which is exactly the opposite of that proclaimed as a goal
 for the rest of the country.<P>

<strong>Former Chetniks, who bombarded this city, who tortured these people
in the camps, and who are still at the same positions are free to enter this city.
We have the same situation as after W.W.II, where victims can see their torturers
at large.  How do you explain that?</strong><P>

We can discuss that.  Still we can not approve the current policy.  Constantly
we encounter the situation in which crimes are justified by previous crimes.
But that's not the point.  The question here is whether you want a city which
will be the capital of the whole country.  If you do, then you should behave
accordingly.  I think that this is irresponsible and shameful.<P>

<strong>Have you discussed this problem with some of the officials</strong><P>

Of course.  I have spoken to president Izetbegovic, Prime Minister Muratovic,
Police Minister Hebib.  All of them agree that this is not right.  But the
looting and attacks have gone on for months.  If there were political will
to stop the crime, it would have been done by now.  What happened with the
solidarity of those multiethnic Sarajevans?  I've seen those terrified Serbs, who
don't deserve what is happening to them.  They are not the victims of Sarajevans.
The city is full of refugees who intend to stay here.  They come to a city, are not 
accustomed to live in a multiethnic society and believe that, because they
are refugees, they have all the rights and the Serbs, although they are Sarajevans,
don't have any rights.  With that sort of policy, you are directly encouraging
separation and division.  Regardless whether it is organized or not, the situation
in Sarajevo is ethnic engineering.<P>

UN-international police is writing reports and delivering them to the local
police.  The local police say that they have problems and that they are doing 
all they can.  I don't believe that.  It's been going on for too long.(...)<P>

<strong>At the last session of the Common Civilian Commission you proposed the
text of the principles for the protection of property.  There is also a working
committee for the complaints in that area?</strong><P>

We must start from the point that the laws in Srpska and the federation are
blatantly braking the Dayton agreement.  Both sides agreed that those laws
must be modified.  Both entities must submit draft laws to the working committee
by July 7, since the next session of the Common Civilian Commission will take
place on July 9.<P>

We proposed several measures: suspension of present laws until the new ones are
enacted.  The decision to do this was made in Geneva in March.  But nothing has
been done until now; ombudsmen have in the mean time received more than 8,000
complaints related to the violations of the ownership of apartments
and houses in the Federation only.<P>

I must say that the fact that these laws still exist casts a shadow on the
intentions of the politicians, here in the Federation too,  regarding the 
return of refugees.  If the present Federation laws are implemented, the
return of refugees to Sarajevo is de facto impossible;  this automatically
damages your credibility when you demand the return of refugees to other
territories.  It is extremely important, especially here in Sarajevo, to
extend the brief period of two weeks during which the refugees are supposed
to return, if they do not want to loose their homes, to the end of the year.<P>

I believe that an absolutely unacceptable and short-sighted election season calculations
are behind all this.  I am concerned that those who obstruct the enactment of such
laws are exactly those who wish to prevent the return of refugees.<P>

Unfortunately, in the Republic of Srpska the situation is much worse, since
there the law about property also must be modified.<P>

<hr><P>

A day after the interview was published, <em>Oslobodenje</em> [daily] carried
several reactions which were recorded by our journalist Borka Rudic.<P>

<strong>Zlatko Maric</strong> (Social Democratic Party of Bosnia-Hercegovina):
"We in SDPBH on several occasions talked to the Serbs from reintegrated
territories.  They also initiated contact, so that we are aware of the situation,"
says Maric, emphasising that he and his party support every action whose goal
is to prevent incidents.  According to Maric, provocations and maltreatment of 
people have decreased lately because of more effective police action.  "Refugees
from Srebrenica and Zepa, who are moving to reintegrated parts of Sarajevo
are behind these undesirable events.  I believe that the reason is that they
have a hard time adjusting to the urban environment and that these incidents
will disappear with time."<P>

<strong>Stjepan Kljuic</strong> (member of the Bosnian Presidency and the
President of the Republican Party): "I took Steiner's interview as an action
of a tried friend of Bosnia and a jurist who should be trusted.  I think that
finally everyone understands that some of our legal authorities
are consciously working against the Dayton Agreement," says Kljuic, adding
that a coup d'etat took place in Sarajevo when the legal city council was dismissed
and the city turned into a canton which doesn't reflect the ethnic structure 
of the local population.<P>

"If on the territory under the control of legal [Bosnian] authorities we
subvert the Republic [of Bosnia-Hercegovina] and the [Muslim-Croat] Federation,
then one shouldn't be surprised by events which take place in various para-states,"
says Kljuic.  He added that as the citizen of Sarajevo he felt especially 
responsible for everything that took place in Sarajevo and that he would,
as the president of the Republican Party, demand the resignation of the
cantonal authorities and the local police command.<P>

<strong>Rajko Zivkovic</strong> (vice-president of the Serb Civic Council):
"When we gave credit to the Federal police immediately after the transition 
of authority, the situation was really satisfactory and there were no big 
problems.  Unfortunately, later the situation became worse although we
contacted the highest officials in Bosnia-Hercegovina (President Izetbegovic, 
[Police] Minister Hebib and others) demanding protection," says Zivkovic.
He thinks that the problems in the reintegrated territories must be viewed
from three points of view, especially regarding the responsibility for the
exodus and suffering of Sarajevo Serbs.  According to Zivkovic, the highest 
responsibility lies with the [Bosnian Serb] regime in Pale which forced the
majority of Serbs to leave their homes, to burn and destroy everything that
could be destroyed.  The second level of responsibility falls on the authorities 
in Sarajevo which failed to timely enact the amnesty law and used every occasion
to state that all but those who served in the Bosnian Serb Army were welcome to stay.
International Community is the third culprit.  They, according to Zivkovic, 
chose to react now when hardly anything can be done, while they failed to
prevent arson, looting and violence...  "Present incidents, somehow seem natural,
having in mind that the refugees from the Serb entity have moved into these
areas," says Zivkovic.<P>

<strong>Kresimir Zubak</strong> (Federation president): He refused to comment
the aforementioned interview adding that he had had bad experiences with 
journalists.<P>

<strong>Ejup Ganic</strong> (Federation vice-president): He was prepared to 
talk to us, but only at the time when this issue was supposed to be in the press.<P>

<strong>Mirsad Ceman</strong> (secretary general of the Party for Democratic
Action [SDA, the largest Bosnian Muslim party]): he stated that Steiner's
interview was very biased and considered only the consequences while failing to
mention the causes.  "Bildt and Steiner should have done much more during the 
phase when we pleaded with the Serbs to stay in Sarajevo, when we almost begged
the international factors to prevent the looting of factories and burning
of houses of those same Serbs who are now complaining that they have nowhere to
return to.  Of course, SDA does not condone attacks on people and their property
and will renew the demand for their full protection."<P>

Ceman said that he would suggest to Steiner to do more for the rights of Bosniaks
and to try to return them to their homes, from which Karadzic and others had
expelled them.  To the question whether the police could have done more to
protect the citizens, Ceman responded that he did not know, but that the police
should have done all that it could.  He added that he didn't know the number of 
actual incidents and that it was impossible to post a policeman in front of
every house.  Ceman was certain that refugees hadn't taken part in the incidents
and added that they were not settled in those areas in order to provoke clashes and 
incidents.  "I thinks that it is humane to settle people in empty houses,
if only for a few months.  SDA never supported resettlement of refugees because
of ethnic homogenisation but in order to help those people," concluded Ceman.<P> 

<strong>Sefkija Okeric</strong> (city hall president) was not prepared to comment
Steiner's interview.<P>

<strong>Avdo Hebib</strong> (Minister of Internal Affairs [Police]): "Despite
trying to get in touch with him for several hours," writes <em>Oslobodenje</em>
journalist Borka Rudic, "we were unable to obtain his opinion."<P>


